ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016


CHAPTER 1: INTRODUCTION‌‌


Welcome to ONESOURCE Income Tax, a powerful system that gives you an integrated and complete tax management solution for your corporate needs. Its comprehensive tax compliance capabilities automate federal and state tax compliance processes for your corporate returns.


THIS GUIDE‌

If you are new to ONESOURCE Income Tax, this guide helps you become familiar with the system and your initial setup tasks. If you are an experienced user, this guide provides you with information about advanced features such as consolidations, batch processing, and using the Enterprise Control Panel, as well as information about new features added this year.


WHAT DO YOU WANT TO DO?

  • Starting ONESOURCE Income Tax. Learn how to make sure your browser meets the requirements to run the software.

  • Touring the Home Window. Become familiar with the program.

  • Federal Charts. Begin using the software by setting up your system charts.

  • Tax Accounting System. Learn how to use each item in this system. We added or changed several items this year. (See Process Options and Action Items.)

  • State Charts. Learn how to set up the state part of your system with K-1 Partnership importing, State A&A Workpapers, and State TI Workpapers.

  • Federal Tax Accounting System. Learn how to import balances, make adjustments, enter Schedule M-3 data, run reports, compute, and set options.

  • Organizer. Become familiar with Organizer menus and where to enter information.

  • Consolidations. Learn how to set up the system for federal and state consolidations.

  • Printing. Learn how to print TAS reports and returns in Organizer.

  • Tools. Learn how to use the powerful tools in the system like the new batch processing, rollover, and the Enterprise Control Panel to save you time and make your job easier.

  • ONESOURCE Tools. Learn how to use items which are related to integration processes.

  • System Tools (Security) Shows how to setup the system security, groups, and users, if you are an administrator user. If you are not an administrator user, this guide shows you how to create and change your password and explains the security for the software.

  • Integration. Learn how ONESOURCE Income Tax data can be shared with other ONESOURCE products.


    OTHER RESOURCES‌


    ONLINE HELP

    Open the online Help system and look for the information you need.

  • Use the table of contents. Select Help | Contents. Navigate through the books and pages for the information you need. You can print any topic.

  • Use the index. Select Help | Index. Enter a word to find a list of topics which contain that word.

  • Use the search feature. Enter one or more key words and click Search. Links to topics containing that keyword are listed below.


    CUSTOMER SUPPORT CENTER

  • Browse the online support web site for tips, release notes, and other information. www.tax.thomsonreuters.com.

  • Call 1-800-327-8829 or visit us on the web at https://onesource.thomsonreuters.com.


    ADDITIONAL USER GUIDES

    For more information about the features in our software, please refer to the following user guides:

  • Administrator’s Guide

  • User Administration User Guide

  • Business Return E-Filing Guides

  • Excel Add-in User Guide

CHAPTER 2: SIGNING IN‌‌


SIGNING IN TO ONESOURCE INCOME TAX‌‌

You must first complete the registration process for your Universal ID.

To open ONESOURCE Income Tax, complete the registration process for your Universal ID and make sure the settings on your Internet browser allow you to access all the components of the software.

There are two platforms this year, ONESOURCE 2014 and ONESOURCE 2016.


ONESOURCE 2014


ONESOURCE 2016


Sign in to the ONESOURCE 2016 platform to open all your applications. Some applications can open in the new platform and some do not. If your application is not upgraded yet, the system will redirect you to ONESOURCE 2014.


SIGN IN‌

  1. Open Internet Explorer.

     You can use any browser for ONESOURCE 2016, however, ONESOURCE Income Tax requires you to use IE 11.

  2. Enter https://www.onesourcetax.com to use the ONESOURCE 2016 sign in screen.


    • If you use a browser that does not meet the system requirements for ONESOURCE 2016, you will see the following message.



  3. Enter https://www.onesourcelogin.com to use ONESOURCE 2014.



    Enter your User ID and Password


    Click View browser requirements

    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



  4. Click View browser requirements on the ONESOURCE 2014 sign in screen to ensure that your browser meets the product requirements.



  5. In the Browser Requirements table, if your browser needs any adjustments, you will see a No in the

    Enabled column.

  6. Click the link next to the item to update the component.

  7. When you are finished updating, click Sign in to return to the Sign in screen.

  8. Enter your Universal ID and Password.

  9. The first time you log in, a security message also appears, asking if you wish to install and run the ActiveX Control.

  10. Select Install ActiveX Control to install the various add-ons. You may need to repeat this step several times until you have installed all add-ons.

  11. After the add-ons are installed, the ONESOURCE platform appears.

Thomson Reuters provides minimum operating guidelines to process tax returns. The System Requirements document contains information available as of October 2016 to use for the 2016 and 2017 tax season planning. Refer to the Customer Center Support web site to review and print a complete list of all the system requirements for both ONESOURCE 2016 and ONESOURCE 2014 (ONESOURCE Income Tax System Requirements.)

 There are slight differences in the system requirements for each platform. Please download each one to verify your system meets the requirements.

  • We do not support IE Enterprise Mode and the software will not run correctly.

  • Microsoft Edge is not supported.

LEARNING ABOUT ONESOURCE 2014 AND ONESOURCE 2016‌‌

With the new and advanced ONESOURCE platform, you can do things that you could not do before. The new ONESOURCE platform supports multiple browsers and devices. You can easily jump from one ONESOURCE application to another within your ONESOURCE suite and still view data across ONESOURCE applications with multiple browser windows. Additionally, you can view your most recent work across all ONESOURCE applications or create tasks as you go through your tax processes. All of these features are available in the new and improved ONESOURCE platform.

The platform is the initial screen for the product. From here, Administrators can complete various system setup tasks and open products you have licensed or purchased.

This year, in addition to the new platform, we have added a new module, User Administration. The User Administration module standardizes the process of adding and editing users and groups, and managing permissions across all ONESOURCE products.

Some of the functions and products are in transition between the previous platform (ONESOURCE v2014) and the new platform (ONESOURCE 2016). This means the setup process and launching products sometimes involves using both platforms.

The types of tasks you can perform are also dependent upon your Administrator permissions. There are three levels of administrators, Full Access, Product-Specific Full Access, and Product-Specific.

For step-by-step instructions on Administrator tasks, please download and refer to the User Administration Guide on the Customer Center website.

MY TO-DO

We added the ability to associate a deep-dive link from a To-Do to a specific location in ONESOURCE 2016. You can set up links when you initially create the To-Do or later when an existing To-Do is added, edited, or deleted.

The "My To-Do" feature lets you create a personal reminder of something you want to do. Previously, this feature allowed you to create the "To-Do" by providing a description and add an optional due date.

Now, when you are working in a ONESOURCE 2016 application:

  1. On the top global menu bar, select Add To-Do.

  2. Enter the To-Do text.

  3. Select the link icon and select Add link to current screen.

  4. Enter a due date, if applicable.

  5. Click Add to save the To-Do. This creates a link to the current screen. If, prior to saving the To-Do, you edit or remove the link,

  1. Navigate to the desired location,

  2. Select Replace with link to current screen or Remove link.

  3. Click Add to save the changes.

Likewise, you can edit or remove a link on an existing To-Do.

"We added the ability to deep-dive from a To-Do by selecting the link icon and navigating to its targeted location in ONESOURCE 2016.

When viewing My To-Do, click the link icon on a specific To-Do and the application takes you to the linked location.

 Links only function when an application has ONESOURCE 2016 functionality.

CHAPTER 3: USER ADMINISTRATION‌‌


Controlling access to ONESOURCE Income Tax, means identifying and setting up different types of users, groups, and assigning permissions. In this chapter, you will learn about the permission hierarchy, types of users and administrator users, and how to use the new User Administrator module to add users and assign permissions to those users.


PERMISSIONS‌

In ONESOURCE Income Tax, new users have no permissions until an administrator assigns them to users. Permissions are comprised of two parts, an action and an object.

  • Examples of actions are Compute or Edit.

  • Examples of objects are a Chart of Accounts or a Binder.

    An example of a permission is (the ability) to Create Federal COAs. Other variations on this permission would be abilities to 1) Delete Federal COAs, 2) Edit Federal COAs.


    EXPLICIT OR INHERITED PERMISSIONS

    Permissions can be explicit or inherited.

  • Explicit permissions are those permissions that are directly granted or denied for a specific object or class of objects.

  • Inherited permissions are the result of permissions granted or denied at a different level such as permissions you have as the member of a group. The explicit permissions granted to that user group will be inherited by the individual users who are members of that group.

    How does ONESOURCE Income Tax determine Permissions?

    User permissions (i.e., what the user can see and do) to access a given object are determined by examining the permissions assigned to them by the administrator and the permissions inherited by belonging to a particular group. Group permissions do not automatically update an individual user. The group permissions are maintained independently of its members.

    The following is an overview of the permission hierarchy.


    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



    OBJECT-LEVEL OR USER-LEVEL PERMISSIONS

  • Object-level permissions allow the system administrator to assign or deny specific users access to specific objects (a workarea, a particular binder or chart, etc.) in the application.

  • User-level permissions allow the system administrator to assign a specific user certain permissions to classes of objects (all workareas, all binders, all federal charts of accounts, etc.)


    BASIC STEPS FOR ASSIGNING PERMISSIONS

    1. Assign specific permissions to groups.

    2. Assign users to a group. Define the (global) permissions for each User or User Group. If users were not assigned to a user group previously, then you can make the assignments by Editing User Groups or Editing Users. As soon as a user is added to the group, the user has the same global permissions as every other user in the user group.

    3. Enable or restrict permissions at the object level.

    4. Edit global permissions. Global permissions to edit federal or state entities and binders must be assigned so the user can submit electronically filed returns.

    5. Assign Federal and State e-Filing Rights.

    6. Assign users to those groups.


      TYPES OF ADMINISTRATOR USERS

      There are several basic types of users to define access and authority:



      FULL ACCESS

      PRODUCT SPECIFIC FULL ACCESS

      PRODUCT SPECIFIC

      Creates other Full Access Administrators

      X

      PERMISSION TYPES‌

      Full access and product specific administrators can be very specific about user permissions.


      BASE LEVEL - USER PERMISSIONS

      • They can give you access to all the binders in a company or just one binder.

      • If you have direct permissions for an object, then it does not matter if any of your groups have permissions for that object.

      • The rights assigned to you control access to objects.


        SECOND LEVEL - GROUP PERMISSIONS

      • If you have permissions to an object, but the group does not, your direct permissions give you access to the object, while other members in the group may not have access.

      • Group permissions supplement individual permissions, but cannot remove direct permissions assigned to you.


        THIRD LEVEL - OBJECT PERMISSIONS

      • The full access or product specific administrator can assign or remove your permissions to access a specific database object (i.e. all Chart of Accounts).

      • These permissions are inherited for each object that is a member of that class.

      • If you do not have the appropriate permissions, you will not see certain enhancements and software features in the product.

    ASSIGNING E-FILING RIGHTS

    Full access and product specific administrators can assign permissions to view, submit, and electronically file returns. They can assign permissions to file both federal and state electronic returns or just federal or just state. You must have global permissions to edit federal and/or state entities and binders.



    RIGHTS TO ASSIGN

    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



    The following items apply when granting these rights and permissions:

  • Only administrators with e-filing permissions can assign e-filing permissions.

  • All other users, including administrative users, must have e-filing permissions specifically assigned to them and they will only have those assigned rights.

  • Users must also be assigned global permissions to edit federal or state entities and binders to submit electronically filed returns.


    NEW USER ADMINISTRATION‌

    In the past, setting up users and groups has been managed in both the ONESOURCE platform and the income tax product. This year, you will complete all of these tasks in the ONESOURCE platform in the new User Administration module. Using the new User Administration module is easy. All tasks are now completed in the module.


    Complete the following tasks in the User Administration module:

  • Adding, deleting, updating users and groups

  • Assign rights and permissions to users and groups

  • Importing and exporting user and group information

  • View and print user details and group details

  • Printing reports.


    ABOUT USER ADMINISTRATION

    The following applies when using this module. Administrators and Assigning Permissions You must have rights to give rights.

    An Administrator can only give users and groups permissions that are equal to their own permissions or below.

    Example: If an Administrator only has View rights for groups, they cannot give Edit or Add rights to other users or groups.

    Example: If an Administrator has access permissions to General Ledger Manager, they can only grant the same permissions or less to General Ledger Manager.

    This not only applies to User Administration related permissions, but also other product related permissions.


    Custom Settings System Messages

    When you assign a user specific permissions for a product at the User Permissions level, the system highlights the permission in pink and displays a message, This User has Custom Settings.

    The permissions that flow to a user from a group are not highlighted in pink.


  • Permission check boxes remain highlighted even if the permission is disabled within User Permissions.

  • For accounts enabled with Client Manager, the message bar appears when you select a Client that has custom settings and disappears if you select a Client that does not have custom settings.

  • Custom settings do not apply to group permissions.


USER ADMINISTRATION SCREENS‌

Once you open User Administration, you will see a new and improved user interface. The Users list is the opening screen and the default for the module.


  1. Tabs

    User Administration has four tabs. Each tab changes the screen and the menu bar.

    • Users - Create, add, edit, assign permissions, import, and export users.

    • Groups - Create, add, edit, and assign permissions.

    • Reports - Create and print User Administration reports.

    • Notification Queue - Shows the status of imports and import messages.

  2. Menu Bar

    The menu bar appears below the tabs on all User Administration screens. The screen and menu items change depending on the tab you select.

    • Add - Opens Add New User or Add New Group.

    • Import - Import user details, locations, and group assignments to update information.

    • Export - Export a template file to add multiple users or groups or export user details, locations, or group assignments.

    • Refresh - Updates the page.

  3. User List

    This is a list of all the available users.

  4. Shared User Column

    This column identifies users granted access to the database through another account.

  5. Groups Column

    This column identifies the groups this user is a member of.

USER PERMISSIONS FOR INCOME TAX USERS

The User Permissions screen shows the permission options for this user. The Administrator selects each application to add or remove permissions for a user. The following sections describe the selections for each area or application.



Green Dot Indicator

The green dot indicator in the left menu next to the product name, denotes that a user or group has permissions for that product. It appears when you assign permissions to a user for a product.

In addition, when you have a Client Manager enabled account, the green dot appears when you assign a client for a product. Green dots mean there are users or groups that have permissions for those products.



 If all permissions for a product are removed for a user, the green dot still appears to indicate permissions for the user are removed.

 If all permissions for a product for a group are removed, the green dot disappears in both the group as well as the users in that group.

    • Assigning permissions at the Entity level enables that action for the specific entity and corresponding binders.

    • Assigning permissions at the Binder level will only enable that specific action for that specific binder.


      1. Assign permissions at the Workarea level.

      2. Assign permissions at the Entity level.

      3. Assign permissions at the Binder level.

  3. In the Choose File to Upload, select the appropriate file on your computer.

  4. You can view the status of imported files on the Notification Queue screen. Here you can search and sort imported files. The total number of import files with IN PROGRESS and ERROR status is reflected in the header.


  5. Click the Status column to see a breakdown of the results for a specific file. If errors exist, click Download Error File.

    • In Progress - Import file was successfully uploaded and is being processed.

    • Errors - Errors were encountered during the import process. The error count on the left of the status indicates the total number of errors in the import file. Click the download image to download the file.

    • Complete - All rows were successfully processed.

    • Failed - A system error occurred during the import process. Import the file again. If you continue to receive this message, contact Support.


ERROR FILE

The Error File contains information from the original import file as well as an Error column that lists the items to correct.



  1. Use the Lists tab to assist you with correcting the import errors.

  2. Navigate through each tab and verify you have addressed all errors and made all necessary corrections.

  3. Save the error file as a new import file and then import it again.


THREE TYPES OF ADMINISTRATORS‌‌

There are three levels of administrators, Full Access, Product-Specific Full Access, and Product-Specific.


FULL ACCESS ADMINISTRATORS

Full Access Administrators can assign all permissions for all ONESOURCE products they have licenses to use.

  1. Select Full Access to create this type of administrator user. When you select Full Access, all other check boxes are selected by default.

  2. Click Done.



PRODUCT SPECIFIC FULL ACCESS ADMINISTRATORS

Product specific Full Access Administrators have rights to assign all permissions for a selected ONESOURCE product. These administrators automatically inherit permissions to View, Add, and Edit User Administration groups, as well as, to assign new and existing permissions for selected products.

  1. Select Full Access, next to the product(s) this user is authorized to access to create this type of administrator user.

    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



  2. Click Done.



PRODUCT SPECIFIC ADMINISTRATORS

Product specific Administrators have rights to assign permissions for ONESOURCE products they use.

1 To create this type of administrator user:

  • do not select the Full Access check box.

  • in the Administrator Role section, select Admin for the specific applications that you have license to use.

  • in the Access Rights section and select the corresponding rights for this administrator.

    TESTING COMMUNICATIONS USING CONFIGUREPROXY.EXE‌

    If you get an error message, Communication session initialization failed when opening Organizer for the first time, you must complete the following steps to enable the Use proxy server setting.

    1. Open Windows Explorer and navigate to C:\Program Files\RIA

    2. Open the folder for the most recent tax year. For example, the 2016 folder appears as INRS2016.

    3. Locate the configureproxy.exe file.

    4. Double-click the file to launch the TTA Client Proxy Configuration.


      ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



    5. Do not make any changes and click Save.

    6. In the Target IP Address field, enter 164.57.152.206.

    7. Click the Test Settings button.

    8. If you receive the Success message, you do not have to do anything else.



    9. Click OK to close the message.

    10. Click Exit to close TTA Client Proxy Configuration.

    11. If you receive the Failed! message, click OK to close the message.


    12. On the TTA Client Proxy Configuration screen, check the Use Proxy Server box.

    13. Click Save.

    14. In the Target IP Address field, enter 164.57.152.206.

    15. Click the Test Settings button.

    16. If you receive the Success message, you do not have to do anything else.

    17. Click OK and then click Exit to close TTA Client Proxy Configuration.

    18. If you get the Failed! message again, please contact ONESOURCE System Support at (800) 327-8829, prompts 3-7-1 for further assistance.


    ASSIGNING READ ONLY PERMISSIONS TO AN OBJECT

    Full access and product specific administrators can assign an object (Binder or Chart) as Read Only. This prevents all further changes to data, properties, or permissions for that object. Marking a binder Read Only overrides any permissions specifically granted to users or user groups. An administrator can also remove the Read Only setting from a specific binder.

     If it is removed, permissions return to their previous settings.

    1. Open the appropriate Workarea, Group, Entity, or Chart.

    2. Select a binder or chart.

    3. Select the Read Only check box to mark the binder or chart as Read Only.

    4. Click Update.

    5. A screen appears informing you that the update is complete.

    6. Click OK.

CHAPTER 5: SETTING UP‌‌


SETTING UP OVERVIEW‌‌

The setup process begins with creating charts of Tax Combination Codes (TCCs), Charts of Accounts (COA), and Charts of Adjustments.

Once you create charts, then you will set up entities and binders and assign charts to them. If you choose the Tree View display option, all the items appear in a navigation tree structure. The navigation tree organizes everything in a hierarchy format.

The levels of the tree are described below:


AREA

DESCRIPTION

Workarea

Store all entities and binders for an Organization. Multiple Workareas can be created but usually one workarea is created for the entire Organization. The creation of multiple workareas depends on an organization’s structure and should be decided during implementation.

Groups

Home Group – the default group containing all entities under that workarea.

User Defined Groups – groups entities and binders by user defined preference (i.e. Consolidation groups, State Groups, etc.). The actual entities and binders within each user defined group will reside in the Home Group and shortcuts will be created in the user-defined groups.

Entities

User defined organizations that are assigned specific return types. (Parent, Subsidiary, Partnership, Consolidation, etc.). Each entity will have associated binders, which are separated into year folders.

Binders

Annual tax returns for the associated entity. Charts are assigned on a individual basis when first creating a binder.


WORKAREAS‌‌

Use Workareas to organize your desktop. A Workarea stores all the entities and binders for an organization or group of companies.



CREATING A NEW WORKAREA

  1. On the My Binders screen, on the menu bar after Workarea, select Add Workarea.

  2. Enter the name you want to assign to the new Workarea.

  3. Click Save.

    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



    Creating Multiple Workareas

    Repeat the process above to create multiple workareas. Multiple Workareas are typically created for the following scenarios:

    • Multiple office locations using the same ONESOURCE Income Tax account. Multiple workareas allows you to have different security options for each Workarea.

    • Organizing entity types such as 1065, 1120, foreign entities.


ENTITIES‌‌

An entity represents a corporation (legal entity), branch, division, or operating location that designates the level where financial information is maintained in the organizational structure. Information is entered, analyzed, and adjusted at the entity level. An entity contains information the system uses when you create a tax binder such as, company name, company number, and FEIN.

Separate company returns, tax calculations, and reports can be generated at the entity level. Information at the entity level can be consolidated for consolidation and combined reporting purposes.

Entities are represented graphically with different icons representing each type of entity.


ENTITY

Subsidiary

Select Entities on the Income Tax menu bar for entity tasks.



ADDING ENTITIES

  1. On the Entities menu bar, select Add Entity.



  2. Enter the Entity Information.

  3. In the Return Information section, select the Entity Type from the drop-down list:

    • 1065 - Partnership

    • 1120 - U.S. Corporation

    • 1120F - Foreign Corporation

    • 1120L - Life Insurance Company

    • 1120PC - Property and Casualty Insurance Company

    • 1120REIT - Real Estate Investment Trust

    • 1120RIC - Regulated Investment Company

    • 1120S - S Corporation

  4. Select the Return Type from the drop-down list.

    • 1120, 1120L, and 1120PC are the only valid return types for international processing.

  5. Select an International Filing type, if one applies.

    • Foreign Tax Credit - Domestic entities with foreign source income or foreign operations. This is the only option for Top Consolidation entities.

      ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



    • Foreign Entity - Foreign corporations, controlled foreign corporations, foreign partnerships, and branches of foreign corporations.

       Selecting an entity’s filing type is permanent.

  6. Select the Source of Data for the Tax Return.

  7. Select the Level of Consolidation/Elimination, if applicable.

     For international entities, complete the Company Information. The company number is required when you want to batch import or process international returns.

  8. In the Fiscal Year section, select the beginning and ending date for the entity.

  9. In the Incorporation section, select the Date of Incorporation and the State.

  10. Click Save.


EDITING ENTITIES

  1. To change entity information, select the entity.

  2. Click the Properties icon.

  3. To rename an entity, select the entity.

  4. On the left menu, select Rename.

  5. Enter the new name.

 Users are charged for every created binder. Deleted binders and entities still count as purchased binders.


BINDERS‌‌

Binders represent year-specific data particular to an entity. All binders for the same entity use data from a common database. You can set up tax binders according to the year required for a particular entity. The software uses the year to invoke the appropriate data entry dialog boxes, workpapers, and computations for that binder.

 If you do not assign a chart to a binder when you create it, you may add a chart at a later date.

The My Binders screen is the opening and default for the application.




ADDING BINDERS

  1. On the My Binders screen, click Add Binder.




  2. Select the tax Year from the drop-down list.

  3. Select the Entity where you wish to add this binder.

  4. Click Create.

  5. The Binder Properties screen has a variety of pages where you will enter information about this binder. The information is dependent upon the type of binder you are adding for this Entity.



     We recommend that you check the information for each of these tabs. Once you assign charts to a binder, you cannot change them.

  6. Select each tab and enter or select the appropriate information.

      translation gain/loss account at the Federal Chart of Accounts level, the entity level, the binder level, and inside the binders under options.

    • If you change the options set at the chart level, currently existing entities must be updated to reflect the changes. If you change the options set at the entity level, currently existing binders must be updated to reflect the changes.

    • The advantage to setting the options at the federal chart level is that any entity that you create based on the chart will default to the federal chart options. Should you make changes to options at the federal chart level, previously created entities and binders must be updated to reflect the change. New binders based on the chart will automatically reflect the changes.

  3. Select Clear Filter and the Home screen will appear as it was initially.

SORT‌‌


When the My Binders screen is in the List view, you can sort all the columns by selecting the filter icon at the top of each column. You can sort by Entity, Year, Binder, Workarea, Entity Type, Return Type and International Type (if applicable.)


CHAPTER 6: BATCH PROCESSING‌‌


The Batch menu is located on the Income Tax menu bar. Batch processing saves time and allows you to perform common tasks for multiple binders.

On the Income Tax menu bar, select Batch.



BATCH: BINDER GROUP‌‌

Creating Binder Groups is the first step on the batch process screens.

  1. Select Batch | Binder Group.

  2. Select the appropriate binder group or click New to create a new binder group.

  3. On the Batch Create Binder Group screen, enter a Group Name.



  4. To locate binders to add to the new Binder Group select:

    • Workarea

      ONESOURCE 2016



    • Return Type (Income Tax or Partnership)

  5. Click Load.

  6. The available binders for your selected criteria appear in the left pane.

  7. Select the binders for the group you are creating and click Add.

  8. The binders appear in the Selected Binders pane.

  9. When you are finished selecting binders, click Save. This returns you to the first Batch screen.

  10. Click Next to continue the batch process.


EDITING, COPYING, OR DELETING A BINDER GROUP

  1. On the Income Tax menu bar, select Batch | Binder Group | 1 Choose binder group.

  2. Select the Binder Group you want to revise and click Edit.

  3. The selected group name will already be in the Group Name field.

  4. To change the Binder Group name, enter the new name in the Group Name field.

  5. Select the Workarea, and Return Type, then click Load.

  6. Select Available Binders and click Add to add binders.

  7. In the right Selected Binders pane, click the check box next to the binder(s) you want to remove from the group and click Remove.

  8. Click Save.

  9. To copy a Binder Group, select the binder group you want to copy, then click Copy. The binder group copy will appear in the Binder Group column, underneath the group you copied and have “Copy” at the end of the binder group name.

  10. To change the name of the binder group, click Edit and follow the steps above.

  11. To delete a Binder Group, select the binder group from the list, then click Delete.


BATCH: CHOOSE ACTIVITY‌‌

The second screen in the batch processes function gives you a list a processes and workpapers which you can perform with the selected binder group.


  1. On the Batch screen, select a Binder Group, then click Next.

  2. The Choose activity screen has two columns of activities you can select, Batch Operation and Launch Workpaper. Batch processes which cannot be performed with the selected group, will not be active.


  3. Select from one of the following batch operations:


BATCH OPERATION


DESCRIPTION


HOW TO:

Compute

Compute nonconsolidated binders.

Check the box to update historical balances. Click Start Batch Compute.

Import

Import data into the group of binders.

See “Batch: Import” on page 72.

Rollover

Rollover nonconsolidated binders to the next time period.

You can check the option to roll the chart assignments with the binders.

Click Start Batch Rollover.

Copy

Create copies of the binders.

  1. Enter a new binder name.

  2. Select the data you want to copy.

  3. Click Start Batch Copy.

Create PDF file for foreign entities.

Selecting Print creates a PDF for the foreign entities in the Binder Group.

Process Options

Edit process options.


State Options

Edit state options.


State TI and Payments

Opens the columnar workpaper.


Federal Adjustments

Opens the Federal Adjustment Workpaper.



BATCH: SET OPTIONS‌‌

The Set Options screen on the Batch menu is the third screen.

  1. Check the box if you want to Refresh Historical balances from prior year related binders when you batch compute the binders in the selected binder group.



  2. Click Start Batch Compute.

ONESOURCE 2016



BATCH: MONITOR STATUS‌‌

The fourth screen in the batch process is Monitor batch status.

  1. After you initiate a batch compute, rollover, copy or print, this screen appears or you can also select this step to check the status of a previously run batch process.

  2. The Compute status displays first.


    Compute Rollover Copy Print


  3. Select the appropriate tab, Compute, Rollover, Copy, Print, to display the status of the process.

  4. Select the Year from the drop-down list.

  5. A list of Binder Groups of the latest batch process, by submitter, and their status display in the Binder Group pane. Print displays all the print batches for 30 days. Refer to the International User Guide for more information.


BATCH: COPY BINDERS‌‌

The Batch Binder Copy function allows you to copy multiple binders together without individually copying binders for each entity.

  1. On the Batch, Choose binder group screen, select a Binder Group, then click Next.

  2. On the Choose activity screen, click Copy.



  3. Select the data to copy.

  4. Enter a new binder name.

  5. Click Start Batch Copy.


BATCH: IMPORT‌‌

Batch importing is a practical timesaver you can use to import preliminary balances for multiple types of data or multiple binders from a single import file. Each import file must contain a company number, account number, and account balance column.

 The company number must match the entered company number on the Properties of the entity. Account numbers must also match the accounts listed in the Chart of Accounts.

ONESOURCE 2016



TYPES OF BATCH IMPORTING

There are several types of batch importing performed within ONESOURCE Income Tax:

  • Batch importing multiple types of data into a single binder.

  • Batch importing multiple types of data into multiple binders.

  • Batch importing a single type of data into multiple binders.


    BALANCES YOU CAN IMPORT

    The following balances can be batch imported using ONESOURCE Income Tax:

  • Preliminary Balances

  • Adjustment Amounts

  • Schedule M-2 Detail

  • Schedule M-3 Detail

  • Exchange Rates by Account

  • State Apportionment Factor Data

  • State TI Modifications and Apportioned Income Adjustments

  • State TI State Tax Expense

  • Tax Payments

  • 1120L Workpaper Data

  • 1120L Prior Year DAC Data

  • International Data

We recommend formatting each import file using the same required columns that are used in an individual binder import to perform batch imports of multiple data files (balances, adjustments, etc.).

 Only an additional required column, Company Number, is added to the import file.


IMPORTING A SINGLE OR MULTIPLE TYPE OF DATA INTO MULTIPLE BINDERS

  1. On the Batch screen, select a Binder Group, then click Next.

  2. On the Choose activity screen, click Import.

  3. Click the Domestic tab and select appropriate options from the drop-down lists.

  4. Click Browse to select the batch file to import. Use the drop-down menu to select a previously imported file.

  5. Click New to create a template that identifies the batch import file to the system. (Refer to “Creating a Batch import template for State Taxable Income” on page 379.)

  6. Use the drop-down menu to select a previously created template. Define the import template.

  7. Repeat the two steps above for all applicable items to import for this batch.

  8. Click Import. If the import is successful, no errors will appear at the bottom of the screen.

  9. Click Error Log to review any issues.

  10. Click Cancel to exit the Import screen.


BATCH BINDER CREATE‌

The Batch Binder Create function allows you to create multiple binders (income tax or partnership) together without individually creating binders for each entity.

  1. On the top menu bar, select Batch.

  2. Select Binder Create.




  3. Select the Workarea, Year, and Binder Type from the drop-down list; and if applicable, Time Period.

    Creating binder types depends on product installations and licenses on the server for the selected tax year.

  4. Enter a binder name for the new binders.

  5. Click Search. Available entities appear in the Available Entities window for the selected workarea.

  6. Check all applicable entities in the Available Entities window and click Add.

  7. Select the Related Binder tab details (related prior year/period binders etc.).

  8. Click Create. If you enter the binder name, that name is applied to every binder.

  9. Click Close.


PERFORMING A BATCH COMPUTE

  1. On the Batch, Choose binder group screen, select a Binder Group, then click Next.

  2. On the Choose activity screen, select Compute.

  3. On the Set Options screen, check the box if you want to Refresh Historical balances from prior year related binders when you batch compute the binders for the selected binder group.

  4. The 4 Monitor Batch Status screen opens or you can return to this screen later to review the batch compute status.

ONESOURCE 2016


EFILE‌‌

Electronic Filing on the Batch menu lets you perform electronic filing for groups of returns. Likewise, Electronic Filing Status lets you check the status of electronically filed returns.



ELECTRONIC FILING STATUS‌‌

Once the return is electronically filed, Thomson Tax & Accounting receives an acknowledgment from the IRS and other taxing authorities that the return was filed. There are two methods for viewing the status of your returns to track their progress: Electronic Filing Status or Binder Properties.


USING ELECTRONIC FILING STATUS

  1. On the top menu bar, select Batch.

  2. Select EFile | E-file Status.




  3. On the E-file Status screen, select the tax year from the drop-down list. The system generates a report on the screen.

  4. When you access the report for the first time, the system populates it with the current year returns that have electronic filing XMLs. Use the year drop-down list at the top, to select a different year and/or use the sort/ filter features at each column headers to customize the report. The system maintains all your settings by default.

  5. You can use the following features to display the information you want to see:

    • Click Export to download the information to an Excel file.

    • Click the Refresh button to update status, dates, and time on the report.


EMAIL NOTIFICATION

You can receive e-mail notifications regarding the status of e-filed returns through the Email Notification enrollment screen.

  1. On the Income Tax menu bar, select Batch | EFile | E-filing Status.

  2. On the E-Filing Status menu bar, select Email Notification. Enrollment is User ID specific.

  3. Toggle Enable Notification so it is activated. Toggle the button again to disable notification.


  4. Enter a valid e-mail address. This is required.

  5. Select all or specific status and jurisdictions to receive notifications.

    • You must select at least one status and one jurisdiction.

    • You will receive an e-mail whenever the status of an e-filed return is updated.

  6. Click Save.

Users which have been suspended, unauthorized, or deleted in Income Tax are automatically removed from the e- mail list.


DISABLING EMAIL NOTIFICATION

  1. On the Electronic Filing Status screen at the bottom, uncheck Email Notification.

  2. Click Save.

Users which have been suspended, unauthorized, or deleted in Income Tax are automatically removed from the e- mail list.

ONESOURCE 2016



MOBILE TRACKING OF E-FILE STATUS‌‌

You can track the status of your e-filings from any mobile device in real time. Visit m.onesourcelogin.com.


E-FILING A BATCH OF RETURNS

  1. On the Income Tax menu bar, select Batch.

  2. Select EFile | E-file Submission.



  3. Select a Workarea, Binder Type, Year, Filing Status (Choose from Federal, Federal and State or State Only unless creating a batch for Massachusetts consolidated returns.)

  4. Select Search.

  5. Select the files you want to electronically file.

  6. Use the Add or Add All buttons to move the desired e-files from the Available Binders list to the Selected Binders list.

  7. Enter a name for the batch of files.

  8. Click E-File.

  9. The Batch E-Filing Status screen appears and shows the status of your submitted returns.


ROLLOVER‌‌

Rollover on the Batch menu allows you to rollover binders and charts simultaneously. The rollover process takes all of the information in the current year binder or chart and rolls it over to the next year binder or chart to save you time when starting a new tax year. If you already have ONESOURCE Income Tax, you must rollover your charts before rolling your binders. You can rollover charts either individually or in a batch.



INTERNATIONAL ENTERPRISE‌

If you use the international product, click Rollover International Enterprise and rollover your source codes. If you do not use the international product, you will not use this option.


CHARTS‌

This option gives you the ability to rollover all your charts in a batch. If you are starting a new tax year and already have ONESOURCE Income Tax, you must rollover your charts before rolling over your binders. Rolling over charts can be done either individually or in a batch.

In addition,

  • You must have Administrator rights to rollover charts.

  • Once a chart has been rolled over, it cannot be rolled over again.

  • If you have the International software, you must rollover the International Enterprise before beginning the chart rollover.

    ONESOURCE 2016



    ROLLING OVER CHARTS

    1. On the Income Tax menu bar, select Batch.

    2. On the left navigation tree, select Rollover | Rollover Charts.


    3. Select the year for the charts you want to rollover.

    4. Select the charts you want to rollover in the Available Charts pane.

    5. In the middle column, click Add to select individual charts or click Add All to select all the charts.

    6. Select the option(s) that applies:

      • Regardless of law or forms changes, do not change my custom logic.

      • Regardless of tax rate changes, do not update the end of year tax rates.

    7. Click Rollover.

    8. Expand the plus sign (+) and select the charts to rollover by checking the box beside the chart and clicking

      Add. To rollover all charts, select Add All.

       When rolling over an Adjustment chart, the software automatically chooses the Federal Chart of Accounts associated with the chart and rolls it over if it has not already been rolled over.

       When a Federal COA has been rolled over and not the Adjustment chart, the Federal COA appears in bold with the word “rolled” next to it.

    9. Click Rollover.

    10. Use the Rollover Charts Status screen to review the progress.


    ROLLOVER CHART DEPENDENCIES

    The rollover process checks certain dependencies before rolling over the chart(s). It logs any errors in a log report for you to review and correct.

    Federal

  • The Federal Chart of Accounts (COA) associated with the adjustments must be rolled over before the Adjustment Charts (Book, Reclass, Tax) charts can be rolled over.

  • The M3 Line Coding and Federal COA associated with the line mapping chart must rolled over before the M3 Line Mapping Chart can be rolled over.


  • The Provision CTD Grouping chart must be rolled over before the Provision CTD Mapping chart can be rolled over.

  • The Federal Tax Adjustment chart associated with the K-1 Transfer chart must be rolled over before the Partnership K-1 Transfer chart can be rolled over.

    State

  • The State TI Categories must be rolled over before the State TI Forms Mapping chart can be rolled over. International

  • The Federal Chart of Accounts and International Summary Charts associated must be rolled over before the

    related International Cross-Reference can be rolled over.

  • The Federal Chart of Accounts associated with the Schedule M chart must be rolled over before the 5471 Schedule M Cross-Reference Chart can be rolled over.

  • The Federal Chart of Accounts associated with the DASTM Chart of Accounts must be rolled over before the DASTM Chart of Accounts can be rolled over.

  • The Federal Chart of Accounts and Tax Adjustment Chart must be rolled over before the related 8865 K-1 Transfer Mapping Chart can be rolled over.

  • The Federal Chart of Accounts and Tax Adjustment Chart must be rolled over before the related International Transfer Mapping Chart can be rolled over.

    If any of these dependencies are not followed, the application generates a log file with error message(s) for you to review and correct.


    ROLLOVER CHART STATUS‌‌

    Once the batch chart rollover process begins, the Rollover Charts Status screen opens. You can view the rolled over charts from this screen which shows the chart type, chart name, rollover status, and a date and time stamp for the rollover.



     Charts are associated with a Federal COA such as the Adjustment charts, will show the Federal COA name in brackets before the Adjustment chart name.

    If the chart name is in bold and the status shows Rollover Failed - Please review the Status Log by the chart, select the Log Report to see the issue.

    ONESOURCE 2016



    Error Messages

    The software gives two types of messages if there is a problem with the requested task:

  • Error. This indicates there is a problem and the software did not rollover the chart.

  • Warning. This indicates that the software rolled over part of the chart and lists the items that it could not rollover.


    BINDER STATUS

    Binder Status tells you the status of the rollover.



    ROLLOVER CONSOLIDATION‌‌

    1. On the Income Tax menu bar, select Batch.

    2. Select Rollover | Rollover Consolidation.



    3. Select the following binder information from the drop-down lists:

      • Consolidation Type


      • Workarea

      • Entity

      • Binder Type

      • Year

      • Binder

    4. Click Next. The screen shows the member list from the prior-period consolidated entity binder on the right side of the screen. All members in the list have a checkmark in front of them. To remove members from this list, click the member name. This removes the checkmark and moves the member from the right side to the left side under the Domestic members to exclude in rolled over binder:section.


    5. The Rollover Wizard can determine if the member binder has already been rolled over or not. This screen displays the domestic members to include in the rolled over consolidated binder. The Rollover Wizard will not roll over a member binder multiple times.

    6. If the consolidated binder includes members that have partnerships assigned to them, then Step 2a of the Consolidate Rollover Wizard allows you to select the partnerships to rollover and assign to member binders.

    7. Click Next. The same screen appears with a list of International members, if applicable.

    8. Select the appropriate members to Not Roll Over.

    9. Click Next. The Finish Rollover screen appears. It contains instructions about finishing the consolidated rollover and selecting the chart assignment options.

    10. Click Finish to complete the rollover process.

    11. To check the status of a rollover, on the left menu, select Rollover Binders Status.

    ONESOURCE 2016


    WORKPAPERS‌


    FEDERAL ADJUSTMENT WORKPAPER‌‌

    This feature gives you the ability to enter or review adjustment data in a columnar format by company workpaper.

    1. On the Income Tax menu bar, select Workpapers | Federal Adjustment Workpaper.



    2. Select the following for the Chart of Adjustments and binders:

      • Select the Tax Year.

      • Select the Federal Chart of Accounts from the drop-down list.

      • Select the Chart of Adjustments and the type of adjustment (Book, Reclass, Tax)

      • Select the Return Type.

      • Select the Binders by: either Binder Identification or Binder Group.

         Before you use the Federal Adjustment Workpaper, complete the Binder Identification process or create a binder group that has the needed binders assigned to it.

    3. Click Load.

    4. The adjustments will be displayed as rows and the binders will be the columns. Use this workpaper to enter or review your adjustment data.

    5. After you enter data, click Save to save it. The adjustment data must be balanced before the system will allow you to save it. Once data is saved in this workpaper it is also saved in the Adjustments area inside a binder and vice-versa.


    ADDITIONAL DETAILS ABOUT THE FEDERAL ADJUSTMENT WORKPAPER

  • Each binder column, displays the Company Number, Company Name, and Binder name. Consolidated binders are not displayed. Binders that are set as "Read only" are inactive (gray) and cannot be edited.

  • The adjustment/account rows will be inactive and unable to edit if the adjustment has any of the following settings:

    • Auto settings

    • K-1 Transfer

    • 8865 K-1 Transfer

    • International Transfer

    • System computed adjustments like A001, A002, A003 and A004.

  • Users must have Edit Federal permissions for a binder in order to make edits.

  • Use the Expand All, Collapse All, and scrolling features to quickly view all details of the workpaper.

  • Use the Export feature to export the data on the workpaper to a csv file.

  • For each adjustment/account row, select the appropriate button to:

    • Show Audit Trail - This detail screen shows the changes for that adjustment. It gives a list of the dates, users, and amounts entered for that adjustment. It shows whether the amount came from data entry, import or transfer from Provision.

    • Show Provision Transfer Detail - This detail screen shows that the data came from a transfer from Provision. It also shows the Enhanced Integration of ONESOURCE Income Tax and ONESOURCE Tax Provision processes. The detail on the screen shows the following information about the data that was transferred from Provision:

    • Source unit code and name

    • Source temporary/permanent code and name

    • Source amount

    • Multiplier - This is the multiplier being applied for this adjustment before it transfers to the income tax return. For example, a user may enter 100% in the Mapping as the multiplier to map a Provision temporary code to an Income Tax adjustment in a chart of tax adjustments.

    • Transfer amount - This is the amount that transfers to the Federal Adjustment Workpaper for that company's tax adjustment. It is also saved in the Adjustments area inside the binder.

    • Needs Review - If Needs Review appears next to an adjustment after completing a transfer from Provision. It means no amounts have been transferred to the tax adjustment for that binder and indicates the adjustments which must be reviewed. One reason for an adjustment needing review may be that some of the items are not 100% allocated in the Mapping area or there is not an account for the amounts to transfer.

CHAPTER 7: ENTERPRISE CONTROL PANEL‌‌


The Enterprise Control Panel (ECP) saves time and ensures consistency among binders. The ECP allows you to control a number of default features on an enterprise level such as, assigning common general information and assigning charts to selected entities and binders or selecting return options for federal, state, or consolidations. You must have administrator rights to use the ECP.

On each of the screens, you can apply the changes to Binder Groups or Binders. The changes appear when you view Binder Properties. For changes to appear in Organizer and Tax Forms, you must compute the binder.

FEDERAL‌

The Enterprise Control Panel menu is on the Income Tax menu bar. You must have Administrator permis- sions to use this menu.



GENERAL INFORMATION‌‌

  1. Select Federal | General Information.

  2. Enter the company information in the appropriate fields.

  3. Enter the beginning and ending fiscal year dates.

  4. Click Select Entities to apply the general information to the entities. The General Information Assignment for Entities window opens.



  5. Select a Workarea for the entities.

  6. Select the entities where you want to apply the general information.

  7. Click Select All to select all entities listed or click Remove all to clear your selections.

  8. To select multiple entities, select the first entity and then hold down the Shift key and select the last entity. All the entities between the first and the last will be highlighted. To select non-consecutive entities, use the Ctrl key.

  9. Click Select to apply the information to all the selected entities.

  10. Click OK to apply your selections or click Close to return to the previous window with no changes.

ONESOURCE 2016



ASSIGN CHARTS TO BINDERS‌

Use the ECP to assign multiple charts to binders.

  1. Select Federal | Assign Charts to Binders.



  2. Select the Year from the drop-down list.

  3. Select the Tax Return Type from the drop-down list.

  4. Select the charts to assign to the binders from the drop-down lists.

  5. Click either Select Binder Group or Select Binders.



  6. Select the Binder Group or Workarea depending on whether you are assigning charts to a Binder Group or Binders. The year and tax type are selected from the previous screen.

  7. Click Search.

  8. On the screen that follows, select the binders to assign charts to them. The system defaults to selecting all binders.

  9. Click Select All if all binders should receive the chart assignments.

  10. To select multiple binders, select the first binder and then hold down the Shift key and select the last binder.


    All the binders between the first binder and the last binder will be highlighted.

  11. Click Select to apply the chart assignment to the selected binders.

  12. Click OK.

  13. Click Yes to verify assignment of the charts.

  14. Click OK to exit Enterprise Control Panel.

 The Enterprise Control Panel cannot change existing binder chart assignments. Once a chart has been assigned and used in a binder, the binder cannot be assigned a new chart.

    • Federal Chart of Accounts

    • Close Books to Retained Earnings Account

    • Post Rounding Difference to Balance Sheet Account

    • Round Up to the Amount of

    • Post Translation Gain/Loss to Retained Earnings Account

    • Toggle Update with Federal TAS On so Federal TAS detail will transfer to Organizer.

    • Toggle Update with Federal TAS Off so Federal TAS detail will not transfer to Organizer.

    • Suppress automatic transfer or reconciling amount to Other Decreases (or Other Increases), Translation Gain/Loss TRC 997 in Organizer

    • Change Read Only flag for binders

      ONESOURCE 2016



    • Change Locked Balances flag for binders

  5. Select Print to suppress or print options for the listed items.

  6. Select Page 1-2 Suppression to select the options to print or suppress information on detail schedules.

  7. Select Jurisdictional Locking to Lock or Unlock Federal or Officer Compensation information for binders. You can view jurisdictional locking in Organizer but can only make changes in the ECP.

  8. At the bottom of each screen, click Select Binder Group or Select Binders to apply the selections and information to binders.

  13. Click OK to save your assignments.


    ENTITY IMPORT‌‌

    Entity Import on the Enterprise Control Panel allows you to streamline the process of setting up entities and binders by importing data from a spreadsheet file.

    Entity Import allows you to:

    • Create several entities at one time.

    • Include information that completes several fields on the entity’s Properties screen for each entity.

    • Create one binder for each entity you create.

    • Create a Workarea if you choose not to import entities into an existing workarea.

    • Import data from a .CSV or .DIF file. Entity Import cannot:

    • Modify entity properties for existing entities.

    • Modify binder properties for existing entities.

    • Add binders to existing entities.

    • Create multiple binders for the same entity.

 Binders created using Entity Import are not counted toward the number of Return Paks used until the binder is opened. Use the Account Information screen to see the number of Return Paks purchased and used.


You can add new entities to an existing workarea or create a new workarea during the import process.


IMPORTING ENTITIES

  1. Select Federal | Entity Import.



  2. Select one of the existing workareas or choose Create New Workarea from the drop-down list.

  3. Enter the unique workarea name.

  4. Either select one of the listed files from the drop-down list or click Browse to choose your source file from the

    Select Import File dialog box and click Open.

  5. To Select an Import Template, either select one of the listed templates or click New to define a new template or use Edit to modify an existing template. (spreadsheet file must be in .csv format.)

     Make sure you specify the correct starting row if the spreadsheet file contains a header row.

  6. Once the template is defined, click OK to return to the Entity Import screen.

  7. Click Import.

  8. Click Error Log to review error messages provided by the system.

  9. Click Cancel to exit.


PREPARING A SOURCE FILE TO IMPORT NEW ENTITIES

To use Entity Import, you must have a source file that contains the information needed by the application to create entities. If you are creating a binder for each entity, you must also have a valid binder year and binder name.

All records in the import source file must have the identical layout and each record must contain all the required data elements. The following items are the required and optional data elements for these files.

The Income Tax Binder Year should be the prior year to allow you to enter information needed for the beginning balance sheet and state property factors.

JURISDICTIONAL LOCKING

This screen allows you to lock or stop state computations for a certain jurisdiction or area of the return. The system also allows you to do this for federal areas. This is an administrator function and can only be updated through the Enterprise Control Panel.

The locking screen is available in Organizer for viewing purposes only.

  1. Select the Jurisdictional Locking tab.



  2. Check the area(s) where you wish to lock jurisdictions; Common State, Allocation & Apportionment, individual states.

  3. Click Select Binder Group or Select Binders to apply the information to binders.

  4. On the Assignments for Binders screen, select either a Binder Group or a Workarea. The Year is selected from the previous screen.

  5. Click Search. The binder groups and binders that fit the criteria appear. The system defaults to selecting all binders (for Binder Groups.)

  6. To select multiple binders, select the first binder and then hold down the Shift key and select the last binder. All the binders between the first binder and the last binder will be selected. To select non-sequential binders, hold down the Ctrl key.

  7. Click Select to apply the option to all the highlighted binders.

  8. Click OK.

  9. Exit the return.

  10. Re-open the return. The locked area will not allow changes.

  11. You can still enter data in the Organizer screens, but it will not be saved when you move to another screen.

 Once you apply a lock to a binder, any computes or updates you make to the data are prevented to ensure that the tax return results are not changed. Therefore, make sure the consolidation process for a top consolidation for a jurisdiction is completed before you lock the members of that consolidation for that jurisdiction. If not, the system cannot access the jurisdiction for each member to complete the consolidation process.

CHAPTER 8: TOOLS‌‌


The Tools menu contains system-wide types of tasks:


ONESOURCE Tools

Provision Admin Tools

Download Client Download Excel Add-in


ONESOURCE TOOLS‌‌

ONESOURCE Tools are tasks related to integration processes between income tax and other ONESOURCE products.

On the Income Tax menu bar, select Tools | ONESOURCE Tools.



BINDER IDENTIFICATION‌‌

Binder Identification gives you the ability to identify data to share with other ONESOURCE systems. The task is a three part process:

  1. Select Binder Identification.



  2. On the Binder Identification (Step 1) screen, select the tax return Year from the drop-down list.

  3. Select the filing method for Federal and each State Jurisdiction you wish to file. The choices are Combined/ Consolidated, Separate, Both, or Not Filing.

  4. Click Next.

  5. You can print each screen by selecting Print.

  6. Select the consolidated binders used for filing for each jurisdiction, on the Binder Identification (Step 2)

    screen.

    ONESOURCE 2016



    When you select a consolidation binder, each member is also selected for that jurisdiction. If you choose Select All the system selects every jurisdiction for that row. This step displays the Top Consolidation and some Sub Consolidation binders if they were used for filing.

  7. After your selections, click Next. To see the previous screen, click Back.

  8. Select the separate company binders used for filing on the Binder Identification (Step 3) screen.



    The items on this screen are the result of the selections from the previous two screens.

  9. You can also Batch Select binders on this screen to quickly select binders for jurisdictions based on the binder name. There is also an option to “de-select” in a batch.


  10. Click Finish to complete the Binder Identification task.

  11. Click Print on any of the three screens to print a copy of the information.

  12. Select the Year and check the boxes for Federal and States. You must select these options before this data can be shared.

  13. To indicate data is available to share, go to Tools | Provision | Return to Provision Availability.

MANAGE WORKFLOW LINKS‌‌

ONESOURCE Income Tax data can be linked with ONESOURCE WorkFlow Manager if you have purchased both applications.

You can create custom links between the two applications on any of the screens in the Tax Accounting System, and manage or modify those links on the Tools menu in the RS Browser.

 Before you can use WorkFlow Manager, you must complete some setup tasks. Refer to the ONESOURCE WorkFlow Manager User Guide for information about how to use the application.

 Before you can access this feature, you must have the appropriate user rights to be part of the Manage_Links_System_OSW group in ONESOURCE platform.


MANAGING WORKFLOW LINKS

  1. Select Manage WorkFlow Links.

  2. Use the icon buttons on the toolbar at the top of the screen to move or copy links from one location to another.

  3. Select the 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 buttons to view the folder and link detail.

  4. To search a link, place your cursor in the Find field and enter the appropriate information. The system will highlight the first link that meets the search criteria.

  5. Select the up and down arrows to navigate to other links that meet the same criteria.

  6. To change the link name, select a link and enter the new name.

  7. Click Save to save the changes.

  8. Select a different Tax Accounting System area to exit.

 Refer to the ONESOURCE Income Tax and WorkFlow Manager Integration Guide for more information.


STATE APPORTIONMENT OPTIONS‌

Select this option if you have a license and use the ONESOURCE State Apportionment product and would like to integrate the data between the two systems.

Activating this option, deactivates the Tax Accounting System State A&A functionality in all binders for the selected year.

  1. On the Income Tax menu bar, click Tools.

  2. Select ONESOURCE Tools | State Apportionment Options.



  3. Select the Year from the drop-down list.

  4. Select Use ONESOURCE State Apportionment for state apportionment data to integrate ONESOURCE State Apportionment data with ONESOURCE Income Tax. This deactivates the ONESOURCE Income Tax State A&A workpapers in all tax return binders in the account for the selected year.

  5. Transfer ONESOURCE State Apportionment data to ONESOURCE Income Tax.

 This feature also requires some set up steps in the ONESOURCE platform. Please refer to the ONESOURCE platform user guide for more information.

ONESOURCE STATE APPORTIONMENT INTEGRATION‌‌

Starting in tax year 2010, we added options to integrate other supported ONESOURCE products with ONESOURCE Income Tax.

One such product is ONESOURCE State Apportionment. The integration feature facilitates the transfer of state allocation and apportionment data in ONESOURCE State Apportionment to selected binders in ONESOURCE Income Tax. You can use it with 1120 C Corporations, 1120S S Corporations, and 1065 Partnership binders.


MAPPING STATE APPORTIONMENT TO INCOME TAX

To allow information to flow freely from ONESOURCE State Apportionment to ONESOURCE Income Tax, you must map State Apportionment Entities to Income Tax Companies.

  1. From ONESOURCE, on the menu bar, select Menu | Mapping.



  2. In the Source drop-down list, select State Apportionment.



  3. In the Target drop-down list, select Income Tax.

  4. Select the year in the Year drop-down list.

  5. The Map Sets and Maps tabs screen appears. Use these screens to build maps and map sets.



CREATING MAPS

You can either create a new map using an existing file as a template or create one without a template. See “Creating a Map Import Template” on page 120.

  1. On the Maps tab, select New.

  2. In the Create New Map dialog box, enter a Name and Description for the map.

  3. OSA Entity Map is the default value for Map Type. No other options are available.

  4. Click OK.



  5. When the mapping screen opens, the next step is to map the data elements. See “Mapping the Data Elements” on page 130.


CREATING A STATE APPORTIONMENT MAP SET

You can create only one State Apportionment Map Set.

  1. On the ONESOURCE Platform menu bar, select Menu | Mapping.

  2. In the Source drop-down list, select State Apportionment.

  3. In the Target drop-down list, select Income Tax.

  4. In the Year drop-down list, select the year.

  5. The Map Sets and Maps tabs appear.

  6. Click the Map Sets tab.

  7. Click New.

  8. In the Create New Map Set dialog box, enter a Name and Description.

  9. In the Associated Map list, select an OSA Entity map.

  10. Click Save. The Map Set now appears in the list.

ONESOURCE Income Tax and ONESOURCE State Apportionment use the associated map in the map set to determine the relationship between the entities and companies in the respective products.

PROVISION‌

Provision tools are tasks to help you transfer data between Tax Provision and Income Tax. The Tools

menu is on the Income Tax menu bar.



TRANSFER FROM PROVISION‌‌

ONESOURCE Tax Provision Transfer gives you the ability to share data between the ONESOURCE Tax Provision system and the ONESOURCE Income Tax system.

You can start the tax return processing for the new year with data used in the ONESOURCE Tax Provision and share tax adjustment balances and trial balance data between the two systems and then transfer it directly into the tax return binders.

Before you can transfer data, you must do the following:

  1. Create binders for the target year and assign a Federal Chart of Accounts and a Chart of Adjustments.

  2. Complete the mapping. (See “Mapping Process” on page 118.)

  3. Review and assign the Transfer from Provision selections, these are the target Balance Sheet and Income Statement accounts for each tax adjustment in the Chart of Tax Adjustments.

  4. To indicate data is available to share, go to Tools | Provision | Return to Provision Availability and mark Federal and State as Final.

 To transfer federal data, you must check Federal on the applicable Binder Identification screen (Tools | ONESOURCE Tools | Binder Identification | <Current Year>)


STARTING THE PROVISION TRANSFER PROCESS

  1. Select Provision | Transfer from Provision.



  2. Select the Tax Year from the drop-down list.

  3. Select the Map Set from the drop-down list.

  4. Select the Data Type, either Tax Adjustment Balances or Trial Balances.

  5. Click Begin to start the process of updating data from Provision to the Tax Return binders.

 A successful transfer of Tax Adjustment Balances and Trial Balances will show a “Successful” status next to the Begin button.

The Status Log section shows the data being transferred, the start and finish date and times, the user initiating the transfer, and a description of the progress of the transfer. A successful transfer will indicate “Successful”. If there is an error please make note of the error when requesting help.

    MAPPING PROCESS‌

    To allow information to flow freely from ONESOURCE Income Tax and ONESOURCE Tax Provision, users must map similar data elements to each other.

    1. From the ONESOURCE platform, on the menu bar, select Menu | Mapping.


    2. Select the Source, Target, and Year from the drop-down lists.



      These screens are used to build maps and map sets.

      • The Source is the system that contains information that will be sent to the Target.

      • The Target is the system that will receive information from the Source.

        For example, tax adjustment amounts from a tax return are needed to prepare return-to-provision adjust- ments for the tax provision. In this case the Source would be ONESOURCE Income Tax and the Target would be ONESOURCE Tax Provision.

        Alternatively, estimated tax adjustments from the current year end provision can be used as a starting point for preparing the tax return. In this case the Source would be ONESOURCE Tax Provision and the Target would be ONESOURCE Income Tax.

        ONESOURCE 2016



    3. You will see two tabs, Map Sets and Map.



    4. Select the Maps tab.

    5. Click New.



    6. Enter the Name and Description for the map.

    7. Select the Map type, either Unit-Entity or Book-to-Tax Difference.

    8. Click Save. The map now appears in the list.

    9. Click the Open button to begin mapping the data elements.

     The Source and Target information is in real-time. The lists reflect the current state of each.


    CREATING MAPS

    There are several methods you can use to create a map file. You can:

  • create a new map

  • create a new map from an import template

  • create a map from an existing map file.

    The best way to create a new map using an import file, is to first save a template for the map type you want to create.

    1. From ONESOURCE Platform, on the menu bar, select Menu | Mapping.

    2. Select the Source, Target, and Year from the drop-down lists.

    3. Once the screen loads click Export Map Template.



    4. Select the Map Type you want to create from the drop-down list.


    5. Click OK.

    6. Select a directory location to save the template.



    7. Enter a file name.

    8. Click Save.

    ONESOURCE 2016

    3. In the Create New Map dialog box.

      • Enter a Map Name.

      • Enter a Map Description.

      • Select the From Map Import File check box.


      • Click OK.



    4. Select your import file. The import file can be in *.xlsx or *.csv format.



      IMPORTANT: If you have multiple tabs in your import file, the tab with the import data must be named one of the following, depending on the map type you are creating:

  • Entity-Unit Map

  • Book-to-Tax Difference Map

  • Unit-Entity Map

    ONESOURCE 2016



  • OSA Entity Map



  1. Click Open.

  2. Once the file is imported you can view the Import Validation Messages log file. The file shows how the system processed the import file.



  3. The Import Validation Messages log shows the results of the import process as either successful or as errors/ warnings found. You can expand or collapse each section of the Import Validation Messages log to see the information.



  4. Click Print to get a paper copy of the log.


  5. Click Save to convert the log to either a *.txt or *.csv file.

  6. Click Close to exit the Import Validation Messages log and return to the mapping screen.


  7. Click Save to complete the mapping process.

ONESOURCE 2016



CREATING A NEW MAP FILE FROM AN EXISTING MAP

You can create a new map by importing into an existing map. This process removes the existing mapping and replaces it with the mapping in the import file.

  1. On the Maps tab, click the Open button at the bottom of the screen.



  2. Click the Import button at the bottom of the mapping screen.



  3. Select the appropriate import file. The file can be in *.xlsx or *.csv format.



  4. IMPORTANT: If you have multiple tabs in your import file, the tab with the import data must be named one of the following, depending on the map type you are creating:

    • Entity-Unit Map

    • Book-to-Tax Difference Map

    • Unit-Entity Map

    • OSA Entity Map



      ONESOURCE 2016



  5. A warning message appears stating that existing mapping will be re-mapped with the mapping in the import file.



  6. Once the file is imported you can view the Import Validation Messages log file. The file shows how the system processed the import file.


  7. The Import Validation Messages log shows the results of the import process as either successful or as errors/ warnings found. You can expand or collapse each section of the Import Validation Messages log to see the information.



  8. Click Print to get a paper copy of the log.

  9. Click Save to convert the log to either a *.txt or *.csv file.

  10. Click Close to exit the Import Validation Messages log and return to the mapping screen.


  11. Click Save to complete the mapping process.

In the ONESOURCE platform, you can export an existing map file. It can be exported in either *.xlsx or *.csv format.

MAPPING THE DATA ELEMENTS‌‌

  1. On the mapping screen, select an item in the Source pane.

  2. Select an item in the Target pane.

  3. Click the arrow in the center between the two systems, which points to the right, to map the selected Source item to the selected Target item.

  4. When an item is mapped, the Source item appears underneath the target for which it is mapped.


  5. Continue until the mapping is done.

  6. Click Save to finish the process.

You can also apply a multiplier to allocate a portion of the mapped item. The mapping system defaults to a 100% multiplier when the item is mapped. If an item is not allocated 100%, the system gives you a warning message when it is saved.



This feature is useful if you have to allocate a Source to multiple Targets.

MAPPING FEATURES

Mapping provides many features that aid in building maps.

  • Find search box: displays items in a list that contain the search term entered.

  • Show All filter button (default): displays all items in the list.

  • Show Mapped filter button: displays only those items in the list that are currently mapped.

  • Show Unmapped filter button: displays only those items in the list that are currently not mapped.

  • Auto-map: used when data elements are identically named in the Source and Target systems. Auto-map in an Entity-Unit map matches ONESOURCE Income Tax Company numbers with ONESOURCE Tax Provision Unit numbers. Auto-map in a Book-to-Tax map matches ONESOURCE Income Tax Tax Adjustment JE numbers with ONESOURCE Tax Provision Temporary/Permanent codes.

  • Un-map: used to remove all previously mapped items.

  • Color highlighting: (Source system only) indicates items in the list that have been mapped.

  • Each column can be sorted by clicking the column heading.

  • Each column can be filtered by clicking the filter indicator in the column heading and then select items to show.

  • Turn on Grouping by Column: allow you to group the list of items by dragging a column heading into blank area above column.


    CREATING MAP SETS FOR TRANSFER FROM PROVISION‌‌

    A map set is used to create the intersection of an Entity-Map and a Book-to-Tax Difference Map. The combination of the two maps provides sufficient detail for data to be mapped and transformed between the Source and Target. A map set defines what maps are used when the sharing of data between the two systems is processed.

    1. From ONESOURCE, on the menu bar, select Menu | Mapping.

    2. Select the Source, Target, and Year from the drop-down lists.

    3. Two tabs appear, Map Sets and Maps.

    4. Select the Map Sets tab.

    5. Select New to create a new map set.

    6. Enter a Name and Description.

    7. Select a Unit-Entity map.

    8. Select a Book-to-Tax Difference map.

    9. Click Save. The Map Set now appears in the list.


    MAPPING EXAMPLE:

    ONESOURCE Tax Provision as the Target

    Income Tax Adjustments mapped to Tax Provision Temporary and Permanent differences
