With Excel Add-in, you can open an existing or new Excel worksheet, map the data, and then export the mapped data to ONESOURCE Income Tax form fields in Organizer or data entry screens in the Tax Accounting System.

The Excel Add-in enhances the efficiency of data transfer by:

  • Decreasing data transfer time.

  • Eliminating transcription errors that can occur when manually transferring data.

  • Incorporating tools for copying data and mapping schema from one worksheet to another in preparation for import.

  • Enhancing the control and flexibility of data transfer and management.

  • Identifying worksheet errors such as duplications, incorrect codes, and miscalculations, before data is loaded into the Tax Accounting System or Organizer, preventing time-consuming edits and corrections.

The Excel Add-in is currently available for 2009 forward Organizer import. The Tax Accounting System import for adjustments is available for 2003 forward.

CHAPTER 9: CHARTS‌‌


The relationship between the Tax Return Code (TRC) and the Tax Combination Code (TCC) is the foundation for all account management. Charts are used to identify TRC/TCC combination codes, accounts, and adjustments for multiple entities and binders. The charts are related by using elements from other charts to create a “set” of charts. Each set of charts is then assigned to an entity to use for TRC/TCCs, accounts, and adjustments. Chart assignments are either Common or Separate as described below.


CHARTS‌

Common Charts

We strongly recommend that you use common charts across all entities when possible. When you use common charts, consolidated workpapers show detail displayed by common account numbers and Tax Combination Code (TCC) descriptions across entities.



Separate Charts across Entities

If each entity uses a different Chart of Accounts, you must create separate charts. When you use separate charts, workpaper detail can only be consolidated at a TRC level. If a common chart of TCCs is used, the tax accounting system can be consolidated at either the TRC or TCC level.


ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



The following charts are created and maintained within the software:

  • Tax Combination Codes

  • Federal Accounts

  • Federal Adjustments

  • State Workpaper: State Allocation & Apportionment (A&A) and State Taxable Income (TI)


    TAX RETURN CODES‌‌

    To create tax returns, the software uses system-defined Tax Return Codes (TRCs) to “map” individual account balances from a company’s general ledger to specific lines on the tax return. To ensure account balances are transferred to the appropriate area of the tax return, every account within a company’s chart of accounts must be assigned a valid TRC.

     For a complete list of TRCs, please download the TRC List on the Customer Center website.

    The following table lists the general category TRC number for each schedule.

    CHART OF TAX COMBINATION CODES‌‌

    The Charts of Tax Combination Codes (TCCs) and the Tax Return Codes (TRCs) relationship are the foundation for all account management. TCCs allow users to add multiple customized descriptions for individual TRCs that populate TAS workpapers, reports and whitepaper detail of the return. The Chart of TCCs is the first chart you create.

    A TCC is a user-defined code used to combine accounts into subcategories within a single TRC. The descriptions you enter for TCCs are used in workpapers and on tax return supporting schedules. The application summarizes and consolidates account balances based on the TRCs/TCCs assigned to the accounts in the system.


     We strongly recommend using a common chart of TCCs.

    Common Charts of Tax Combination Codes Rules and Guidelines

  • Page 1 and Schedule M-1 descriptions are limited to 50 characters.

  • Balance Sheet descriptions are limited to 35 characters.

  • Tax Return Codes are limited to 150 Tax Combination Code descriptions except for the Schedule M-1, which is limited to 255 descriptions for line 5C and 8C.

  • Every account number must have a valid TRC and TCC.

  • You can enter data into a Chart of TCCs manually, copy it from an existing Chart of TCCs, or import from an outside file.

  • ONESOURCE Income Tax provides a default Chart of TCCs for copying.

  • A TCC number can be up to three-digits in length.

  • Use of a common chart of TCCs is strongly recommended (contact your client service representative for assistance with establishing a common chart of TCCs)

  • Skip between TCC numbers so more can be added later.

    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



  • Changing a TCC affects all charts and data based on that chart.

  • Changing a TCC affects all charts and data based on that specific Chart of TCCs.

  • There must be a common TCC Chart for a cross-tie return in consolidations.

  • Once a Chart of TCC is assigned to a Chart of Accounts, it cannot be deleted until all Charts of Accounts that use that particular Chart of TCCs are deleted.

    A Chart of Tax Combination Codes consists of TRCs and related TCCs. The application uses predefined TRCs to relate accounts in a Chart of Accounts to a specific line on a federal or state tax return.


    ADDING A CHART OF TAX COMBINATION CODES

    1. On the Income Tax menu bar, select Charts.

    2. Select Federal | Tax Combination Codes.




    3. Select the Year.

    4. On the Chart menu, select Add Chart.



    5. Enter the:

      • Year for the chart.

      • Chart Name.

      • Select an existing chart of TCCs to copy from the Copy from drop-down list, if desired.

    6. Click Save. You can enter data in the Chart of Tax Combination Codes either manually or by import.


    MANUALLY SETTING UP THE CHART OF TCCS

    1. Select the Tax Combination Codes you wish to edit.

    2. Open the chart.



    3. Select the Tax Return Type from the drop-down list. (1065, 1120, 1120F, 1120L, 1120PC, 1120REIT, 1120S, 5471/8858/8865)

    4. Select the appropriate TRC that you wish to edit TCC’s and click Add.

    5. Enter a TCC three-digit number and description.

       TCC 001 should be the first TCC added with the same description as the corresponding TRC. When defining additional TCCs start with 002 or higher for customized TCC descriptions.

    6. Click Save.

    7. Repeat the process for as many TCCs as desired.

    8. Click Close.

    Editing or Deleting TCCs

    To change TCC information in the Chart of TCCs, select the field to edit and revise the text.

    To delete a TCC and the description, select the TCC and click Delete. When the confirmation dialog box appears, click Yes to delete or No to cancel.

     Editing and Deleting TCCs affects all accounts and account balances for all years to which the TCCs are related.


    IMPORTING DATA INTO A CHART OF TCCS

    1. On the Tax Combination Codes chart screen, click Import.

    2. Select the import type, see below. (These types apply to all chart imports.)

    3. Click Browse to navigate to your spreadsheet (saved as a .csv file).

    4. Click New to create a new import definition template.

    5. Define each field being careful to specify the correct starting row.

    6. Click OK to save the import definition.

    7. Click Import to load the data from the spreadsheet.

    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



    Import Types

    Select the appropriate import type as defined in the table below. These import types apply to all chart imports.


    IMPORT TYPE

    RESULTS

    Add new entries to an existing chart

    Key records for the chart are compared and any new entries in the spreadsheet are added to the chart.

    Add and replace entries

    Key records for the chart are compared, new entries are added and existing entries are overwritten with spreadsheet contents.

    Replace existing entries only

    Key records for the chart are compared and existing entries are overwritten with spreadsheet values. Any new entries are ignored during import and written to an error log.


    CHART OF ACCOUNTS‌‌

    The Federal Chart of Accounts consists of the general ledger account numbers, account titles, and TRC-TCC code combination assignments displayed in ascending alphanumeric sequence by account number, with the account number serving as the chart lookup code.

    These charts provide the system with the tax attributes of the account and corresponds with the financial accounts of the trial balance you bring into the system. Charts of Accounts are independent of any company or tax function.

    When creating a Federal Chart of Accounts, you must assign a Chart of Tax Combination Codes. Otherwise the default chart is assigned to it. The default chart is the first chart of TCCs listed alphabetically.

    Accounts that you add will be sorted automatically in numerical sequence. Federal Charts of Accounts can be created by either:

  • manually entering data

  • importing data

  • copying data.

    You can edit the Chart of Accounts on an “as needed” basis. Typically, edits take place at the beginning of the filing season before current year balances are entered. Charts should reflect the new account numbers that were added to the organization’s General Ledger throughout the year. To manually edit the chart of accounts, follow the steps on the previous pages.

    The following fields are required in the Chart of Accounts:

  • Account Number

  • Account Description

  • TRC

  • TCC.

    Chart of Account Rules and Guidelines

    Use the following guidelines when using Chart of Accounts:

  • All accounts within the Chart of Accounts must have a valid TRC-TCC code combination.

  • Once a Chart of Accounts is assigned to a binder, it cannot be “un”-assigned.

  • Account Number maximum is 45 characters

  • Account Description maximum is 65 characters


CREATING A CHART OF ACCOUNTS

  1. On the Income Tax menu bar, select Charts.



  2. Select Federal | Accounts and Adjustments.

  3. On the Chart menu bar, select Add Chart.

  4. Enter the following information:

    • Chart Year

    • Name of new chart.

    • Income Tax or Provision Master chart.

    • Chart of TCC from the TCC drop-down list.

  5. To copy an existing Chart of Accounts, select the Chart of Accounts from the Copy from drop-down list (optional).

  6. Click Save. A message appears indicating that the new chart was successfully created.


DELETING A CHART OF ACCOUNTS

  1. From the Chart screen, select the chart you wish to delete.

  2. Click Delete. A message confirmation dialog box appears.

  3. Click Yes to confirm deleting the chart. A second confirmation dialog box appears.

  4. Click Yes to delete the chart or No to return to cancel the request.

 Once you create and assign a Federal Chart of Accounts, you cannot delete it until you first delete all binders that contain a trial balance that used this chart.

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



SETTING ACCOUNT OPTIONS

When you are in a Chart of Accounts, the system allows you to select the rounding and closing options at the enterprise level (chart level), entity level, or binder level.

Closing Options

Closing options depend on whether an open or closed trial balance is entered in the TAS area.

  • Open Trial Balance – This option reports the retained earnings at last year’s ending balance. The retained earnings account balance does not include current-year net income or loss per books. Additionally, debits and credits of the Trial Balance are equal with the possible exception of a nominal rounding amount. Selecting a retained earnings account in the closing options section causes the software to calculate current- year net income and loss per books which closes the trial balance.

  • Closed Trial Balance – This option includes current-year net income or loss per books is included in the retained earnings account. Debits and credits differ by the amount of current-year net income or loss per books.

    Not selecting a retained earnings account in the closing options section prevents net income or loss from being calculated by the software, for not only book income, but also for the income effect of tax adjustments.

    Rounding Options

  • Balance Sheet Account to Post Rounding Differences - This allows you to select the balance sheet account to which to post rounding differences.

  • Rounding Amount - This allows you to select the rounding amount that the system uses to judge out of balance tolerance when you enter your general ledger. For example, assume that you specify your rounding amount as 10. When you import your general ledger, if your debits and credits are not off by more than

    $10.00, the system will post the difference as a rounding adjustment to the account that you select in the Post Rounding Difference to Balance Sheet account: field.


    SETTING OPTIONS FOR A CHART OF ACCOUNTS AT THE ENTERPRISE (CHART) LEVEL

    1. Select the appropriate chart.

    2. Select the More bar to see the sub menu.


    3. Click Closing & Rounding Options.

    4. Select the appropriate closing and rounding accounts from the drop-down list.

    5. Enter a dollar amount for rounding.

    6. Click Save.

    Each line shows the TRC/TCC in brackets that the account is mapped to, the account number, account description and the type of account (Balance Sheet - B/S or Income Statement - I/S).

    The Federal COA Xref chart below was automatically created when the Federal COA was rolled over. The accounts are cross-referenced one to one.



    When using a new chart of accounts or condensing several prior year charts into a current year chart, you must cross-reference the accounts either manually or by importing them.


    MANUALLY CROSS-REFERENCING TO A CURRENT YEAR ACCOUNT

    1. Select the account(s) from the prior year.

    2. Select the account in the current year and click Add. Cross-referencing allows you to map one account to one account or many accounts to one account. The prior year accounts with balances appear with a blue triangle.

    CHART OF ADJUSTMENTS‌‌

    ONESOURCE Income Tax lets you track and analyze book/tax differences and various adjustments to Federal taxable income. The key to this capability is administering Charts of Adjustments, where you define book, reclassification, book-to-tax, adjustments and then assign them to the binder.

    You can create Charts of Adjustments by either manually entering data, importing data, or copying data.

    Each adjustment type uses account numbers from a related chart of accounts which have been assigned a TRC/TCC combination from the Chart of TCCs. Linking account numbers to the Chart of Adjustments completes the chart relationship in the software.

    Types of Adjustments

    ONESOURCE Income Tax includes five types of adjustments:


    ADJUSTMENT TYPE

    DESCRIPTION

    Book

    Adjusts the preliminary book amount. The adjusted book balance is the value after posting book adjustments

    Reclassification

    Moves amounts from one account to another without affecting net income per books. You use this type to achieve proper presentation of amounts in a tax return or workpaper.

    Tax

    Produces book/tax reconciling differences shown on various forms

    AMT

    AMT adjustments and tax preference items.

    ACE

    ACE adjustments and tax preference items.


    Each Chart of Adjustment is independent of any entity or tax function.

     You can have separate adjustment charts for different domestic and international adjusting entries if needed. Typically, fewer adjusting entries are used in international entities.

    Chart of Adjustment Rules and Guidelines

  • Adjustment Number maximum is 10 characters

  • Adjustment Description maximum is 65 characters

  • A separate Chart of Adjustments is created for each type of adjustments (book, reclass and tax.) When setting up a tax adjustment, define specific attributes for it - such as how it is presented on federal tax forms.

  • Every Chart of Accounts must have a Chart of Book Adjustments assigned to it so the system can close the books and book adjustments.

  • Tax adjustments are entered in a journal entry format, with one side of the entry belonging to a P&L account and the other side of the entry belonging to a balance sheet account. This approach lets you maintain a tax basis balance sheet.


  • Each Chart of Adjustments contains a journal entry type, a journal entry number, a description (caption), account numbers, and account descriptions within each journal entry.

  • The Transfer from Provision check box is applicable to ONESOURCE Tax Provision users only. This feature allows the user to designate one default Income Statement and Balance sheet account for each tax adjustment. These selections are used as the target accounts during the Provision Transfer process.

    The following types of tax adjustments do not allow users to select default accounts:

    • System generated tax adjustments (A001, A002, A003, and A004)

    • K-1 Transfer tax adjustment

    • 8865 K-1 Transfer tax adjustment

    • International transfer tax adjustment

    • Tax adjustments that have “Auto” settings applied to each account within the adjustment.


ADDING A CHART OF ADJUSTMENTS

  1. Select Federal | Accounts and Adjustments.

  2. Select the Year of the chart.

  3. On the Accounts and Adjustments screen, on the appropriate chart, select Adjustments.

  4. On the Federal Adjustments screen, select Add Chart.


    New Adjustment Chart


    Select the Adjustment Type of chart.


  5. Select the Adjustment Type from the drop-down list (Book, Reclass, Tax, AMT, ACE).

  6. Enter the name of the new chart.

  7. Click Copy from and select the Chart of Adjustments you want to use as a template (optional).

  8. Click Save and Close.

Enter adjustments either manually or by importing them.

    • Select either Permanent or Temporary to designate the appropriate option for Schedule M-3.

    • Equity adjustments are historically used to indicate adjustments to exclude from the provision. Permanent Equity adjustments must contain at least one balance sheet account and at least one income statement account. Temporary Equity adjustments must contain at least one Asset or Liability account and at least one Equity account and no Income Statement accounts.

    • Select K-1 Transfer to receive data from partnership binders.

    • Purchase Accounting adjustments are historically used to enable you to have permanent and temporary purchase accounting adjustments grouped together on various Provision review workpapers and reports.

       Temporary equity purchase accounting adjustments need at least one asset or liability and one account with an account TRC of 11-830 or 22-100 through 22-440.

    Find.

    • Prior Year Federal COA

    • Prior Year Tax Adjustment

    • Current Year Federal COA

Prior-year, cross-referenced charts appear in blue. Each line shows the tax adjustment number in brackets, the tax adjustment description and the adjustment option (Temporary or Permanent, and Equity, if applicable).

CROSS-REFERENCING TAX ADJUSTMENTS‌‌

  1. Select the tax adjustment(s) from the prior year.

  2. Select the tax adjustment in the current year and click Add. Cross-referencing allows you to map one adjustment to one adjustment or many adjustments to one adjustment.


IMPORTING ADJUSTMENT DATA

The import file must have the Prior Year Adjustment number in one column and the Current Year Adjustment

number to cross-reference to in another column.

  1. Create an import template by clicking Export and saving the file as a .csv file.

  2. Enter your data and then import the file back into the application by clicking Import.

  3. The import process provides you with a log if there are any problems in the import file.


    VALIDATION REPORT‌‌

    When you map the tax adjustments, the system maps the accounts in the Prior Year adjustment to the accounts in the Current Year adjustment based on the Federal COA Xref chart associated with the Tax Adjustment chart.

    The system again provides you with a log if there are any problems. You must first click Save to keep your adjustment changes and then click Validation Report to view the log.


    MAPPING ADJUSTMENT REQUIREMENTS

    The following requirements are necessary to map an adjustment:

    • You must have a balance sheet and an income statement account in the adjustment, unless it is a temporary equity adjustment.

    • You must map the same adjustment options, temporary to temporary, permanent to permanent, equity to equity.

       If changing the permanent/temporary/equity option of a tax adjustment, unmap the adjustment first.


      TAX ADJUSTMENT CROSS-REFERENCE CHARACTERISTICS‌

      After you cross-reference a tax adjustment, you will get the following message on the Edit Federal Tax Adjustment screen, “This adjustment is cross-referenced, you cannot change the options (Permanent, Temporary, Equity) or delete an account until the cross-reference is removed.”

      You must remove the cross-reference to delete an account or change the options Permanent, Temporary, Equity. All other functions are available on the Tax Adjustment screen without removing the cross-reference.


      AUTOMATIC ADJUSTMENTS‌‌

      Adjustments within the Chart of Adjustments can be set to automatically adjust certain items of taxable income and expense based on selected limitations or computations. Auto adjustments should be created when you create the Chart of Adjustments.

       Adding new automatic adjustments or changing existing automatic adjustments impacts all associated entities and binders that use that Adjustment Chart.

      Automatic adjustments can perform functions such as the following:

    • Reverse account balances to zero dollars

    • Adjust for differences between beginning and ending balances

    • Close Net Income.

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



Setting Up Automatic Adjustments

  1. Navigate to the appropriate adjustment type folder to edit adjustments.



  2. Select the desired adjustment and click Edit.

  3. Select an account in the adjusting entry and click Auto.



  4. For each account in the adjustment that you designate as automatic, select:

    • Accounts (first pull-down list) – the target journal entry account that is being automated. This account comes from the journal entry.

    • Source Account (second pull-down menu) – the balance for the target account used in the journal entry comes from this chosen source account. Use the drop-down list to choose the appropriate source account.

    • Balance Type (third pull-down menu) – use the drop-down list to choose the balance type of the source account (for example, preliminary, book, or tax).

    • Percentage - allows you to indicate a percent of an account to be adjusted and thus create custom calculations. For example, you could select 50% here to adjust meals and entertainment per books.

    • Reversing and Balance Options: You must select Ending, Beginning, or Difference first, and then select Negate or not select Negate.

    • Negate – reverses the amount in the selected target account. Commonly used to reverse the FIT general ledger account.

    • Beginning/Ending – applies the automatic adjustment to the beginning or ending account balance. Commonly used for tax exempt income.

    • Difference – takes the difference in source account balances to calculate the adjustment. Commonly used for reserve liability accounts to compute tax amounts.


       An individual account may be used in only one “account” type automatic adjustment per chart type (book, reclass, tax, and so on).


  5. Click OK.

  6. Select an account in the adjustment to balance the entry. Each account automatic adjustment must have

only one account designated as the Balance Entry account.

TAX ADJUSTMENT ATTRIBUTES‌‌


TAX RETURN PRESENTATION

Tax adjustments are entered in a journal entry format, with one side impacting an income statement account and the other side impacting a balance sheet account. This produces the book/tax reconciling differences that appear on various Federal forms. The assignment of a debit/credit impact TRC/TCC code to each adjustment specifies the adjustment presentation (whether as a separate item or combined with other adjustments and associated descriptions) on the Schedule M-1. The net effect on taxable income of each tax adjustment is summarized by the TRC/TCC and shown as a reconciling difference.


SCHEDULE M-3 ATTRIBUTES

The software is designed to generate Schedule M-3 categorization for tax returns. The Options area categorizes each adjustment as either permanent or temporary.

Additional Attributes (for Provision Charts prior to 2014)

  • taxable versus deductible

  • current versus noncurrent.

    The following table describes the provision attributes:


    PROVISION ATTRIBUTES

    DEFINITIONS

    Permanent

    A book/tax difference that will not be offset by a corresponding adjustment in future periods.

    Examples:

    Federal income tax

    Interest income on municipal obligations not taxable for Federal income tax purposes.

    Temporary, Deductible

    An adjustment that will be offset in future periods by deductible amounts. Examples: Loss reserves, Contribution carryover

    Temporary, Taxable

    An adjustment that will be offset in future periods by taxable amounts. Example: Accelerated tax depreciation

    Current/Noncurrent

    Relates to the financial statement classification of the offsetting asset or liability.


    SCHEDULE M-3‌‌

    Schedule M-3 charts for Line Coding and Line Mapping are part of the Charts. Setting up the charts is the first step for using the M-3 feature in the system.


    SCHEDULE M-3 PROCESS

    Use the following steps to process the Schedule M-3 with ONESOURCE Income Tax:

    1. Analyze the organization’s activity to determine the areas of Schedule M-3 that will be populated.

    2. Line Coding: Setup User Defined M-3 Codes for each line that you need on Part II and Part III.

    3. Line Mapping: Map all income statement accounts in each Chart of Accounts to the appropriate user- defined Line Codes for Schedule M-3 in the Home Window.

    4. Data Entry: Enter preliminary balances and adjusting journal entries (JEs). You may need to create some additional JEs to separate Temporary and Permanent amounts. Analyze the chart of journal entries for the following:

      • Do the accounts in the existing entries contain the necessary Schedule M-3 Line Mapping in order to correctly populate the lines of Schedule M-3?.

      • Have the options been correctly setup to populate the Permanent/Temporary columns of Schedule M- 3 Parts II and III?.

      • Edit existing journal entries to include the new “tax” accounts that are mapped to specific areas of Schedule M-3 as well as coded with the appropriate TRC for Form 1120 presentation.

      • Create new journal entries that use the new “tax” accounts for Schedule M-3 Gain/Loss presentation. Code these entries to also populate Schedule M-1 with the appropriate 600 series TRC.

      • Enter preliminary balance and adjustment amounts in the TAS portion of the software.

    5. Detail Data Entry:

      • Enter M-3, Part II, Lines 1-12 for 1120, 1120L, and 1120PC required detail data such as company name and EIN number in the Tax Accounting System (TAS).

      • Enter M-3, Part II, Lines 1-10 for 1120S required detail data such as company name and EIN number in TAS.

      • Enter M-3, Part II, Lines 1-10 for 1065 required detail data such as company name and EIN number in TAS.

    6. Review Your Data: Both Organizer/Tax Forms and Print Preview.


    SETTING UP SCHEDULE M-3‌‌

    Each line of Schedule M-3 is activated for use through the creation of a user-defined line code. Setting up line codes gives the ability to map multiple charts of accounts to single line codes on Schedule M-3. Line codes are established for Schedule M-3, Parts II and III only. Once set up, income statement accounts from the chart of accounts will get mapped to these individual line codes. You can enter data either manually or by importing it.

    Schedule M-3 codes have the following characteristics:

  • user-defined

  • can be alphanumeric up to 12 digits

  • line code descriptions 40 characters in length

  • allows you to determine the level of detail to display on whitepaper reports

  • are exportable, importable, and roll over from year-to-year.

    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



    ENTERING SCHEDULE M-3 LINE CODES

    1. On the top menu bar, select Charts.

    2. On the navigation tree, select Schedule M-3 | Line Coding.


    3. Select the Year and Tax Return Type from the drop-down lists.

    4. Click + to expand Part II or Part III.

    5. Click Add to create a new code and description.

    6. Continue until you are finished entering the amount of detail you wish to see on your whitepaper report.

    7. Click Export to export a file to use as a template.

    8. Click Import to import a .csv file instead of entering the data manually.

    9. Click Close when you are finished with the screen.


    COST OF GOODS SOLD SECTION EXPANDED

  • Part II, Lines for Cost of Goods Sold has been expanded on IRS Form 8916-A for filing the required detail. You must code these expanded lines to correspond with this form.

  • Cost of Goods Sold - Other Items with Differences allows you to add multiple line codes for additional whitepaper detail.


    INTEREST INCOME AND EXPENSE ITEMS EXPANDED

  • Part II Interest Income: Expanded detail on Form 8916-A. You must code Interest Income lines to correspond with the required detail for Form 8916-A.

  • Part II Interest Income – Other Interest line allows for multiple line codes to create further detail.

  • Part III Interest Expense: Expanded detail on Form 8916-A. You must code Interest Expense lines to correspond with the required detail on Form 8916-A.

  • Part II Interest Income – Other Interest Expense allows for multiple line codes to create further detail.

Multiple Codes per Line for Supporting Whitepaper Detail

The IRS requires additional whitepaper detail for specific lines of Schedule M-3. The software populates this whitepaper detail when you assign multiple line codes to one line of Schedule M-3.

Creating Multiple Line Codes for one line of Schedule M-3

  1. Expand a row requiring multiple line codes (for example, Part II, Line 25.)

  2. Click Add and enter a code and description.


Adding a code and description for a line.


 User-defined detail line codes are only created for each “new” detail line added. The actual line item where the detail line codes exist do not have a user-defined code.

Special detail for specific company information and allocation may be required for the first group of lines on Schedule M-3 Part II. Company name, EIN, and other detail can be entered in TAS on the Schedule M-3 screens.

Additional detail for whitepaper statements can also be created with multiple M-3 Line Codes which are used to summarize lines for attached schedules.

The following Schedule M-3 lines support either special detail data entry or supporting detail setup with multiple line codes in the software.

IMPORTING SCHEDULE M-3 LINE CODES‌‌

You can set up line codes using Microsoft Excel and import them into the application. As a best practice, use the following procedure to import line codes:

  1. Export the Schedule M-3 Line Coding window to establish a .csv template.

  2. Using Microsoft Excel, open the .csv exported template and enter the user-defined line codes.



     When creating multiple codes for one line, copy the row in Excel of the line that will contain multiple codes and paste copies in between the copied row and the next row or line in the file. For example, see Part II, line 17.6 in the screen shot above.

  3. When all codes are entered, save the Microsoft Excel file as a .csv file.

  4. On the Line Coding screen, click Import to import the populated .csv file.

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



SCHEDULE M-3 LINE MAPPING‌‌

Once you establish line codes, you can begin account mapping. All income statement (TRC 30s and 40s) accounts in each chart of accounts are mapped to the user-defined Schedule M-3 line codes. When you enter the data, balances populate Forms 1120C, 1120S, 1065, and Schedule M-3 simultaneously because each account is coded with a 30s or 40s series TRC and then mapped to specific lines of Schedule M-3. Line Mapping is performed for Part II and III only.

You can map your data by either entering it manually or importing it. Schedule M-3 Line Mapping Guidelines

  • Only one Schedule M-3 Chart is allowed but you can map multiple Charts of Accounts to it.

  • Multiple Charts of Accounts are mapped to one set of common Schedule M-3 Line Codes.

  • Data can be exported, imported, and rolled over from year to year.

  • Accounts may be unassigned and moved to different line items of Schedule M-3 at any time.


MAPPING SCHEDULE M-3 LINES TO CHARTS OF ACCOUNTS:

  1. On the Income Tax menu bar, select Charts.

  2. Select Federal | Schedule M3 Line Mapping.

  3. Select the Year and Tax Return Type from the drop-down lists.



  4. Select the Chart (of Accounts) you wish to map to the Schedule M-3 codes from the drop-down list. The Federal COA (Chart of Accounts) appears in the left pane and the Schedule M-3 codes appear on the right.

  5. Click the + to expand Part II or III in the Tax Return Lines area.

  6. Check the Chart of Accounts line you wish to cross-reference to the Schedule M-3 code and click Map. You must map each Chart of Accounts you want to use to the Schedule M-3 line codes.

  7. Click Uncheck to clear any check marks.

  8. Click Add to assign an account to the Schedule M-3 code.

  9. Click Remove to unassign an account mapped to the Schedule M-3 code.

  10. Click Import or Export to enter data from .CSV files.

  11. Click Close when all mapping for all charts is done.


ACTION ITEMS FOR SCHEDULE M-3‌‌

When you open the binder, review the folder Action Items for messages regarding your Schedule M-3 Line Mapping.


Then select Show Selected Item to see the messages.



NAIC ANNUAL STATEMENT CHART‌‌

The NAIC Annual Statement Chart gives you the ability to view your accounts in the Tax Accounting System Federal Chart of Accounts grouped according to the lines of the NAIC Annual Statement within insurance binders.

The NAIC Annual Statement Line Mapping allows you to map accounts in the Federal Chart of Accounts to lines of the NAIC Annual Statement lines. The mapping chart can be rolled over.

When you use the Tax Accounting System, the process starts with setting up charts in the Home Window, then importing or entering data in the Tax Accounting System, reviewing data, and then computing the binder to transfer the data into the tax application Organizer.

 Please refer to the ONESOURCE Income Tax Insurance Returns Guide for more information.

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



STATE WORKPAPER CHARTS‌‌

State A&A and State TI Workpapers

For information about State A&A, State Factor Reconciliation, and State Taxable Income (TI) Workpaper charts see “State A&A Workpaper System” on page 343 and “State Taxable Income Workpaper System” on page 368.


PARTNERSHIP A&A AND K-1 TRANSFERS‌‌

This feature, transfers apportionment and K-1 data for a partner from the Organizer of a Partnership binder to a target binder. ONESOURCE Income Tax automates the process of transferring the K-1 information from the K-1 to an 1120, 1065, or 1120S binder.

K-1 data transfers are completed according to the K-1 data for the partner in the Partnership binder. State A&A data transfers are completed according to the A&A data in the Partnership Organizer to an 1120 binder with the partner’s ratio applied.

Steps to a Successful 1065 Partnership A&A to 1120 Corporate Transfer

  1. Map Partnership A&A fields to categories.

  2. Assign a Mapping Chart to the Partnership binder.

  3. Complete A&A data entry in the Organizer of the Partnership binder.

  4. Assign the Partnership to the Corporate binder’s Properties.

  5. Assign an A&A Logic chart and Forms Cross-Reference charts in the Corporate binder’s Properties.


MAPPING PARTNERSHIP A&A FIELDS TO CATEGORIES

  1. On the Income Tax menu bar, select Charts.

  2. Select, Partnerships | Partnership A&A Mapping.



  3. On the Chart menu bar, select Add Chart.

  4. Complete the information to create a new chart.

  5. Once you create the chart, select Edit. Map the partnership tax application A&A fields, to the TAS categories/ subcategories associated with the State Workpaper Logic Chart.

  6. Select the Tax Return section from the drop-down list:

    • Property Factor - Assets

    • Property Factor - Rents

    • Payroll Factor


    • Sales Factor

  7. Select the Tax Return Presentation from the drop-down list.



  8. Assign partnership tax application fields to categories/subcategories by dragging and dropping A&A tax fields from the left pane to the right pane of the screen. The total of the user defined group Miscellaneous Other fields available in the tax application will map to one category/subcategory field in TAS.

  9. You can also click Import to make the mapping assignments.

 You are not required to use the same chart for every partnership. Data can be transferred at a detail level for one and a summary level for another. Export charts to use as a template to create import files.

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



ASSIGNING MAPPING CHART TO THE PARTNERSHIP BINDER

  1. Select a partnership binder.

  2. Select the Properties icon.

  3. Select the Charts tab.

  4. Go to the Chart of Partnership A&A Forms Mapping box and select the appropriate chart from the drop- down list.



 Once charts have been assigned to an existing binder, they cannot be changed.


COMPLETING A&A DATA ENTRY IN ORGANIZER OF PARTNERSHIP BINDER

  1. Finish entering data on the A&A Data Entry screens in the Partnership binder’s Organizer.

  2. Close Organizer. This saves the data and makes it available for transferring it to the TAS of the target binder.

 In 2008 and earlier binders, you must perform a TAS compute with Update Organizer with Federal TAS selected in the partnership binder before transferring data to the corporate binder.


TRANSFERRING DATA TO A CORPORATE BINDER

  1. Select a corporate binder and click Properties.

  2. Select the Partnership tab.

  3. Select the partnership that has the apportionment data you want to flow to the corporate return.


     Generally, both the K-1 check box and the A&A box will be checked for each partnership.



  4. Verify that you have both the A&A Logic chart and the Forms Cross-Reference charts assigned in the binder's Properties.

  5. Perform a full recompute from TAS in the corporate binder.

  6. Review the partnership transfer to TAS in the State A&A Data Entry, Data Entry by State (with partnership detail.) workpaper.


SUCCESSFULLY TRANSFERRING K-1 DATA‌‌

Beginning with 2009 binders, K-1 data is automatically transferable from the Partnership tax application into the TAS of 1120, 1120S, and other 1065 binders. Previously, you could only transfer K-1 data to 1120 binders.

  1. Designate tax adjustment(s) that the data flows into as K-1 Transfer adjustments.

  2. Map the specific items from the K-1 into user-defined tax adjustment(s) individual accounts.

  3. Complete the K-1 data in the Organizer of the partnership binder.

  4. Assign the Partnership K-1 Mapping chart to the target binder whether it be an 1120, 1065 or 1120S binder.

  5. To assign partnership binders to a target binder, go to the Properties | Partnership tab and select the applicable partnership from a drop-down list of all partnerships. The system searches for the partner data within the partnership binder by matching the FEIN of the target binder with the FEIN of the partner, as displayed in the partnership binder.

  6. Initiate and review the K-1 Transfer data.


CREATING A CORPORATE TAX ADJUSTMENT

The first step in transferring K-1 data into 1120, 1120S, or 1065 binders is to create tax adjustment(s) in your existing Chart of Tax Adjustments to receive the K-1 data. You must do this before you map the specific items from the K-1 into individual accounts of your defined tax adjustment(s). This allows you to control the level of detail in the target return.

If you have multiple charts of accounts and adjustments you may need to identify a different journal entry for each chart, and map the K-1 amounts into individual accounts for each chart. The adjustment selection and mapping of accounts will apply to all partnerships using that K-1 Transfer chart.

  1. In a corporate binder, go to the Properties screen and select the Charts tab.

  2. Confirm that a Chart of Tax Adjustments has been selected for the binder.

  3. Open a Chart of Adjustments to create tax adjustments to receive K-1 data.

  4. Select the adjustment and click Edit.

  5. In the Special Adjustments section, check the box for K-1 Transfer. If you do not check this box, nothing appears when you open the K1 Transfer Charts List (Access | Partnership | K1 Transfer Chart List).

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



 Multiple income statement accounts and one balance sheet account is allowed per tax adjustment.



 In the target binders (1065, 1120 or1120S) all data entry is blocked from these journal entries; these adjustments are read-only.


CREATING A K-1 MAPPING CHART

  1. On the Income Tax menu bar, select Charts.

  2. Select, Partnerships | Partnership A&A Mapping.

  3. Add a chart.



     Beginning with tax year 2009, these charts are tax-return-type specific. Only charts for the binder’s tax return type are available to assign to the binder.

  4. Save the chart.

  5. Click Edit.

  6. Drag the K-1 lines from the Unassigned Partnership K-1 Tax App Fields pane to the Income Statements Accounts pane created for your K-1 adjustment. As an alternative, you can export the Partnership K-1 Tax App Fields and import the mapping assignments.



COMPLETING THE K-1 DATA IN THE ORGANIZER OF THE PARTNERSHIP BINDER

  1. Complete entering K-1 data in the Organizer of the Partnership binder.

  2. Click the Tax Form tab and review the partner’s share data.

  3. Verify that the FEIN of the corporation you are transferring matches the FEIN on the K-1.

  4. Close the Organizer. This saves the data and makes it available to transfer to the TAS of the target binder.

 In 2008 and earlier binders, you must perform a TAS compute with Update Organizer with Federal TAS selected in the partnership binder before transferring data to the corporate binder.

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



MAKING ASSIGNMENTS TO THE TARGET BINDER PROPERTIES

  1. Select the target binder.

  2. Open the Binder Properties.

  3. Click the Charts tab.

  4. Select the Tax Adjustment chart that contains the tax adjustment(s) for the K-1 transfer.

  5. Select the K-1 Mapping chart.


  6. Select the Partnership tab.

  7. Add the partnership(s) of the K-1 data you want to flow into the target binder.



INITIATING AND REVIEWING THE K-1 TRANSFER

  1. Close the Organizer.

    After the K-1 data is complete in the Organizer of the partnership binder, the system saves the data when you close the Organizer. The system searches for the partner data within the partnership binder(s) by matching the FEIN of the target binder with the FEIN of the partner, as displayed in the partnership


    binder(s).

  2. Perform a full recompute from the TAS in the target binder.

  3. Review the data transferred on the Partnership K1 Transfer Workpaper. This shows the amounts transferred from each of the partnership(s) for the target partner. There is a column for the total of each row.



  4. The amounts in the total column for the accounts are the amounts that populate the tax adjustment screens and thus, are included in the WTB and the transfer into the Organizer of the target binder.

 When transferring into 1065 and 1120S binders, if you are transferring K-1 data into accounts with activity transfer TRCs (38-xxx and 48-xxx), remember to enter the activity numbers and names on the Balances screen. This is needed so the amounts transfer to Organizer.


EXCHANGE RATES CHARTS‌‌

For income tax binders in which the local currency is something other than U.S. dollars, you must have an Exchange Rate chart. For foreign entities, the Exchange Rate chart is assigned on the binder’s Properties on the International tab. For domestic foreign tax credit entities, the chart is assigned within the binder. (This is the same process that you use for income tax binders.)

The TAS balances and adjustments are entered in local currency and translated to U.S. dollars using the rates in the Exchange Rate chart. Amounts entered in the provision data entry workpapers are entered in U.S. dollars.

 If multiple controlled foreign corporations (CFC) operate in the same country but have different year ends, separate charts of exchange rates should be established for each year end.

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



Foreign Currency Exchange Rate Charts

To use foreign currency translation in ONESOURCE Income Tax, you must create an Exchange Rate chart and assign it to the applicable binders.

  1. On the Income Tax menu bar, select Charts.

  2. Select Federal | Exchange Rates.




  3. On the menu bar, select Add Chart.



  4. Enter a name for the chart.

  5. After saving the chart, click Edit to enter or import the currency translation information. The following columns are included in these charts:

    • Country

    • Country Abbreviation

    • Currency Name

    • Currency Abbreviation

    • Beginning Rate

    • Ending Rate


    • Weighted Average Rate.



  6. Click Assign Countries to select countries where currency translation is needed. All rates unless entered or imported are assumed to be 1.0000000. You should import or enter both an ending and weighted average rate.

Assigning Exchange Rate Charts to Binders

You must assign the foreign currency exchange rate chart to the applicable binders before they are computed so the software can translate the data.

To assign these exchange rate charts to a binder:

  1. Open the binder.

  2. Go to the Currency Translation page.

  3. Select a chart from the drop-down list in the Exchange Rate Chart Assigned field. You must also select the

    Functional Currency and Local Currency before exiting the currency translation page.

  4. Click Save.

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016


CHAPTER 10: TAX ACCOUNTING SYSTEM‌‌


ONESOURCE Income Tax software is comprised of two major components. One component is the Tax Accounting System (TAS) which is used to store and adjust trial balance data from the general ledger systems. The other is Organizer, which is used to complete forms and supplemental schedules required by taxing jurisdictions. This chapter provides information about the TAS part of the software.



TAX ACCOUNTING SYSTEM OVERVIEW‌

The Tax Accounting System stores preliminary book balances. It is where you can make all necessary adjustments to arrive at tax basis balances. The balances and adjustments areas of TAS contain templates that are created when the Chart of Accounts and Chart of Adjustments are assigned to the binder. The balances and adjustment areas reflect the account numbers, account descriptions, and adjustments included in the assigned charts.

TAS is the trial balance or general ledger portion of a specific binder. In TAS, you can enter book adjustments, reclassification adjustments, and tax adjustments. You can also enter detailed information required by Schedule M-3 as well as State Workpapers, print reports, and set various processing options for returns.


TAX ACCOUNTING SYSTEM NAVIGATION TREE


MENU ITEM

DESCRIPTION

Balances

Using the assigned Chart of Accounts, the balances area allows you to view the imported trial balance data or manually enter or change data.

Adjustments

Using the assigned Chart of Adjustments, the adjustment area provides you with the ability to enter Book, Reclassification, or Tax adjustments to the trial balance data. Adjustments can be manually entered or imported.

Working Trial Balance

The Working Trial Balance (WTB) gives you a view of the trial balance data and all adjustments in a columnar format, allowing you to track the movement of data from book numbers to tax adjustments.

NAIC Annual Statement Reconciliation (Insurance only)

The views on this screen are sorted by the NAIC Annual Statement lines and display accounts according to the mapping chart you created in the Home Window.

Schedule M-3

The Schedule M-3 section allows you to review the trial balance and tax adjustment data by Schedule M-3 line. You can also enter company-by- company detail for those Part II lines which require it.

Schedule M-2

The Schedule M-2 screen allows you to enter or import data for this workpaper. The line detail of the Schedule M-2 is then transferred to Organizer to be included in the tax return.

Reports

The report section allows you to print or export various reports.

Action Items

Action items provide you with diagnostics.

Audit Trail

The Audit Trail area allows you to see changes that have been made to balances and adjustments by date and user.

1120L Insurance Workpapers (1120L only)

These workpapers allow you to group TRC data, enter data, and display calculations for reviewing. The workpaper data transfers to Organizer so that the information can be included in insurance returns (if applicable.)

Process Options

The Process Options screen gives you the ability to review and edit consolidated member’s TAS and Organizer options all in one place.

State Options

The State Options screen gives you the ability to edit or review the state options for consolidated binders. The options affect how the system handles items in your return and vary depending on the type of return. You can also select these options in the state's Organizer.

State Workpapers

The State Workpapers provide customized data entry and review workpapers for state allocation and apportionment and other components of state taxable income.

Tax Payments

Enter estimated payments amounts either manually or by importing it.

Compute/Consolidate

The compute/consolidate function incorporates any changes that have been made to the TAS data. It selectively “pushes” the TAS data to Organizer and the tax forms.

Currency Translation

The Currency Translation area allows you to change the assigned Exchange Rate charts or enter different exchange rates for both local and functional currencies.

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



ENTERING DATA IN THE TAX ACCOUNTING SYSTEM

In general, entering data in TAS involves entering preliminary book balances and then posting various adjustments to arrive at tax balances and calculated amounts. The following diagram illustrates the data entry process:



BALANCES‌‌

Entering data in TAS begins with the balances area where you enter your book balances. Your trial balance data appears with the account numbers and descriptions used in the assigned Chart of Accounts. Account balances can be entered either manually or by importing them.


MANUALLY ENTERING BALANCES

  1. From the TAS navigation tree, select Balances.



  2. Select the appropriate debit or credit field for each account and enter the balance. All balances are limited to 16 digits and entered as positive numbers.

  3. Click Save or check Always to save your entries.

 To populate reports (WTB) with preliminary balances you must perform a compute.

EDITING THE CHART OF ACCOUNTS

You can edit the Chart of Accounts through the Balances area of TAS if you have the appropriate rights.

  2. Use the command buttons to edit the Chart of Accounts.

    TRIAL BALANCE CLOSING AND ROUNDING OPTIONS‌‌

    After entering your balances, we recommend reviewing closing and rounding options for the trial balance. ONESOURCE Income Tax allows you to select these options at the enterprise level (chart level) or binder level. Closing options depend on the type of trial balance entered in TAS.

    • Open Trial Balance - This type of balance reports the retained earnings at last year’s ending balance.The retained earnings account balance does not include current-year net income or loss per books. Debits and credits of the trial balance are equal with the possible exception of nominal rounding amounts. Selecting a retained earnings account in the closing options section causes the system to calculate current-year net income and loss per books which closes the trial balance.

    • Closed Trial Balance - This type of balance includes current-year net income per books in the retained earnings account. Debits and credits differ by the amount of current-year net income or loss per books. Not selecting a retained earnings account in the closing options section prevents net income or loss from being calculated by the system.


      You can review closing options at the enterprise and entity level inside the binder by selecting Compute on the TAS menu tree and then selecting the Options tab.



      Reviewing Closing and Rounding Options

      1. On the TAS navigation tree, select Compute.

      2. Select the Options tab.

      3. Verify the closing and rounding amounts and dollar amounts.

      4. If you change the amounts, click Save.

       We do not recommend changing closing and rounding options at the binder level.


      ADJUSTMENTS‌‌

      Use the Adjustments area of the Tax Accounting System to adjust book basis balances to tax basis balances using various types of adjusting entries (book, reclass, tax). Adjustments are located after Balances on the TAS menu tree.


      ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



      A separate row appears for each type of adjustment assigned to the binder (Book, Reclass, Tax). Each row contains entries, setup at the chart level, with account numbers and descriptions. Depending on the type of adjustment you select, the system provides different features to assist you with entering, editing, and viewing adjustments.

      Adjustment Features

    • Display only adjustments with account balances - This option hides adjusting entries that have no values entered.

    • Do not show Option and Tax Return Presentation information - This option hides the Schedule M-3 presentation and the Schedule M-1 presentation information.

    • Expanding the categories:

      • Click 1 to list all adjustment numbers and descriptions for each adjustment type.



      • Click 2 to see detail for all adjustments.


• +or - Use these controls to expand or collapse individual adjustments and detail.

Editing the Chart of Adjustments in TAS

The assigned Chart of Adjustments can be edited through the Adjustments screen in TAS. You can select either:

EDIT. Edits an adjusting entry. You can add or remove accounts, change the impact of P&L tax entries, and setup automatic adjustments.

NEW. Creates a new entry that is added to the chart. Once added, all binders assigned to this particular chart can access and use the new entry.

The Adjustment screen is the same regardless of whether you edit or add the adjustment. The following example uses the Edit feature to make changes to a tax adjustment.


Once the Edit dialog box appears, the adjustment number and description as well as account numbers and descriptions can be changed with the following commands:


BUTTON

DESCRIPTION

Add

Opens the Chart of Accounts screen to add accounts to the adjusting entry.

Insert

Inserts a new account from the Chart of Accounts in the desired area of the entry.

Delete

Removes a selected account from the entry.

Auto

Sets automatic adjustment commands for the entry.


 You must have appropriate rights to add or edit the Chart of Adjustments.


EDITING TAX ADJUSTMENTS

When adding or editing tax adjustments, you must assign Schedule M-3/Provision options and the tax return presentations.

Tax Return Presentation (P&L Impact) – You must assign a 60 (or 63 or 64) (M-1) series debit and credit TRC for the correct flow of the adjustment amounts to the proper area of M-1. In the example shown above, depreciation expense accounts subject to MACRS have been coded to Debit TRC 60-510 (M-1, line 8a) for the years when MACRS depreciation is greater than book depreciation. For later years, when book depreciation is greater than tax depreciation, the system uses credit TRC 60-210 (M-1, line 5a).

  1. From the Chart of Tax Adjustments screen select a chart.

  2. Click Edit.

  3. Click New. The adjustment number is automatically assigned in sequential order as adjustments are added. You can change the system assigned number to any alphanumeric entry not already used for another journal entry.

  4. Enter a description for the tax adjustment.

  5. Click Add to add accounts (you must have a minimum of two accounts; one must be a Balance Sheet account and one an Income Statement account.)

  6. From the Accounts list, click the desired accounts (use the SHIFT and CTRL keys to select multiple accounts). To find a specific account, right-click and select Find Account from the submenu. Enter the number of the account you want to find and click Find.

  7. Click Add. Selected accounts appear in the Accounts pane.

  8. Click Close to exit the Add Account dialog and return to the Adjustment.



  9. Select the appropriate items from the following areas on the screen:

    • Options:

    • Permanent or Temporary - Refers to whether this book/tax difference is a permanent or temporary difference and will determine in which Schedule M-3 column this adjustment appears.

    • Taxable or Deductible - Refers to whether the temporary difference is deductible or taxable in future tax years.

    • Current or Non-current - Refers to whether the temporary difference will reverse entirely in the current year or whether it will require more than one year to reverse.

    • Automatic: For Charts prior to 2014.

    • Income Tax or Provision - Refers to whether this adjustment will be included in the income tax return, or the Provision, or both. The system default selects both options when a Provision binder is related to the return binder.

      ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



    • Special Adjustments:

    • K-1 Transfer - Indicates that this adjustment involves a K-1 transfer from a partnership in which the corporation is a partner.

    • 8865 K-1 Transfer - Indicates this adjustment involves a K-1 transfer for Form 8865.

    • Purchase Accounting (Meaningful for Provision only) - Designates a purchase accounting adjustment in the RTP-Current Federal screen in TAS, as well as in the Provision Cumulative Temporary Differences reports.

    • Equity/OCI (Meaningful for Provision only) - Designates adjustments that will be excluded from the provision. Permanent Equity adjustments must contain at least one balance sheet account and at least one income statement account. Temporary Equity adjustments must contain at least one Asset or Liability account and at least one Equity account and no Income Statement accounts.

    • International Transfer - Select this to utilize the automatic flow of tax adjustments from a CFC to a U.S. Shareholder.

  10. Indicate the Tax Return Presentation for Schedule M-1 for domestic returns and Form 5471, Schedule H for international returns. Choose separate Debit or Credit TRC/TCC combinations from the drop-down lists.

    The presentation TRCs determine where on the Schedule M-1 your tax adjustment amount flows. The 60- series of TRCs represent M-1 presentation for Form 1120, the 63 and 64 series of TRCs are for 1120L spe- cific tax adjustments and the 62-1xx series of TRCs represent Form 5471, Schedule H presentation.

     Please refer to the TRC List on the Product Assistance web site for a detailed list.

     If an adjustment is cross-referenced in the Tax Adjustment cross-reference chart, you cannot make changes to the permanent/temporary options, the Equity/OCI special adjustment, or delete an account unless the cross-reference is removed for that particular adjustment.

  11. Click Save or select the Always check box to continually save.

  12. Click Close. The adjustment(s) display in the list box of the Adjustment screen for the chart that you selected.

  13. You can also add adjustments by importing them.


AUTOMATIC ADJUSTMENTS‌‌

Adjusting entries within TAS can be set to automatically adjust certain items of taxable income and expense based on selected limitations or computations. Automatic calculations include the following:

  • Reverse account balances to zero

  • Adjust for differences between beginning and ending balances

  • Close net income

  • Reduce amounts by a user defined percentage.

     Adding new automatic adjustments or changing existing automatic adjustments impacts all associated entities and binders.


    Setting Automatic Adjustments

    1. Open the Adjustments screen.

    2. Expand the adjustments.

    3. Select an adjusting entry and click Edit.


    4. Select the Account radio button on the Automatic Adjustment dialog box and make the following selections:

      • Accounts: (first drop-down list) – the target journal entry account. This account comes from the journal entry.

      • Source Account (second drop-down list) – the balance for the target account used in the journal entry comes from this source account. Use the drop-down list to choose the appropriate source account.

      • Balance Type (third drop-down list) – select the balance type of the source account (for example, preliminary, book, reclassification, or tax).

      • Percentage - allows you to indicate a percent of an account to be adjusted and thus create custom calculations.

      • Reversing and Balance Options: You must select Ending, Beginning, or Difference first, and then Negate, if applicable.

      • Beginning/Ending – applies the automatic adjustment to the beginning or ending account balance. Commonly used for tax exempt income.

      • Difference – takes the difference in target and source account balances to calculate the adjustment. This is commonly used for reserve liability accounts.

      • Negate – reverses the amount in the selected target account. This is commonly used to reverse the FIT general ledger account.

     An individual account can be used in only one “account” type automatic adjustment per chart type (book, reclass, tax, and so on).The offsetting account must be marked as Balance Entry.

    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016

    WORKING TRIAL BALANCE‌‌

    Working Trial Balance (WTB) enables you to review your tax information in an accounting working trial balance format. It also displays prior year historical balances for comparison. The WTB shows the flow of the amounts on the books to the amounts on your tax return in a spreadsheet format. All the information is conveniently on one page. The tabs on the screen vary depending on the type of tax return.

    You can also view underlying levels of detail by double-clicking on a line. The Working Trial Balance information is not updated until you perform a compute from inside the binder at the Compute item on the menu or in the Home Window by selecting Tools | Batch | Compute.

    Debits and Credits

    On the Working Trial Balance, the program displays debits as positive amounts and credits as negative amounts. As a result, income appears as negative and losses and expenses appear as positive.

    Viewing Options

    There are many options for reviewing your tax information through Working Trial Balance. One option is by Tax Return Page/Schedule. Listed below are the available tabs in the WTB that correspond to each of the different tax return types.

  • Functional Currency

Consolidation binders will sum each member binder for each currency. If different local and functional currencies and different exchange rate charts are used for each member binder in the consolidation, then the WTB will only show the translated U.S. dollar amounts.

ENTERING SCHEDULE M-3 LINE DETAIL

The Schedule M-3 line detail shows the summary of accounts assigned to Schedule M-3. You can open this screen from the TAS navigation tree.

The top part of the screen shows the accounts and the balances for Columns A, B, and C of the Schedule M-3. This information comes from the balances and adjustments entered for each account.

The bottom part of the screen allows you to enter special detail, specifically for lines 1-12 of Part II: Income (Loss) items for 1120 and for lines 1-10 for 1120S and 1065 return types.

You can set up and import an Excel spreadsheet for account allocation detail lines for 1-12 of Part II for 1120 or for lines 1-10 for 1120S or 1065.

  2. Select any line from the drop-down menu.

  3. Export the Schedule M-3 Line Detail to establish a .csv template.


     Create a common template to import all Schedule M-3 Part II, Lines 1-12 fields.

  4. Using Excel, open the .csv exported template and enter the detailed information.

  5. When you have entered all your data, save the file as a .csv file.

Import.



SCHEDULE M-2‌‌

Use the Schedule M-2 workpaper to enter or import data. The line detail of the Schedule M-2 is then transferred to Organizer for inclusion on the tax return form. Import includes not only single binder import (both within and outside the binder), but also Batch import.

Batch Import functionality for Schedule M-2 is available by going to Tools | Batch | Binder Groups | Import and then selecting the Domestic tab.

  3. On the workpaper, the system populates the Beginning Balances line from the prior year binder and Net Income (loss) per books populates with the same amount as line 1 of the Working Trial Balance, Schedule M-

    1. These two fields are read-only fields. If a binder has currency assigned to it and you have not checked the box to Suppress calculation of Other Decreases (TRC 62-302) or Other Increases (62-300), Translation

    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



    Gain/Loss TCC 997, then the system also calculates currency translation gain/loss and displays it as a read- only field.

  4. Enter amounts for other lines either manually or by importing them.

    • In consolidated subgroup binders, the workpaper is read-only and displays member detail in columns in addition to a consolidated column.

    • In partnership binders, date fields are available for TRCs 62-304, 62-305, 62-306, and 62-308.

    REPORTS‌‌

    The Reports area of TAS provides many system reports that support the Federal and State tax preparation process. The Reports screen is divided into Administrative and Federal report types.



    Administrative Reports contain information about a binder’s charts. Balance Sheet Accounts and Income and Deduction Account reports are also included in this type of report.

    Federal Reports provide information about the data entered in the Tax Accounting System. These reports are printed from within the binder and pertain only to the contents of that particular binder. The following are examples of federal reports:

    • Tax Basis Balance Sheet Reports

    • Adjustment Reports (Current Period and Comparative)

    • Schedule M-3 Reports

      Each type of report has folders that categorize available system reports. Once a report is generated it can be printed or exported.


      GENERATING REPORTS

      1. On the TAS navigation menu, select Reports. By default, the report screen opens the Administrative tab. It then defaults to the last tab you used.

      2. Select Open in a separate window or Batch Print (optional).

        • Select the Open in separate window check box to open the report in an additional browser window.

        • Select the Batch Print check box if you want to print multiple reports in one print request. When you select this check box, the program enables the Print Batch button and allows you click on the reports you want to include in the batch. When you select a report, a check mark appears on that report to indicate that you have chosen to include that report in the batch print. Click Print Batch when you are ready to print your selections.

      3. To generate a single report in a print preview window, single-click the desired report.


      4. Use the arrows on the report toolbar to scroll through the report. Select the magnifying-glass drop-down to zoom the view of the report.

      5. Click the Print icon to print the report. The report can be printed to either a printer or a .PDF file.

      6. Use the search field to search for specific adjustment numbers, account numbers, values, or words within the generated report.


         Detailed reports display only the accounts with balances. Accounts with zero balances are automatically suppressed.

      7. Select Export to save the file in .pdf format. On the Export to PDF dialog box, select Export to export the report with the default name and directory.

      8. Or, select Browse and choose a directory destination.

      9. Enter a report name.

      10. Click Export.

        ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



         Reports can only be exported to .pdf (Adobe Acrobat) format.

      11. If you have licensed the ONESOURCE WorkFlow Manager application, you also have the option to send the report to FileRoom.

    • If the TAS option Update Organizer with OSA and in Organizer, Consolidated Return | State to Combine | Allocation and Apportionment are both selected

    • If the Division entity type in the Organizer is not a Parent or Division

  3. Perform analysis and generate Action Items based on the following rules for all binders:

    • If in TAS the return type is not the same as the return type in Organizer.

AUDIT TRAIL‌‌

The Audit Trail allows you to define a search for information about user changes made to preliminary balances, adjustments or Schedule M-2.

The current binder information automatically populates the fields on the top of the screen. Then you enter the criteria for the query. Click Run Query and the bottom half of the screen lists Before Change and After Change debits and credits. The Audit Trail also shows which user changed the preliminary balance, adjustment, or Schedule M-2 data and when it was changed.


USING AUDIT TRAIL

  1. In a binder, on the TAS navigation tree, select Audit Trail.


  2. To search and view changes:


    • Enter the Date Range or leave blank to view for all dates.

    • Select a user from the User Name drop-down list.

    • Select the Data Type, Preliminary Balances, Adjustments or Schedule M-2.

    • If the Adjustments Data Type is selected, then check each desired Adjustment Type: Book, Reclass, Tax, AMT, ACE.

    • Click Run Query. A list of the balances, adjustments fitting your criteria appears.

  3. Click Close to exit.

    On this screen you can also:

    • Click Export to export viewed information as a .csv file.

    • Click Print to print viewed information.

       The Audit Trail shows user changes only.


      1120L INSURANCE WORKPAPERS‌‌

The workpapers allow you to view group TRC data for form lines, enter data, and display calculations for reviewing. The workpaper data transfers to Organizer so that the information is included in the insurance return and applicable tax forms.



      The insurance workpapers are:

    • Schedule F Increase (Decrease) in Reserves

    • Schedule G Policy Acquisition Expenses

    • Prior Year DAC

      The workpapers are available beginning in tax year 2011.

      For more information, please refer to the Setting Up Your Insurance Return Guide located on the Customer Center website.

      PROCESS OPTIONS‌‌

      Use the Process Options screen to review and edit consolidated members’ Tax Accounting System and Organizer options.

      You can review and edit the options all on one screen instead of opening each member’s binder to make changes and must be an Administrator. If you are a non-Administrator, you can only view the options. The options transfer from the Process Options screen to a binder or transfer back to the Process Options screen.

      Administrators must have Edit Federal or Edit State permissions to modify the options.


      USING PROCESS OPTIONS FOR CONSOLIDATIONS

      1. Open a Top Consolidation, Sub Consolidation or Divisional Consolidation for 1120, 1120S, 1120PC, 1120L, 1120REIT, 1120RIC, or 1065 binder.

      2. On the TAS navigation menu, select Process Options. The consolidation member company binders appear in rows on the screen.





      3. To edit Process Options, in the Tax Accounting System section, check or uncheck the appropriate option for:

        • Update Organizer With, or

        • What to Consolidate

      4. Click Save. The system transfers the settings to the associated binder(s).

         The Update Organizer With options only display if you have assigned charts to the binder.



      5. In the Organizer section, double-click on a field and select an option from the drop-down list.



         If you select Combine or Add for a jurisdiction in the Organize, and then change the setting to None in Process Options, the jurisdiction is hidden in the Organizer, not deleted. If you reset the jurisdiction to Combine or Add the data will re-appear. You must be in Organizer to delete a state and its data.

      6. Once you select the options, click Save.

      7. To transfer the settings to Organizer, perform a TAS compute or open the member's Organizer.

      8. If you change something and do not click Save, you will get a message, "Are you sure you want to navigate away from this page?" If you do, any unsaved data will be lost. Click OK to continue or Cancel to stay on the current screen.

      9. Refresh the Process Options screen to view the latest changes from the consolidated members binders' TAS or Organizer fields. You can refresh the screen by clicking the Process Options screen again.


      PROCESS OPTIONS TOOLBAR

    • When Save is bold, it means you have changed something on the Process Options screen. Click Save to keep the TAS and Organizer option settings. This updates the TAS database.

    • Click Export to save the Process Options settings to an Excel file. When the save file dialog box opens, enter a file name, a location to save the file Excel (*.xlsx) and click Save.

    • To set an option consistently for all members, make the selection for the first applicable company binder and then, with your cursor residing on the field, click Copy Down. This populates all the fields below the activated field with the same data.

    • Click Jurisdictions to open a screen that lists all the available jurisdictions. Only the selected jurisdictions display on the Process Options screen.

    • The jurisdiction filter is user specific. Once you have selected the desired jurisdictions to view, the filter will apply to all binders for that user.

    • Click Search and enter alpha and numeric characters to search for Entity Name and Entity Numbers. (The consolidating entity displays in addition to the member entity.)

    • Click Close to exit the screen.

      SELECTING PROCESS OPTIONS AS A BATCH ACTIVITY

      Beginning in 2013, you can access Process Options as one of the activities on the Batch - Binder Group

      screen on the Tools menu.

      1. Follow the process to create a Binder Group.

      2. In Step 2 - Choose Activity, select Process Options.

      3. If the binder group includes multiple binders for one entity, Process Options will appear gray, not active, as indicated by a tooltip.

         Notes:

        • In Batch, Process Options is based on the members in the Binder Group and is not limited to the consolidation and its members. This allows flexibility for the User.

        • A group can be comprised of any type of return.

        • When a Binder Group includes 1120 and 1065 return types, you must select 1120 or 1065 from the

      Return Type drop-down list in the top menu to view the desired return type.

      Important: The jurisdiction filter settings are User specific. If jurisdictions have been filtered in consolidated binders at the Home screen, this filter will apply for the binder group. Similarly, if the jurisdictions are filtered in a binder group this will affect the display in the consolidated TAS screen.


      STATE OPTIONS‌‌

      Use this screen to review state options for consolidated binders.

      Use the State Options screen on the Tax Accounting System menu to edit or review the state options for consolidated binders. The options affect how the system handles items in your return and vary depending on the type of return. You can also select these options in the state's Organizer.


      OPENING THE STATE OPTIONS SCREEN

      1. Open a consolidation binder.

      2. On the TAS navigation menu, select State Options. The consolidation member company binders appear in rows on the workpaper and the state options appear as column headings.

      3. Select the applicable Jurisdiction and the system displays the data. You can use this screen to make sure your consolidation member company binders are set with consistent state options.

      4. To set an option consistently for all companies, make the selection for the first applicable company binder.

      5. Then right-click and select Autofill Column. The entry will be applied to all company binders for that option.

      6. You can also quickly remove or change an option for all companies with the same Autofill Column

        command.

      7. After making your selections for a state, select Update Organizer to apply the options to each of the selected company binders.

      8. To export the Process Options, click Export. You can either export to an Excel workbook (*.XML) or Excel 97-2003 (*.XLS) format. The XML format can be used for viewing in Excel 2007.


      SETTING STATE OPTIONS FOR SEPARATE BINDERS

      You can also use the State Options feature to set options consistently for binders that are not a part of a unitary or combined group.

      1. In the Home Window, go to Tools | States | State Options.

      2. Select the binder Year, Tax Return Type and each Jurisdiction. This controls the list of binders which are displayed.

      3. After making these selections, select Load and then edit or review the options.

    • Consolidation Options

    • Force Print

    • Suppress Print


      TIPS

    • The options for each state vary. Some categories may not be applicable for some states. To see the options for each state, go to the Organizer on the Return Options screens.

    • The State Options workpaper contains additional capabilities, such as a “hover” feature which allows you to see the category each option is categorized under even as the label fades. This is helpful when using the Force and Suppress Print options.

    • Use the column Sort and Filter options to see which company rows to isolate.

    • For Date options, use the calendar to select a date or simply enter the date. You do not have to enter slashes; the workpaper formats them automatically.

    • If you change any state options inside Organizer, the changes will automatically display on the State Options workpaper(s).

       In 2009 binders, eight states are available for this feature, California, Illinois, Kansas, Massachusetts, Minnesota, South Carolina, Texas, and Virginia. In 2010 binders, 47 states are available.
