INCOME AND DEDUCTIONS

The Income and Deductions folder contains several review and data entry screens. Much of the financial information in these screens is automatically populated from TAS. To complete supplemental forms and schedules such as Schedule E Officers’ Compensation and 4562 Depreciation Overrides, enter data in this area.

Entering Officer Information

  1. Navigate to Organizer | Income and Deductions | Deductions | Officers’ Compensation | Individual Officers.

  2. Double-click * Add new officer.



  3. Enter the officer’s name and click OK. The software creates a system form for the new officer that is stored in the Forms List window. Detail information of the officer can be added in the Forms window.

  4. Repeat the process until all officers’ information has been entered.


     Selections which flow individual officer information to Federal, all applicable states, and/or selected applicable states can be made on each officers’ system form under Compensation of Officers – Application and Compensation of Officers – Information for States sections. On-screen instructions provide information as to where the officer information carries based on these selections.

    Entering Information for Form 4562

    Tax balances transfer from TAS to populate the Deductions Detail and Cost of Goods Sold/Cost of Operations screens of Organizer. The sum of the values from these screens represent the binder’s total depreciation and amortization expense which must be recorded on Form 4562 in order for the binder to be in balance.

    Organizer provides the following ways to enter depreciation data on Form 4562:

    • Asset Detail – Enter information on an asset-by-asset basis letting the software calculate depreciation expense that populates Form 4562. We do not recommend using this method when entering data for large numbers of assets.

    • 4562 Overrides – Enter depreciation expense calculated from a depreciation system external to the software directly on Form 4562.

       Do not enter information in both the Asset Detail and 4562 Override areas of a binder.

       For a consolidated group, use a consistent method when populating depreciation. (i.e. all members of the consolidated group use 4562 overrides). 4562 Overrides is the most commonly used method and is discussed in the next section.


      ENTERING SUMMARY DEPRECIATION INFORMATION USING THE 4562 OVERRIDES SCREEN

      1. Navigate within Organizer to Income and Deductions | Deductions | Depreciation and Amortization | General Depreciation and Amortization | Form 4562 Information | 4562 Overrides.


        ONESOURCE 2016



      2. Enter appropriate data in the Basis for Depreciation, Recovery Period, Convention, Method, and

        Current Year Depreciation fields.

      3. Enter the total tax depreciation in the MACRS deduction for assets placed in service during prior years field (include Schedule A, Cost of Goods Sold amounts).

      4. Detail for amortization balances flowing from TAS must be entered in the Amortization - Activity Form 4562 (Overrides) section.

      Summary amortization expense is entered in the following fields:

    • Amortization of costs that begins during the current tax year.

    • Amortization of costs that began during prior tax years.

       The return will be out of balance if amounts for 4562 Depreciation and Amortization do not equal amounts transferred from TAS.

      Deduction Detail Options

      The Deductions Detail screen lists five options used to customize deduction calculations. In Organizer, double- click Income and Deductions | Deductions | Detail.



      The following options appear as check boxes in the detail screen. Scroll through the screen to find the following available options:

    • Suppress the automatic reduction of wages for job credits. If not checked, the software deducts the amount of the credits from salaries and wages and cost of goods sold, if applicable. Calculated amounts carry to Schedule M-1, line 5c - Other.

    • Compute the contributions limitation based on line 28 taxable income. If checked, the software disregards NOLs and calculates contribution limitations based on line 28, Taxable Income before NOL and Special Deductions.

    • Do not check this for subsidiaries that consolidate into a top consolidation. All limitations will be calculated on a consolidated basis.

    • Depreciation balance to page 1….(Override). If checked, the populated number overrides calculated depreciation or depreciation flowing from TAS to populate page 1.

    • Meals and entertainment….(Is this a net amount?). If checked, the software treats amounts coded to meals and entertainment as net amounts and does not apply the 50% limitation. This balance will carry to M- 1, line 5b.


    • Do not check this for subsidiaries that consolidate into a top consolidation. All limitations will be calculated on a consolidated basis.

    • Unlimited NOL computations (for members of consolidations: NOL carryforwards only). If checked, NOL carryforward deductions are not limited for members of consolidations allowing 100% of the member NOLs carryover to appear on page 1, line 29a.

       When using the Computed Adjustment in TAS, it is not necessary to check the Meals and Entertainment check box in Organizer.


      GAINS AND LOSSES

      Tax basis balances for asset gains and losses transfer from TAS to populate the Income Summary screen of Organizer.



      Individual sales of assets must be further defined in Organizer on Form 4797 and Schedule D in order for these supplementary schedules to balance to the 1120 tax return. The following types of sales are recorded in Organizer:

    • Form 4797 - Sales of Business Property

    • Sch. D - Capital Gain/Loss

    • Form 6252 - Installment Sales

    • Form 8824 - Like-Kind Exchanges

    • Form 4684 - Casualty and Theft Losses

    • Sec. 1265 - Contracts and Straddles

ONESOURCE 2016



Form 4797 and Schedule D are covered on the following pages. Entering General Gain/Loss Information for the Sales of Assets

  1. Navigate to Gains and Losses | Disposition of Property | Disposition Detail | Create Dispositions of Property.



  2. Enter a Description of property (Mandatory) in the pop-up box and click OK.

  3. Select Disposition Type and Type of Property (Mandatory).

     When entering net loss detail select Section 1231.

  4. Enter eight-digit dates in the Date acquired and Date sold fields and a Bulk Sale Identifier, if used, for the system to calculate the gain or loss based on entries in the Computation of Gain (Loss) section.

     If dates are not known and/or assets should be grouped, use: Date acquired: 07/01/2009, Date Sold: 12/31/2009 for Short Term assets Date acquired: 01/01/2008, Date Sold: 12/31/2009 for Long Term assets Date Sold must be within the fiscal or calendar year of the binder.

  5. Navigate to Gains and Losses | Dispositions of Property | Disposition Detail | Sales of Business Property to enter the remaining detail for the sale.

  6. Enter the sales price, other sale information such as expenses related to the sale, depreciation recapture information and built in gains information (for S-corps).

 Amounts entered in the Gain (Loss), if no detail is entered, field override the system calculations. To maintain consistent levels of data entry for consolidation purposes, either all companies with gains/losses must use this field or none of them can use it.


Entering Capital Gains and Losses Detail (Sch D)

  1. Navigate to Gains and Losses | Capital Gains and Losses | Capital Assets Sale Detail.

  2. Double-click * Add new Capital Asset Sale Detail.




  3. Enter the Description of property in the pop-up box (Mandatory).

  4. Enter eight-digit dates in the Acquired and Sold fields for the software to calculate the gain or loss based on entries in the Computation of Gain (Loss) section. If dates are entered, select Calculated based on dates in the Holding Period section.

     If dates are not known and/or assets should be grouped, use: Acquired: 07/01/2009, Sold: 12/31/2009 for Short-Term assets or Acquired: 01/01/2008, Sold: 12/31/2009 for Long-Term assets.

  5. If no dates are entered, select the applicable Holding Period and check the Date Alternatives to indicate

    various for print and e-filing purposes.

     The Date Sold must be within the fiscal or calendar year of the binder.

  6. Enter amounts for Gross sale price and Cost or other basis for the system to calculate the gain/loss on this asset.

  7. If only net gain or loss is known, enter the net loss amount in Cost or other basis and net gain in Gross sales price.

  8. Populate dates in the Print Only fields.

  9. Select the Property Type in the Holding Period section to keep the system from calculating gain or loss.

     For a consolidated group, a consistent method must be used when populating capital gains. (i.e. all members of the consolidated group record capital assets individually). Do not use gain/loss summary overrides and individual asset entry together.

  10. For Schedule M-3 purposes, if the gain/loss generates from a flow-through entity, an abandonment loss, or worthless stock, make this designation in the Schedule M-3 Classifications section.

  11. Fields are provided for the corporation to enter the required statement for Basis Used Other Than the Actual Cost of the Property and Postponed Gain Statement for SSBIC Election.

ONESOURCE 2016



Entering Capital Carryovers

  1. Navigate to Capital Gains and Losses | Capital Gains and Losses | Other Information.




  2. Enter the Capital Loss amounts in the Amount Available column.

The Parent or Subsidiary Utilization column is not required, however, you may manually enter the capital loss used in the consolidation so the net amount will roll into next year’s binder.


ENTERING CAPITAL GAINS AND LOSSES SUMMARY

Use the Summary Overrides screen to record capital gains at a summary level, i.e. no detail is entered. Navigate to Gains and Losses | Compute and Print Options | Summary Overrdies.

 For a consolidated group, a consistent method must be used when populating capital gains. (i.e. all members of the consolidated group record capital assets individually). Do not use gain/loss summary overrides and individual asset entry together.


BALANCE SHEET/M1-M2-M3

Organizer's Balance Sheet/M1-M2-M3 group topic displays fields found on Schedule L, M-1, M2, and M-3 of the tax return. The majority of this information is transferred from TAS through the mapping of TRC codes to account balances. Each sub-topic of Balance Sheet/M1-M2-M3 has options and overrides that further define amounts and calculations in Organizer.

 Amounts associated with TRCs are populated from TAS and should only be reviewed in Organizer. Amounts entered in TRC Organizer fields are automatically replaced with TAS amounts when you perform a Full Recompute.

Balance Sheet Options

Tabs (Assets, Liabilities, etc) separate each section of Schedule L in the Balance Sheet sub-topic of Organizer. Navigate to Balance Sheet/M1-M2-M3 | Balance Sheet to review data transferred from TAS. The following options are available:

1120:

  • Automatically compute ending unappropriated retained earnings.



1065:

  • Do Not have the system automatically compute ending unappropriated retained earnings. The system forces the balance sheet to balance by “plugging” the ending retained earnings amount.

  • Additional accrual options for Depreciation, Amortization, etc. can be selected on the Accrual Options tab.


  • Sch L Compute Options tab contains options related to depreciation, depletion, and amortization.

  • Options related to the allocation of liabilities are on the Liabilities Alloc tab.


RECONCILIATION (M-1)

Calculation and override options may be set for Form 1120, Schedule M-1 in Organizer. Navigate to Balance Sheet/M1-M2-M3 | Schedule M1/M2 to set options and/or review data transferred from TAS.



Review M-1 fields in Organizer to verify entries flowing from adjusting tax entries made in TAS. Make reconciliation changes in the Tax Adjustments area of TAS and perform a Full Recompute to update Organizer.

The following fields in the M-1 Organizer are not updated by the TAS:

  • Passive Loss Adjustment (Credit) - Enter an amount if you are not using Form 8810, Passive Loss Limitation.

  • Bad Dept Reserve Recapture (Credit) - Enter an amount if not selecting an option on the Accrual Options tab of the Balance Sheet topic.

  • Passive Loss Adjustment (Debit) - Enter an amount if not using Form 8810, Passive Loss Limitation.

  • Prior year passive loss absorbed (Debit) - Enter prior year passive loss absorbed.

     Amounts associated with TRCs are populated from TAS and should only be reviewed in the Organizer. Entered amounts in TRC Organizer fields are automatically replaced with the TAS data when performing a Full Recompute.

    Net Income Per Books

    The software automatically posts the net income per books to the Organizer if the following is done:

    1. Select a Chart of Book Adjustments.

    2. Select rounding options.

    3. Select a retained earnings account as the close account on the compute options feature.

    4. Maker sure the return has current year profit or loss activity.

    5. Complete a full-compute of the return.

    6. Make sure TAS balances, debits, and credits are equal.

    ONESOURCE 2016



    RETAINED EARNINGS(M-2)

    Schedule M-2 adjusting entries in Organizer are one-sided entries (the balancing entry is reflected during consolidation.) Because TAS requires two-sided entries, Schedule M-2 adjustments can only be entered in Organizer.

    Form 1120:

    1. Navigate to Balance Sheet/M1-M2-M3 | Schedule M1-M2.

    2. Select the Ret. Earnings (M-2) tab to make M-2 entries.

    3. The following fields are automatically populated on the Ret. Earnings (M-2) tab:

      • Retained earnings at the beginning of the year - previous years' amount rolls over to the current year binder.

      • Net income per books - flows from M-1, line 1.

      • Bad debt deduction - flows from bad debt calculations based on selections made on the Accrual Options tab of the Balance Sheet sub-topic in Organizer.

     All other fields must be manually entered.

    Form 1065:

    1. Navigate to Balance Sheet and Reconciliation | Sch M-2.

    2. Enter all necessary detail on each of the tabs.


    ORGANIZER COMPUTES‌‌

    A return must be computed for data to flow from Organizer to Tax Forms and associated schedules. The following computes are available:

  • Auto Compute. Computes Organizer data as it is entered allowing the population of related Organizer fields as well as tax forms and schedules. Turning off Auto Compute can speed up some data entry in Organizer.

  • To turn off/on Auto Compute, from the Options menu, select Auto Compute.

  • Full Recompute. Computes all Organizer data. Each binder must have a Full Recompute performed before the consolidation can occur.

  • To perform a Full Recompute, from the File menu, select Full Recompute.

  • TAS | Compute. Computes all data beginning with TAS and continuing through the Organizer. Each binder must be computed before the consolidation can occur.

    To perform a compute, select Compute on the TAS Compute dialog box.

     If changes are made in TAS, you must close the Organizer before performing the compute so the data properly flows into the Organizer.

     Entered amounts in the TRC Organizer fields are automatically replaced with TAS data when performing a Full Recompute.


    TAX FORMS‌‌

    The Tax Forms area of a binder shows forms and schedules that resemble actual federal and state government forms. The Tax Forms tab is arranged by levels of government (Federal, State, City). Lines appearing on a tax form are displayed along with calculated dollar amounts.

    Tax Forms should only be used for review purposes after information is added within TAS and Organizer. The following places and tools can be used to review and help finalize tax returns before printing:

  • Tax Summary

  • Hyperlinks

  • Diagnostics & Overrides.

 The Tax Forms area should not be used for data entry. Changes made in the Tax Forms area are considered overrides and DO NOT carry back to Organizer or TAS.


Reviewing the Tax Return

The system offers several ways to review the tax return.


TAX SUMMARY

The Tax Summary provides a reconciliation of Income, Balance Sheet, and Retained Earnings amounts. Differences, if any, are noted on this screen.



If differences exist in Income or Retained Earnings, it generally means that detail information (Form 4797, 4562) is missing. Differences in the Balance Sheet area usually mean that closing options have not been set in TAS.


DRILL - DOWN ARROWS

Blue curved arrows beside fields within the Tax Forms represent direct hyperlinks to the source of the field's data. Usually, these arrows drill back to a yellow workpaper or grey Organizer screen.


To use the drill-down feature, either double-click the blue arrow or the appropriate field.

ONESOURCE 2016



HYPERLINKS

Hyperlinks are built-in short-cuts that show how data flows in an individual field from related forms and workpapers in the Organizer and TAS. To use hyperlinks, select a field and right-click the mouse. Select Related from the pop-up menu list.



The dialog box above shows the Related or Hyperlinked areas to line 9, Net gain or (loss) from Form 4797. To navigate to the source data simply double-click the desired field in the Related dialog box.


WORKPAPERS

Workpapers are screens that display supporting calculations and totals appearing on the tax return.



The workpaper displays the categories that make up line 26, Other Deductions. Hyperlink arrows on yellow workpaper screens drill back to the appropriate data entry point in Organizer.

 Do not use workpapers for data entry. Amounts associated with TRCs are populated from TAS and should only be reviewed in Workpaper screens. Entered amounts in TRC Workpaper fields are automatically replaced with TAS data when performing a Full Recompute.


Overrides

The data flow from Organizer can be interrupted by manually overriding data directly on the Tax Form and workpaper fields. When completing the parent and subsidiary returns, many times users override information to force the return to balance. These types of overrides give the consolidation process confusing messages about what level of data entry to combine (for example, Organizer data vs. Tax Form overrides).

 Do not use Tax Forms for data entry. Changes made in the Tax Forms area DO NOT carry back to Organizer or TAS. Entered amounts in the Tax Forms fields are automatically replaced with TAS data when performing a Full Recompute

Different types of overriding data on the Tax Forms area of a binder causes a “snowflake” to appear beside the field. The system applies two different types of snowflakes to tax form fields:


Red – indicates the computed data and manual override do not agree.


Blue – indicates the computed data and override agree.

 Overriding at the workpaper level only generates a red or blue snowflake at the workpaper (yellow screen) level, but the snowflakes will not appear on the Tax Form.

 We strongly recommend that you clear Tax Form overrides before consolidating the return.

The consistent level of detail rule dictates that, if overrides are entered in the same field across all entities in the consolidated group, the field should consolidate.


STATE AND CITY RETURNS‌‌

The majority of data for the state/city returns flows from the federal return once the state/city returns have been activated.

Activating States/Cities in Organizer

Individual states and city folders do not appear in the State Organizer unless they are activated. This makes navigation easier. Use the following steps to activate states/cities in Organizer:

  1. From Organizer, click the States folder, then Add/Delete | States and Cities.

  2. The following options are available on the State Organizer Add/Delete topic for Individual States and Allocation and Apportionment.


    ONESOURCE 2016



    • Add. Activates the State, City, or Allocation and Apportionment areas of Organizer. States and Cities will only appear in State Organizer once they have been “Added”. Activating allocation and apportionment (A&A) triggers the A&A area in Organizer which is used in each state to calculate A&A.

    • Delete. Deletes are entered and rolled over information for selected States, Cities, or the entire Allocation and Apportionment area.

       Use this function with care. If you delete a return, you also delete all the information for that return. Everything you entered for that return will be lost. Once chosen, all data for the deleted state or city disappears permanently.

    • Blank. Leaves entered and rolled over information for selected States, Cities, or the entire Allocation and Apportionment area, but removes individual states and cities from the State Organizer navigation tree. Allocation and Apportionment will always appear in the State Organizer.

  3. Select the appropriate radio button for individual states, cities, or the Allocation and Apportionment area of the State Organizer.

 After making Add, Delete, or Blank selection, press the Enter key to initialize the selected items.

States can be activated in multiple binders simultaneously by using the Enterprise Control Panel. (You must be an Administrator to use this feature. Refer to “CHAPTER 8: Tools” on page 107 for more information.)

 Read the note at the top of the screen before making changes. Your state/city will be displayed when the Add option is selected. Marking Delete erases all information. Keep in mind that adding a state/city will not make it consolidate.

For more information about state consolidations and combined/consolidated returns in Organizer, refer to “The State Consolidation Process” on page 392.


COMMON STATE‌‌

The Common State area of Organizer is helpful when a company is compliant in multiple states. The organization of the Common State area allows a more efficient method of data entry for multiple items. If the Common State area is utilized for the data entry on a particular entity, then in order to keep the levels of data entry consistent, the Common State area should be used for data entry on the parent and subsidiaries in that consolidated group.

You must do this in order to process extension requests and applications for selected states. The steps for this are:

  • activate states

  • input basic company information overrides

  • input miscellaneous information

  • enter state identification numbers

  • enter tentative tax amounts, prior year overpayments

  • states/cities requiring special input

  • compute

  • printing extension forms

  • output.

Data entered on this screen overrides entries made on the federal return and flows to each activated state and city.

Entering General Information in the Federal Return

  1. Open the General Information folder.

  2. Complete the information requested under all applicable topics in the folder. If your state general information is generally the same as your federal return, we recommend you enter all general information at the federal level to minimize required data entry.

  3. To override general information for a specific state but not all states, you must access each state individually and enter the override information. To access general information for each state, click the desired state folder and General Information. Enter the applicable override information for that state.


FILING STATUS AND ENTITY TYPE‌‌

Use the Filing Status and Entity Type Organizer to enter state return filing status and entity type for each state. The default is the same as it is for federal returns.

  1. Navigate to Common State | General Information | Return Type/Entity Type.

  2. For each applicable state, select the filing status, C Corporation, S Corporation, or same as federal.

  3. For each applicable state, select the entity type:

    • If the entity is a member of a consolidation, select Subsidiary.

    • If the entity is a parent of a consolidation, select Parent company.

    • If the entity is a tax paying entity, select Single company.


ESTIMATED TAX OPTIONS‌‌

Each state’s Organizer has an estimated tax area. Use the [Name of State] Estimated Tax Organizer to override the data entered on the Common State screen thereby setting the default estimated tax calculation for all states and overrides for individual states.

The system suppresses the estimated tax computation if the computed tax liability is less than the minimum amount specified by the state. The system can also print vouchers if payments are due, round the estimates, and calculate installment payment amounts.

Entering Estimated Tax

  1. Navigate to States | Common State | Tax Estimate Options | Estimated Tax tab.



  2. Select the applicable options as follows:

    • Calculate estimate even if less than the minimum.

    • Pay entire amount of estimate, net of any overpayment, as the first installment.

    • Suppress the print of vouchers if no payments are due.

      ONESOURCE 2016



    • Alphabetic information only for all states

  3. Various print options are available for the vouchers.


  4. Check the Only print vouchers with amounts check box to suppress all vouchers without amounts. If you enter None in the voucher the system will still print it when using this check box.

  5. Select the appropriate Estimated Tax Rounding Options if you wish to change the default value.

  6. Check the 1st quarter, 2nd quarter, 3rd quarter, and 4th quarter check boxes to print vouchers for those specific quarters.

  7. Select the Estimated Tax Payments tab to enter the Installment Payments in Next Year’s Estimated Tax

for applicable states.


OVERPAYMENT OPTIONS

Use this screen to set the default application of overpayment options for all states and overrides for individual states.

  1. Navigate to States | Common State | Tax Estimate Options | Overpayment tab.

  2. Select the default option for application of overpayment.

  3. Click the applicable button to set any overpayment option overrides for individual states or cities.



UNDERPAYMENT OPTIONS

Use the Underpayment Options screen to set the underpayment of estimated tax penalty for individual states. There is no default option since the methods for computing the penalty vary from state to state.

  1. Navigate to States | Common State | Tax Estimate Options | Underpayment tab.




  2. Click the applicable button to select the underpayment options in an individual state or city organizer.


    NET OPERATING LOSS (NOL)‌‌

    Each state has a Net Operating Loss Organizer. This screen allows data entry for:

    • the original NOL amount

    • the amount utilized in prior years

    • the amount used in the current year

    • the carryover to next year.


      ONESOURCE 2016



      The NOL deduction will be limited in accordance with state law.


      ALLOCATION AND APPORTIONMENT IN ORGANIZER‌‌

      The recommended method for allocation and apportionment is to use TAS. (Refer to “State Workpapers” on page 211.) However, if you want to manually enter allocation and apportionment data you can use Organizer.



      Entering A&A in Organizer

      1. Navigate to Organizer | States | Allocation and Apportionment | A&A Data Entry.

      2. Enter all necessary data in the Allocation, Property, Payroll, and Sales screens.

         The software uses system defined logic to calculate A&A for each state. Customized logic can be implemented by using TAS. (See “State Workpapers” on page 211.)

      3. To review your factors, go to Tax Forms | States | Allocation and Apportionment | A&A Factor Review

      screens.


      A&A OPTIONS

      Various A&A options are available under Organizer | Allocation and Apportionment | A&A Options.

    • Weights. The default factor weights are shown for each state. You can override these on the screen.

    • Nexus Suppression. Use these check boxes to indicate if no nexus exists for a particular state or city. Use the feature if a company does not have a business presence in a particular state, but the state must be activated on the return so the company will be included in a combined report.

    • Deactivate State A&A. Use these check boxes to indicate the states which you wish to suppress A&A. This prevents all A&A details from flowing to the state tax return.

    • Change State Defaults. The apportionment ratio for states and cities with no A&A activity defaults to 100%. This selection will change the default apportionment ratio to None and result in no apportionable income.

    • Partnership Categories. Select states and cities where you would like information entered on the Data Entry screens for partnership business income (i.e. partnership property, partnership payroll, and partnership sales) to flow to that state tax return.

    • Threshold Variance. This field allows you to enter a threshold variance for the apportionment variances shown on the A&A Factor Review Comparison report. If the variance is greater than the percentage entered here, the software will generate an informational diagnostic.


    • Prior Year Amounts. These fields will show your prior year apportionment and allocation factors. This information is used on a Prior Year/Current Year Comparison report that can be printed for review.

    • Optional Method. Various state specific options are listed in this section. Selecting any options in this section will flow to the individual state.

    • Miscellaneous Items. Non-standard apportionment data should be entered in this section. Each state is listed separately.

    • Print Options. Various A&A print options are available on this screen.

      ONESOURCE 2016



      STATE ADJUSTMENTS‌‌

      The majority of the state return flows in from the federal return, however, you must enter the state adjustments. We recommend using the State TI Workpapers in TAS to enter state adjustments (refer to “State Taxable Income Workpaper System” on page 368) however, you can also enter adjustments manually.

      Use the States | [Name of State] | State Adjustments screens to enter the state specific modifications. Many of the adjustments are generated automatically by the software based on data entry from the federal return, such as, state and local income taxes.

      Reviewing State Returns

      Once you have completed entering the data for the state return, go to View | Diagnostics to review any open items that may require your attention. See Chapter 8: State Consolidations, regarding state consolidations for filing state combined/consolidated returns.


      EFILE REVIEW‌‌

      Business returns and extensions are transmitted to the IRS as XML files. Reviewing the actual XML file confirms the accuracy of the return or extension e-file that is sent to the IRS. There are two ways to review the XML file, the EFile Reviewer in the software or viewing the XML file with Internet Explorer or a text editor.

      The EFile Review function gives you the ability to view, print, and save the electronic data file you created in PDF format. The system converts your XML file into a PDF in a grid format to make it easier for you to review the return.

      Viewing, Printing, and Saving the EFile Review File

      1. Successfully generate an e-file XML in the Organizer.



      2. In the binder, on the navigation tree, click Tax Return | EFile Review.

      3. On the EFile Review navigation tree, click the PDF node to access the file.

      4. When you select the Full XML node, select either Open or Save. If you select Open, the XML file opens in a separate screen.Large PDF files may take several minutes to download. We recommend using the Save As option and view the file offline.

         Do not click the PDF node repeatedly. Doing so restarts the process.

        The system displays your file on the right side of the Efile Review screen.

        • Column 1 reflects the actual form line number.

        • Column 2 lists each line description.

        • Column 3 displays the balance for the line items.


        • Column 4 includes the XML tab for each line item.

      Screen Features and Navigation

      Use the Save, Search, and Print toolbar icons at the top of the screen. The left side of the Adobe Acrobat Reader® screen also has other features such as pages and bookmarks which you can use to jump to specific pages and areas in the return.

      Line item descriptions that appear in blue text are hyperlinks to other supporting pages.

      In addition to XML information, each page includes header information displaying entity name and EIN and footer information which displays a date and time stamp and page number.

      Additional File Information

      You can only create one XML at a time in the Organizer. The system automatically adds a date and time stamp to the bottom of each PDF page every time it is updated so you can track the changes confidently. If the date and time stamp of the PDF is different from that of the XML, you must recreate the e-file.

    • Consolidated returns are presented only in stacked format.

    • The IRS requires that the cross-tie print options do not apply to electronic filing.

    • Supporting statements may not appear in the same order as they would print for a return.

    • Non-numerical information may appear at the entity level for which it was entered.

    • The system does not include the PDF Attachment in the PDF Reader, but the return should have a Binary Attachment section that displays the associated attachment information.

      Downloading and Viewing the XML File with Internet Explorer

      The actual XML files generated by the system are displayed in the Efile Review tree. The system supports large XML file downloads.

      1. Select the Full XML node.

      2. Select either Open or Save. If you select Open, the XML file opens in a separate screen.

      3. Click Save to download the file to your computer. We recommend using the Save option if you have a large XML file.

      4. When you view the XML file (through Internet Explorer or a text editor), you can identify the return/ extension data by the surrounding schema element names.

      ONESOURCE 2016


      CHAPTER 12: FEDERAL CONSOLIDATIONS‌‌


      THE CONSOLIDATION PROCESS‌

      During the federal consolidation process, information for the parent company and each subsidiary or division included in the consolidated tax return is combined in a Consolidation Binder.

      This process is accomplished by performing the following steps:

      1. Create entities and binders

      2. Complete Member Binders

      3. Consolidate!

      4. Review and Revise

      5. Print the Consolidated Return


      FEDERAL CONSOLIDATION CAPABILITIES‌‌

      The federal consolidation process includes the following capabilities:

    • Performs complex multi-tier consolidations

    • Combines data from parent, subsidiaries, and divisions

    • Computes eliminations and adjustments

    • Prepares Tax Bracket Allocation Schedule and Controlled Group Election Statement

    • Offers stacked and cross-tied whitepaper for consolidated federal Form 1120.

    • Provides look-through print options for sub-consolidated detail

    • Provides summary consolidated return schedules in eight-column format for key federal forms and schedules, including Form 1120, and Forms 4562, 4626, 3468, 3800, 4797, 5884, 6478, 6765, and Schedule D.

    • Computes limitations for NOL, contributions, capital loss carryovers, various credits, and SRLY/non-SRLY NOL deduction.

       For information regarding divisional consolidations and subconsolidations, please refer to “Divisional Consolidations” on page 257.


      TYPES OF CONSOLIDATIONS‌‌

      The system offers the following types of consolidations:

      Single-Tier Consolidation

      All Entities (parent, subsidiaries, and eliminations) are combined into one consolidation binder. This type of consolidation is also referred to as a single-tier consolidation.



      Multi-Tier Consolidation

      A divisional/subsidiary consolidation is the combining of financial information for specific levels of divisions and/ or subsidiaries. Because these lower level consolidations will be combined into a top consolidation, these consolidations are referred to as multi-tier consolidations. The divisional/subsidiary consolidation binders include individual binders for each subsidiary, a binder for the parent entity, subconsolidation binders for each group of divisions, an elimination binder for each subconsolidation group, and the top consolidation binder.



      PRE-CONSOLIDATION‌‌

      We recommend you do the following before continuing the federal consolidation process:

      1. Enter all data consistently across each member of the consolidation.

        DETAIL CONSISTENCY. Keeping the level of detail consistent for each company in the consolidated group is the key to a successful consolidation.

        For example, Schedule D, Form 4797, 4562, 6252. Because the system allows data to be entered in several levels of Organizer, users must maintain consistency from entity to entity for consolidation purposes.

        The following represent the most common areas where data is entered inconsistently:

        • 4562 Overrides vs. Asset Detail (See the following section for more detail.)

        • Capital Gain Calculation options (Net vs. Gross Amounts)

        • 4797 Gain/Loss Net Amounts vs. system-calculated 4797

        • Net Income per books vs. system-calculated net income per books

          The danger with inconsistency is that totals on the supporting detail statements will not match the 1120 return amounts at the consolidated level. This often causes the system to produce adjustments in the Con- solidated Review screen in order for all data to balance.

          The best way to enter data is at the lowest level of detail in the Organizer on all binders. As long as the data is entered consistently across all entities (for example, all use 4562 Overrides), then data consolidates as expected.

      2. Clear all binder overrides and diagnostics from each binder, including e-file diagnostics for electronically filed returns.

      3. Balance and fully recompute all binders.

      ONESOURCE 2016



      CONSOLIDATING ENTITIES AND BINDERS‌‌

      Consolidations must include the following entities:

    • Parent Company

    • Subsidiaries

    • Elimination Company

    • Top or Sub Consolidation.

       For divisional consolidations, all member binders are divisions rather than subsidiaries.


      ENTITY

      DESCRIPTION

      Parent/Subsidiary

      Used to create individual, specific entity returns. Data is entered at this level and combined in the sub-consolidation or top consolidation binder. It is critical that data is entered consistently across all entities.

      Elimination Binder

      Stores all elimination entries. Data from this binder is combined with the parent and subsidiary entities in the sub-consolidation or top consolidation binder. Amounts entered at the elimination level will add to, or subtract from, the consolidated totals calculated from the parent and subsidiary binders. For this reason, amounts entered in the Elimination binder that should also be entered to the consolidated totals should be entered as positives and amounts to be subtracted from the consolidated totals as negatives. As with parent and subsidiary binders, data must be entered consistently in the eliminations binder in order to have a successful consolidation.

      Sub and Top

      Stores the combined or consolidated amounts of all the consolidation binder entities. The system automatically combines information from each entity in the Top Consolidation binder. Generally, very little information is entered in this binder. The same consolidation binder can be used for both federal and state consolidations.


      An Elimination and a Consolidation entity are required for each type of consolidation (Top, Sub, Divisional). To create them:

      1. Go to the My Binders screen.

      2. On the Binders menu bar, select Add | Entity.

      3. On the Return Type tab, select the type of entity from the drop-down list.

      4. On the General tab only the Elimination or Consolidation name is necessary. Since the consolidation return takes its information from the parent, only the entity name is required.

      5. Click OK.


      CREATING BINDERS FOR CONSOLIDATIONS

      Once you create the entities, create the binders. Create the elimination binder first because it must be added to the consolidation binder.

      1. Select the Entity for the binder.

      2. On the menu bar, click Add | Binder.

      3. Enter the name of the binder. This will not print on the return and is only for reports and reference.

      4. Select the Charts tab.

      5. Select the Federal Chart of Accounts from the drop-down list.

      6. Select the appropriate, associated Charts of Adjustments from the drop-down lists for the elimination entity.


         Because adjustments are made at the lower entity levels (parent/sub/elimination), Charts of Adjustments do not need to be identified at the consolidation level.

      7. Select the Options tab.

      8. Verify the closing and rounding options. If the fields are not populated, the Charts tab is complete since they were not selected at the chart level.

      9. Enter a Round up to the Amount of: number.

      10. Click Save.

       Once Chart assignments have been made for a binder they cannot be changed.

      A consolidated binder has an additional tab that allows you to select entities belonging to the consolidated group.

      Entering Eliminating Entries

      Use the Elimination binder to enter any eliminating entries you want used when computing the consolidation.

    • Enter amounts to add as positives.

    • Enter amounts to subtract as negatives. We do not assume entered amounts are negative.

      ONESOURCE 2016



      ADDING MEMBERS TO A CONSOLIDATED BINDER

      1. From the Binder Properties screen, select the Members tab.

      2. On the Binder Properties menu bar, click Add Members to add the elimination company to the consolidation.



      3. Select the appropriate workarea from the drop-down list.


      4. On the Add Members screen, select the Elimination binder.

      5. Click Save. The elimination binder is now added to the Elimination field.

      6. Repeat steps 2-5 to add additional entities and binders to the consolidated group. Do not choose the Top Consolidation Entity.

      7. A parent is automatically designated as the first entity listed. If this is not correct, select the entity that will be designated as the Parent from the Entity list and click the Set As Parent button.

      8. When selections are complete, click Update. This consolidation member information automatically updates the TAS Consolidate screen and transfers to the What to Consolidate screen in the Organizer.


      Consolidation Members Tasks

      The Binder Properties menu bar also includes the following features:


      1. Add members to the consolidation.

      2. Moves entities up in the entity listing. The entity listing on Form 851 will show this order.

      3. Moves entities down in the entity listing.

      4. Import consolidation members in a batch.

      5. Export a list of consolidation members.

      6. Remove a consolidation member.


      IMPORTING BINDERS FOR ENTITIES IN CONSOLIDATIONS

      Use the Members tab on the Binder Properties screen to import binders for entities of a top consolidation, subconsolidation, or divisional consolidation binder using a .csv file.

      The following items apply when using this feature.

    • Unique company numbers are required to use Members Import even though the system does not require unique company numbers in the user account.

    • Members Import only adds members to the members list. It does not delete or replace binders in the list.

    • You must use the Remove button to delete binders from the member list or to change binders in the list for a company number that already exists in the list.

    • You must initialize all binders before importing them into the members list.

    • To initialize newly created binders, use Batch Compute.


IMPORTING MEMBERS INTO A CONSOLIDATION BINDER

  1. In the Home Window, select the appropriate binder.

  2. On the menu, select Properties.

  3. Click the Members tab.

  4. Click Import.

  5. In the Select Import File drop-down list, either select a file or click Browse to select the source file.

  6. Click Open.

  7. Select an import template from the drop-down list to choose an existing template or for new items, you must define the import template.

  8. Click New to create a new template.

  9. Import files in .csv format must include at least two columns, Company Number and Binder Name of the specific binder to be included in the consolidation.

  10. The first import of a members list to a blank screen must include one Elimination binder and at least one

    non-Elimination binder.

  11. Click Import when you are ready to import the list.

  12. The import process sets the Parent and Elimination binders as follows

  13. Subsequent imports of members after the Parent and Eliminations binders are set on the Members tab will append new members to the end of the members list.

ONESOURCE 2016



EXPORTING MEMBERS FOR CONSOLIDATIONS

Use the Members tab on the Binder Properties screen to export binders for the entities of a top consolidation, subconsolidation, or divisional consolidation binder using a .csv file.

  1. On the Binders screen, select the appropriate binder.

  2. On the Binders menu bar, select Properties.

  3. Click the Members tab.

  4. Click Export.

  5. Enter a unique Export File Name.

  6. Browse to the directory where you want to save the file.

  7. Click Save.


CONSOLIDATING ORGANIZER‌‌

Once the consolidation of the subsidiary listing screen is complete, consolidate Organizer. The organizer consolidation process consolidates detail entered in the various member binders such as Form 4562 detail, Form 4797 detail, M3 detail NOL carryforwards, etc. The consolidation binder holds the results of the consolidation. Enter only a minimal amount of data in the consolidation binder, since each time you consolidate, the application deletes Organizer data and replaces it with the new consolidated amounts.

Complete the consolidation steps using either the Organizer screen that appears under Consolidated Returns in Organizer as described below or using the TAS Consolidate screen to make similar options as shown in the TAS Consolidate section later in this chapter. (See “Tax Accounting System Consolidate Screen” on page 279.)

 The TAS Consolidate screen is provided to give a condensed location for consolidating.


STEP 1 - WHAT TO CONSOLIDATE

Consolidated Return List

Confirm the members listed here. These are populated by adding members on the Binder Properties screen and then computing the binder to transfer the listing from TAS to Organizer. If you add or delete a member, you must repeat these steps.



Selecting Federal Forms to Consolidate

The system default is to consolidate all federal forms.



  1. In Organizer, navigate to Consolidated Returns | Step 1 - What to Consolidate.

  2. Select the Federal Forms to Consolidate tab.

    • If you leave the X on Consolidate ALL Federal Forms, then the application consolidates all the federal forms listed.

    • If you remove the X, then you can choose which forms to consolidate by selecting the check box next to the form.

  3. If the amounts on the consolidated returns are not consolidated, you must verify that you have not changed the default option to consolidate all federal forms and schedules. This tab is not needed for state consolidations.

    ONESOURCE 2016



    Selecting States to Combine/Consolidate

    Use this tab to activate the states that you want to file a combined/consolidated return with this binder. If the state does not allow combined/consolidated filings, it will not be listed.



    Click State and City Activation/Consolidation.

    Select the Allocation and Apportionment option to consolidate/combine allocation and apportionment. This is mandatory if you wish to have allocation and apportionment consolidated. Do not select this option if you want to roll up divisions and then enter allocation and apportionment information on the divisional roll up return.

     If you are using divisional consolidation binders, please see the divisional consolidation portion of this guide prior to making this selection. There are situations, when using divisional consolidations, where you will not mark the state to combine/consolidate in this section but would need to activate the state in the Add/Delete area instead.

  4. Select the appropriate check box(es) next to the states you wish to consolidate/combine.

  5. For more information, click Combined State Overview or Combined State Reports List to view topics in the online Help system.

  6. Click the Review State Combined Steps link to view the steps to complete before consolidating states.


STEP 2 - ENTER CONSOLIDATED OVERRIDES

This step is for federal overrides you may wish to make on a top consolidation level. Overrides entered here are used instead of the consolidated amounts from subsidiaries. If you override on the top consolidation, the system creates and adjustment on the white paper schedule with possible footing errors.

To view these screens, select the Organizer | Consolidated Returns | Step 2 - Enter Consolidated Overrides.


1120 PG 1-5

  1. Select this item on the navigation tree to view override items related to page 1-5 on an 1120 return.


  2. Enter special deductions.

    ONESOURCE 2016



  3. Select the Schedule J tab to enter override tax computations, tax credits, and Page 1 Credits.



  4. Select 1120 Consolidation NOL to enter amounts for 1120 Consolidated NOL.



  5. Select Tax Accruals - Cons to enter tax accruals for consolidated returns if accruing to Schedule M-1.



OTHER FORMS

  1. Select the Organizer | Consolidated Returns | Step 2 - Enter Consolidated Overrides | Other Forms.

  2. Select each tab to enter override amounts for Forms 3468, 4255, 4626, 4797, 8810, and AMT Consolidation NOL.



  3. Select the Organizer | Consolidated Returns | Step 2 - Enter Consolidated Overrides | Financial Institution Bad Debt.

  4. Select this screen to enter bad debt amounts.


    ONESOURCE 2016



    Any overrides entered directly on this screen are deleted on the consolidated Organizer or Tax Form screens each time you reconsolidate.

     If you enter override amounts on the top consolidation, the system creates an adjustment on the whitepaper schedule with possible footing errors. If you enter override amounts, you may want to attach your own whitepaper detail.


    STEP 3 - SELECT PRINT AND CALCULATION OPTIONS

    • Detail Print Options tab. Use this tab to indicate your printing preferences. Stacked Print prints the whitepaper detail for each company one after another. Cross-tie Print prints the whitepaper detail in a spreadsheet type format.

      This tab also contains options for look-through and divisional print. If you wish to list the detail separately for each subsidiary, select Look-through print. If you wish to list each division separately in your return, select Break-down by divisions.



       The selection you make on this tab only affects your printed return. It does not alter the electronically filed return. The electronically filed return will be submitted in stacked format.

    • Form Print Options tab. Use this tab to mark various form print options. Many of the options on this tab will affect the outcome of your return. Read through each one to see which options apply to your return.

    • Federal Divisional Roll-up tab. Use this tab for divisional consolidations, to select various consolidation options.

    • State Divisional Roll-up tab. If this consolidated binder is a divisional consolidation, use this tab to select the necessary options. If you do, all members of the consolidation must be divisions, parents and subsidiaries are not permitted.


STEP 4 - REVIEW PRECONSOL CHECKLIST

Preconsolidation Checklist. This screen displays the checklist of tasks which must be completed before consolidating.



Inconsistency Report. This screen identifies the area in each return where data was not entered consistently. For example, if one binder entered asset detail for the Form 4562, while another one used the override screens, the software would list the information here. You must enter data consistently in all entities in order to consolidate properly.


ONESOURCE 2016



Check Out of Balance and Compute Pending. This button will display the number of binders in the consolidation, as well as, identify the number of missing binders, the out of balance binders, and the binders that have computes pending. This is a useful checklist to run prior to consolidating the Organizer of the return. You can also compute subsidiaries with computes pending or compute all the subsidiaries from this screen. (This computes the Organizers of the subsidiaries only. It will not perform TAS transfers.)



STEP 5 - CONSOLIDATE!

This step starts the Organizer consolidation. It includes an option to consolidate with Cross-Ties. State returns do not use Cross-Ties. Each individual state has a specific whitepaper presentation format based on the state- required information.

A consolidation binder may be consolidated prior to the completion of the member binders, however, it will only consolidate data that has been entered. The binder may be consolidated as many times as needed.

 You must Consolidate TAS before consolidating in Organizer.


  1. Select Consolidated Returns. | Step 5 - Consolidate!



  2. Check the Consolidate with Cross -ties option if you want cross-tie detail schedules.

  3. Click Consolidate.

During the consolidation process, the application does the following steps:

  1. Runs a pre-consolidation utility that deletes previous consolidated files, and consolidate cross-tie codes if applicable.

  2. Transfers 851 and general information from the parent and subsidiary binders to the consolidated binder.

  3. Combines amounts from every binder on the consolidated listing.

  4. Performs an initial compute of the consolidated tax return.

  5. Applies Elimination adjustments entered in the elimination binder.

  6. Performs the remaining computations.

  7. Applies any automatic adjustments (for example, capital loss or contribution deduction limitations).

 Processing time may vary depending upon the number, size and complexity of the binders included in the consolidation. You can access the consolidation screen by selecting File | Consolidate. This takes you to Step 5 - Consolidate!


STEP 6 - REVIEW CROSS-TIE INFORMATION

Select Step 6 - Review Cross-Tie Information to review the diagnostics created by combining the Organizer screens for the consolidated review.


When the consolidation is complete, use the review tools in the next section to review the return.

ONESOURCE 2016



REVIEW AND REVISE‌‌

Review tools are available in Organizer to alert you to potential errors within the consolidation. The functionality that is available in individual binders are also available in consolidated binders, however, consolidated binders offer additional methods of reviewing the return.

  • Diagnostics and Overrides

  • Subview

  • Consolidated Review Screens

  • Cross-Tie Review

  • Tax Summary

  • Drill-Down Arrows

  • Hyperlinks

  • Workpapers


    SUBVIEW‌‌

    Subview is a special feature that allows you to review the amounts from each subsidiary included in the consolidation. This is especially helpful when processing multi-tiered consolidations.

    Follow these steps from any Tax Form or Organizer field within the consolidated return:

    1. Position the cursor on the selected field and right-click to access the short-cut menu.



    2. Select Subview from the short-cut menu. This displays a dialog box that shows the amounts from each subsidiary, parent, eliminations, or subconsolidation making up the total.



    If you need to make changes to a parent or subsidiary, double-click the line for that amount on the right of the screen. The application opens the return for that company and takes you to the selected field. You can make any needed changes and select the red “X” on the left side of the toolbar to close the return. This returns you to the top consolidation.

     If you change any amounts in the parent or subsidiary, you must reconsolidate.


    CONSOLIDATED REVIEW‌‌

    The first review is the Consolidated Review, which allows you to review tax form amounts for pages 1-5 in columnar format by navigating to Tax Forms | Federal | 1120-U.S. Corporation Return. This review allows you to see how the columnar schedules for the consolidated returns will print (including adjustments).



    There are many reasons an adjustment appears in Subview and on the Consolidated Review Workpaper. Some of them are as follows:

  • One of the member binders contains an override. This causes the override to appear on the top consolidation and therefore the sum of the member binders does not equal the amount on the consolidated binder.

  • Based on the law, a reclass was required. This is commonly found on Schedule D and on Form 4797.

  • Amounts were entered inconsistently. Example - One member entered data on a detail screen while other members entered similar data in an override section, such as Form 4562 detail.

    There are other review tools located in the Tax Forms section of the application, as seen on the menu tree below.


    ONESOURCE 2016



    CROSS-TIE REVIEW

    Open the Cross-Tie Review folder to review total amounts for any line with cross-tie codes available, as shown below. Selecting the Commonly Asked Questions button will display important instructions and answers for cross-tie codes.




    To see the cross-tie detail that makes up the total shown above, select the desired field. This displays the detail screen below, which shows the cross-tie codes, descriptions, and amounts that comprise the total.


    TIPS AND TRICKS FOR CONSOLIDATIONS‌‌


    VERIFYING GAINS AND LOSSES DATA ENTRY

    For general sales of business property (Form 4797) or Capital Gains (Schedule D), users have the option of allowing the software to calculate gains or losses or overriding the calculation in favor of a user defined amount.

    1. From within Organizer, navigate to the Gains and Losses folder and open either Disposition of Property or

      Capital Gains and Losses.

    2. Select an entered asset.

    3. To maintain consistent levels of data entry, make sure that all subsidiaries and parents have either:

      • An amount entered on the Gain (Loss) Automatic** field, or

      • No amount entered in the Gain (Loss) Automatic ** field for system calculation.


    VERIFYING NET INCOME PER BOOKS CALCULATION

    Net Income per Books is normally a system calculation. However, the calculation can be overridden in favor of a user-defined amount.

    1. Navigate to Balance Sheet/M1-M2-M3 and click Schedule M1/M2/ M3.

       Net Income per books is a system-calculated amount unless a check is placed next to the option Do not automatically adjust Schedule M1, Line 1 for accruals. An amount can be manually populated using the Net Income Per Books fields.

    2. For consolidation purposes, in each subsidiary:

      1. Allow automatic system calculation for all entries (Net Income per books field is automatically populated), or

      2. Check the box Do not automatically adjust Schedule M1, Line 1 for accruals and enter an amount for

    Net Income Per Books for all entities.

    Printing the Consolidated Return

    Before you actually print the return, there are several types of print styles available to you. Types of Consolidated Form Print

    The first type of consolidated print is called columnar form print, or consolidated form print. This is columnar

    white paper print that mimics the tax form. We provide columnar print for the following tax forms:



    Table 1:


    Form 1120, Pages 1-5

    Form 4797

    Form 8826

    Form 1125-A

    Form 8810

    Form 8903

    Form 4562

    Form 4626

    Form 8825

    Schedule D


    This columnar form print always consists of two pages:

  • Page 1: The first page always contains four columns: combined, eliminations, adjustments, and the consolidated amount, and

  • Page 2: The second page always contains a column for each entity making up the combined column on the first page.

    ONESOURCE 2016



    The first page does not change and contains the following columns:


    COLUMN 1

    COLUMN 2

    COLUMN 3

    COLUMN 4

    COMBINED

    ELIMINATIONS

    ADJUSTMENTS

    CONSOLIDATED AMOUNT

    This is the total of all subsidiaries or divisions, subconsolidations, and the parent.

    The heading on this column is the name on your eliminations return. Any entries you made in that return will appear here.

    This is the difference between (columns 1 and 2), and column 4. This column will contain adjustments made in the consolidation process, like charitable contribution limitations. If we find any other differences, we will print them here also. If these appear, you probably have an override in one of your subsidiaries that is forcing an adjustment here.

    This amount is the amount found on your return. If you have not been consistent in the level of your detail, this amount will not add to the combined amounts and will force an adjustment.


    The first page of the schedule is displayed below:



    The second page contains the amounts from each entity in the consolidation, and may change based on how you choose to view subconsolidations.



    As you can see, the second page contains columns for the parent and all subsidiaries.

  • If you select Look Through print, you will see the amounts for each subsidiary within a consolidation rather than the subconsolidation.

  • If you select Print divisions, you will see the amounts for each division in a divisional consolidation rather than the divisional consolidation.

Displaying Supporting Line Item Detail Print

Supporting detail print is print for line items on the tax form, for instance Line 5, Interest Income.

To format supporting detail for subsidiaries, first, choose the way you would like your supporting detail for each subsidiary or subconsolidation to print. In the application, you can choose between two styles for this: stacked and cross-tie.


STACKED PRINT

“Stacked” white paper is print in a portrait orientation showing the detail for each member of the consolidation, one below the other, printed in the order in which you listed your returns on the What to Consolidate screen. The parent is always the first company shown. We print each company name followed by descriptions and amounts.


Stacked is the default print for the application and the format that prints if you make no selections.

ONESOURCE 2016



CROSS-TIE

Cross-tie is columnar print; you see the amount from each subsidiary in a spreadsheet format, rather than one below the other. Cross-tie print has two parts just like columnar form print; the first page shows combined, eliminations, adjustments, and consolidated. The second page shows each amount making up the combined amount. Below is an example of the second page.



Displaying Amounts for Subconsolidations

Next, choose how you would like to view amounts from subconsolidations. The selections for stacked or cross- tie made above also apply to these selections. You may disregard these options unless you have subconsolidations within your top consolidation.

Your first choice for subconsolidations is to choose how to display amounts for your subconsolidations containing subsidiaries.

You have three types of display for subconsolidations.


COLUMNAR FORM PRINT - PAGE 2

Standard print shows columnar form print (page 2) showing a single total for United Refineries and Subsidiaries, the subconsolidation of subsidiaries.



Look through print shows columnar form print showing the amounts for the parent and each subsidiary within the subconsolidation rather than the amount for the subconsolidation itself. Now you can see the amounts for the parent (United Refineries) and each subsidiary (Coastal Refineries and Rocky Mountain Refineries).



LINE ITEM DETAIL PRINT (SUPPORTING DETAIL) - STACKED

Now let’s see how the line item detail will print for your subconsolidations, based on whether you chose stacked or cross-tie above.

If you chose stacked:

Standard stacked print - shows Page 2 detail print with a single total for:

  • United Refineries and Subsidiaries, the subconsolidation, and

  • United Refineries Sales Group, the subconsolidation of divisions (divisional roll-up).


ONESOURCE 2016



Look through stacked print shows the amount for each subsidiary in the top consolidation, and the amount for each subsidiary in the subconsolidation, and a total for the subconsolidation containing divisions. You have looked through to the subsidiaries in the subconsolidation.



SUPPORTING DETAIL PRINT - CROSS TIE

Standard cross tie print shows Page 2 detail print with a single total for United Refineries and Subsidiaries, the subconsolidation and United Pipeline Sales Group, the divisional roll-up.

COMPLETING FORM 851: CORPORATE AFFILIATIONS SCHEDULE‌‌

Preparing Form 851 for your consolidated group

Form 851 is printed from the Top Consolidation return, but consists of information entered in the parent and subsidiary returns. To create the 851 correctly, it is important to know where to enter information for each field and section of the form. These instructions will lead you through that process.

Generally, information for the 851 comes from these three places: the Top Consolidation return, the parent return and the subsidiary returns. When you create a consolidation return, you select the active members to be included in the consolidation on the What to Consolidate screen. The program can now transfer in certain information from the entities you have listed. The corporation name, address, FEIN, estimated and extension payments, Principal Business Activity, and PBA code information will carry in from the general information area in the respective parent and subsidiary returns.


CONSOLIDATION CARRY INFORMATION

The information that transfers into the top consolidation from other returns is referred to as “consolidation carry information.” Every time you perform a consolidation, the program sweeps the parent and subsidiary returns to collect the Consolidation Carry Information.

 Be careful not to enter any of this information in the top consolidation’s Organizer or Tax Forms. If you manually enter any data in these fields, the application overwrites this information each time you consolidate when it transfers the Consolidation Carry Information into the Organizer.

First we will look at what information comes from which return, and then we will go through the form field by field and list the source for the data. In general, the following information transfers from the returns shown.

PARENT. The following information carries automatically to the top consolidation return from the parent. To have this transfer occur, you must enter the company locator numbers on the Top Consolidation return in Organizer | Consolidated Returns | What to Consolidate screen.

  • Name and address (street, city, state, zip code)

  • Tax year ending

  • Employer identification number

  • Prepayment credits

  • PBA Code number

    SUBSIDIARIES. The following information carries automatically to the top consolidation return from the subsidiary returns:

  • Names and addresses

  • Employer identification numbers

  • Prepayment credits

  • Principal business activity

  • PBA Code numbers.

    TOP CONSOLIDATIONS. Enter the following information in the Top Consolidation return:

    INACTIVE SUBSIDIARY INFORMATION. If you do not prepare returns for inactive members of the consolidation, you can add these members to your Form 851 on the top consolidation return. This information carries to Part I of the Form 851 Tax Return.

  • In the top consolidation return, access Organizer | Informational Forms | Affiliation Schedule | Inactive Subsidiary Information.

  • Enter the name, address, FEIN, and PBA information for each inactive member company.

  • Be sure to assign the first inactive subsidiary a company number that follows the last number assigned to active subsidiaries on the Consolidated Returns | What to Consolidate | Consolidation Locator List screen.

ONESOURCE 2016



VOTING STOCK INFORMATION. Enter your company number, and the PBA activity and code will appear.

PART III AND PART IV INFORMATION. Enter Parent and Subsidiary information for Parts III and IV of Form 851.
