TAX ACCOUNTING SYSTEM CONSOLIDATE SCREEN‌‌

The Consolidate screen is used to process income tax return consolidations and run all underlying consolidations and computes from the Top Consolidation binder. This feature gives you the ability to:

  • Consolidate Federal, State A&A, State TI and Organizer simultaneously.

  • Process consolidations and underlying members.

  • Member binders from the binder’s Properties screen are automatically listed on the Consolidate screen and then transferred to the Organizer, What to Consolidate screen.

    When you update the member binders in the binder's Properties, then a list of all member binders including lower level consolidations and their members appear on the Consolidate screen.



    This screen shows you the following information about the consolidation and each of its members:

  • Company Number (at the beginning in brackets)

  • Entity Name/Binder Name

  • Consol Options column

  • Needs Compute indicator

  • Last TAS Compute

  • Status column.


    The ONESOURCE entity type icon appears next to each different entity to give you a hierarchal representation of your consolidation structure.

    Best Practices

    Use the Enterprise Control Panel to select options that apply to each of the consolidated binders before processing them, such as:

  • Detail Print Options - Use this area to select the Cross-tie or stacked print option and any other consolidated print option for each consolidated return binders.

  • States to Consolidate/Combine - Use this area to select the states in Organizer that will file combined or consolidated returns.

  • State Combined Options - Use this area to select combined options by state that need to be selected. For example, the Kansas combined income filing method.

  • What to Consolidate - Use this area to select Federal, State A&A, State TI, and Organizer as the data that needs to be consolidated for each consolidation binder. For example, set these options in Divisional or Sub consolidations before processing the Top Consolidation.

ONESOURCE 2016



Using the Consolidation Compute

  1. Open a Top Consolidation tax return binder.

  2. On the TAS navigation tree, select Consolidate.

  3. The Consolidation screen lists all the member binders for the consolidation.


    If there is a green marker in the Consol Options field , click the icon to access the

    Consolidation Options screen.


  4. Check the appropriate consolidation options for the consolidation from the bottom of the Consolidate

    screen.


  5. Before starting the consolidation process, select from the following options:

    • Compute and Consolidate Underlying Members. Select this option when you are ready to compute and consolidate members of this consolidation. Any binders set as “Read Only” will not compute. If you only want to process this consolidation and not underlying consolidations, do not select this option.

    • Only Consolidations. Select this option to compute and consolidate only consolidation members. When you select this option, all underlying consolidations will be processed and any other member binders will not be computed.

    • All Members. Select this option to compute and consolidate all members. When you select this option, any non-consolidated binders will also be computed. The compute of each member binder will use its own Update Federal TAS, State A&A, and State TI, Transfer International settings during the compute.

    • Include Partnerships that use K-1 or A&A transfer. Select this option to compute and consolidate all partnership binders with corporate partners that are a part of this consolidation. These are the


      partnerships that flow to some members of this consolidation and they use the K-1 or A&A transfer feature.

    • Include Foreign and Foreign Partnership. Select this option to compute and consolidate all foreign entity binders and foreign partnerships that are International members in this consolidation. International computes are not included with this process.

    • Only If They Need Computing. Select this option to compute and consolidate only binders where the data has been changed but the computed results do not reflect the changes. The Needs Compute column shows the binders that would benefit from this option. Please contact your account manager if you would like to use this feature.

    • Refresh history for this consolidation and underlying consolidations. Select this option to update each consolidation's historical balances from the prior year related binders.

  6. Click Begin to start the compute and consolidation processing. This button will not become active until you select the Consol Options. You must select them before beginning the process. After starting the consolidation, you can either leave this screen open or close it while the software processes the information.

  7. While the process is running, the Status column will show various status messages for each member and consolidation binder being processed.

  8. When the consolidation processes are complete, the Status column will show Ready in it.

  9. Click Export to export the consolidation member list into a .csv file. Locator numbers will appear next to each member.

  10. Click Close to close this screen after processing or without processing the consolidation.


TAX ACCOUNTING SYSTEM CONSOLIDATION OPTIONS‌‌

The Consolidation screen is set up in spreadsheet format with the following columns. The columns give you information about the consolidation members and are described as follows:



ONESOURCE 2016



[Company Number] Entity/Binder

This column shows the ONESOURCE entity type icon next to each different entity to give you a hierarchal representation of the consolidation structure.

Consol Options

This column shows the consolidation binders where you must select consolidation options which tell the software how to process the consolidation binder. Check the box(es) for the data you want to consolidate and the appropriate update option(s):



Update Organizer with:

  • Federal TAS. Select this option to update this consolidation's Organizer with information from Federal TAS. This option is available for "Foreign entity" Divisional Consolidations or consolidations using the Binder Rollup option.

  • State A&A. Select this option to update this consolidation's Organizer with information from State Allocation and Apportionment. This option is available for Divisional Consolidations.

  • State TI. Select this option to update this consolidation's Organizer with information from the State TI data entry area. This option is available for Divisional Consolidations.

  • Update International Organizer with Federal TAS (2004 and prior). Select this option to update International Organizer with Federal TAS information. This option is only available for binders preceding 2005.

  • Transfer International. Select this option to transfer international information to Foreign Tax Credit Divisional Consolidations.

    What to Consolidate

  • Federal - Select this to consolidate all Federal TAS information. This consolidates the Working Trial Balance, Schedule M-3, and all federal reports.

  • State A&A - Select this to consolidate State A&A data entry and review workpapers. You do not need this option for a federal consolidation.

  • State TI [requires state selection] - Select this to consolidate State TI data entry and review workpapers. In addition to selecting this, you must also select each state to consolidate State TI, activate each applicable state in Organizer, and select the option Update State TI with Organizer in order to synchronize the State Tax Forms with the State TI review workpapers.


    If you select a state where you have manually entered amounts in the State TI data entry workpapers then these amounts will be overwritten with the consolidated amounts on the consolidated binder.

  • Organizer - Select this to consolidate the Organizer and Tax Forms and generate necessary information for filing the return.


  • Save Options - Click this button to save all of your choices for future processing sessions for this consolidation. Member binders, including underlying consolidations, should already have the same selections before processing the consolidation.

  • Close - Click this button to return to the Consolidation screen and continue the process.


    NEEDS COMPUTE

    This column indicates whether or not there have been changes to this binder such as TAS data, binder property selections, related binder, or chart information. TAS data changes can include balances, adjustment balances, and Schedule M-3 data for Return binders.

  • A Yes indicates the binder must be computed to reflect the changes.

  • A No indicates a compute is not needed for that member binder. Text Color

  • If a member binder needs to be computed, the text will be "blue".

  • If it does not need a compute, then the text will be "black"

  • As member binders are processed, the text color will change to "green" indicating a member is being processed.

  • The text color "gray" indicates the binder is Read-Only. Last TAS Compute

This column indicates the most recent date and time when the binder was successfully computed.

Status

This column represents the processing status of this consolidation binder and its members. Some of the status' include: Ready, TAS Computing, Opening Tax Data File, Tax Consolidating, Computing, Compute Never Finished, etc.).

This column is important, especially when the consolidation process is unsuccessful. If the status is Compute Never Finished for a binder, you must process it again before continuing with the consolidation process.


FORM 1120 S - CORPORATE CONSOLIDATIONS‌‌

We provide the ability to treat the assets, liabilities, income, deductions, and credits of qualified subchapter S subsidiaries (QSSS) as those of the parent S corporation. To consolidate the QSSS items into the parent return, we use the same consolidation procedures used for C corporation consolidation. These procedures require top consolidation, parent, elimination, and subsidiary (QSSS) returns be used. The consolidation process combines data from the parent, elimination, and subsidiary returns into the top return. Also, no Division should be included in the Subsidiary Listing with parent and subsidiaries on a consolidation.

We also provide the ability to consolidate S Corporation divisions. You should not include any entities marked as Parent or Subsidiary in the divisional consolidation. You must set the entity type as a Division, and include an elimination in the divisional consolidation.

You need to input detail with Tax Combination Codes (TCC) for all members; otherwise, the detail will not be consolidated and you may see duplicate descriptions. The system will consolidate the detail by TCCs for all members, and bring detail information up to the Organizer on the divisional rollup during consolidation. You may review the detail in the Organizer and print as a single company.

Specific to S corporation consolidations are the following points:

  • We assume 1120S returns identified as subsidiaries meet the requirements for QSSS treatment, and the parent has made the proper election.

  • Since the top return is the return that is actually filed, the taxpayer name should not refer to as Top or

    Consolidated Return and Subsidiaries, or a similar designation.

  • Even though eliminations may not be applicable, an elimination return is required to complete the consolidation process.

    ONESOURCE 2016



  • Shareholder information, including share transfers, special allocations, and time segment allocations, must be entered on the parent return. In the consolidation process, shareholder information is transferred from the parent to the top return.

  • Section 179 limitations and tax (excess net passive income tax. or tax from Schedule D) are computed on the top return, and Schedule K is based on the combined amounts.

  • Schedules K-1 are computed based on the top return shareholder information and the Schedule K items and amounts.

CHAPTER 13: DIVISIONAL CONSOLIDATIONS‌‌


ONESOURCE Income Tax gives you two ways to consolidate divisions. You can use either the typical consolidation method or the Binder Rollup method.

  • The typical Divisional Consolidation process combines the Organizer information for each division within the consolidated group which allows the system to prepare a consolidated tax return and supplemental schedules.

  • The Binder Rollup method combines the TAS data of the underlying divisions and then transfers the combined TAS data to the consolidated Organizer.

    The following diagram illustrates the difference between these two methods:



    In each type of Divisional Consolidation, the system maintains the general ledger data in TAS for each division. The Columnar WTB in the Divisional Consolidation binder allows you to view the combined data, as well as a comparison of the data for each division.

    In a binder rollup, the system combines the TAS data in the Divisional Consolidation binder and then transfers the combined data to the Organizer as if it is one entity. Therefore, there are no combined or consolidated reports in the Organizer.



    BINDER ROLLUP VS. DIVISIONAL ROLLUP‌‌

    We recommend that you know the difference between a Binder Rollup and a Divisional Rollup. You cannot

    select both methods.


    BINDER ROLLUP

    A Binder Rollup combines several divisions (which are not legal entities) into a legal entity. The system removes Organizer consolidation options from the consolidation binder.

    You must change the entity type to Subsidiary and then the binder rollup entity can be included as a member of a consolidated group.

    To activate Binder Rollup, in a Divisional Consolidation, access the Binder Properties screen and select

    Activate Binder Rollup.



    DIVISIONAL ROLLUP‌

    A Divisional Rollup combines several divisions (which are not legal entities) into a single taxable entity. You must set the entity type to Subconsolidation so the system can complete the consolidation process while still calculating taxes and limitations as if the binder is a single entity.

    A Divisional Rollup binder becomes the filing entity and cannot be a member of a consolidated group.

     The Divisional Rollup method is rarely used.

    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



    To activate a Divisional Rollup, in the Consolidated Organizer, select Consolidated Returns | Step 3 - Select Print and Calculation | Federal Divisional Rollup tab | Option 4.



    DIVISIONAL CONSOLIDATION DECISION TREE‌

    For either Divisional Consolidation method, you must identify and correctly set the options for each entity. The Decision Tree on the next page guides you in selecting the appropriate method (the Typical Divisional Consolidation vs. Binder Rollup) and the required options to select.

    The decisions about which method to use and which options to select is driven primarily by where you enter key data. For instance, the first decision focuses on where Federal Organizer data is entered:

  • If you enter Federal and/or state Organizer data in the Division binders, then use a typical Divisional Consolidation.

  • If you enter both Federal and state Organizer data in the Divisional Consolidation binder, then use the Binder Rollup option.

     Federal Organizer data is defined as detail that is entered directly into the Organizer, such as 4562 detail, 4797 detail, M-3 detail, NOL carryforwards, officer information, etc.

    Subsequent decisions focus on questions such as the following:

  • Where is State Organizer data entered?

  • Where is State A&A data entered?

  • Where are State adjustments entered?


USING THE DECISION TREE

As you progress through the Decision Tree, you will eventually identify one of several scenarios to use for your Divisional Consolidation. Each scenario is described in detail following the Decision Tree.

Refer to the specific scenario section for detailed information about where data should be entered, which options should be selected, and step-by-step instructions for completing the consolidation process using the selected scenario.


ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016

  73. Consolidate using the selected TAS and Organizer options indicated above.

Exception States

States are typically activated at the member level and not in the consolidated binder. However, there is an exception to that rule for some states, which we refer to as exception states. The exception states are:

  • California

  • District of Columbia

  • Illinois

  • Kansas

  • Massachusetts

  • Minnesota

  • Ohio

  • South Carolina

  • West Virginia

  • Wisconsin

    When performing a Divisional Consolidation, the exception states should be activated in the consolidated binder, because these states have combined forms that are different than their single-entity forms.

     Do not activate an exception state in both the member and consolidated binder. This could trigger double calculations.

    1. Mark State to Combine/Consolidate:

      • In the Divisional Consolidation binder, go to Organizer | Consolidated Returns | Step 1 - What to Consolidate.

      • Select the States to Combine/Consolidate tab.


      • Select the states to combine/consolidate.



    2. Add (Activate) the A&A Area in Organizer:

      • In the Division binders, go to Organizer | States | Allocation and Apportionment | A&A Activation.

      • Select Activate the Allocation and Apportionment Area to activate an A&A.

         The Allocation and Apportionment area can also be activated from the Add/Delete | States and Cities screen.



    3. Mark A&A Combine/Consolidate:

      ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



      • In the Divisional Consolidation binder, go to Organizer | Consolidated Returns | Step 1 - What to Consolidate.

      • Select the States to Combine/Consolidate tab.

      • Select Allocation and Apportionment to combine/consolidate A&A data for the selected states.



    CHAPTER 14: STATE PROCESSING‌‌


    STATE ALLOCATION AND APPORTIONMENT‌‌

    ONESOURCE Income Tax offers State Allocation and Apportionment (A&A) Workpaper and Organizer data entry as options for managing state allocation and apportionment information. The primary difference between the two lies in the customization features available in State A&A Workpapers. The graphic below illustrates the data entry methods.



    BENEFITS OF USING STATE A&A WORKPAPERS

  • Allows easy import of data from .csv files.

  • Provides a spreadsheet (workpaper) method of A&A data entry in the TAS portion of a binder.

  • Customized with specific categories, jurisdictions and logic, which determine what categories are included in the A&A factors for each state.

  • Customized presentation of A&A information for each state by using Forms Cross-Reference charts.

  • Review across jurisdictions

  • Transfers A&A data in the TAS workpapers to Organizer.

  • Overall provides efficient and automated state processing.


    BENEFITS OF ORGANIZER STATE A&A

  • Uses the same categories of allocation and apportionment as State A&A Workpapers.

  • Does not allow for customization of the categories, logic or presentation on the tax form.

  • Can override calculated apportionment information.

 The option you select is based on the complexity of the returns, the way data is maintained, or the procedures preferred by the tax department. The remainder of this chapter discusses both options in detail.

 A consistent A&A method should be used for all members of a consolidated group in order to perform a successful consolidation.

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016


STATE A&A WORKPAPER SYSTEM‌‌

The State A&A Workpaper System is comprised of State A&A Charts which are set up in the Charts area and State Workpapers located in the Tax Accounting System.



The state workpapers collect, calculate, and summarize data used to complete portions of the state return forms. Tax data for apportionment factors and allocable income and expenses are entered and summarized on the workpapers.

You can either enter the data manually or import your data into the workpapers. Prior year information needed for the property factor must be entered in the prior year binder and rolls over from year to year.




STATE A&A WORKPAPER SYSTEM SET UP‌‌

The State Workpaper system set up starts with State A&A Charts. You must have administrator rights or adequate permissions to set up the system.

  1. Select Jurisdictions.

  2. Select categories or create sub-categories.

  3. Create and edit logic charts.

  4. Create a State Factor Reconciliation Chart.

  5. Create and edit Forms Cross-Reference charts.

  6. Create User-Defined Filters.

  7. Assign State Workpaper Charts to Binders.

  8. Import or manually enter data into workpapers.

  9. Transfer A&A Workpaper data to Organizer.


JURISDICTIONS‌‌

Jurisdictions enable you to specify the states to use when sourcing data for allocation and apportionment factors. The available jurisdictions include the 50 states, District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, Foreign, and Other.


SELECTING JURISDICTIONS

  1. On the Income Tax menu bar, select Charts.

  2. Select State A&A | Jurisdictions. By default, all jurisdictions are selected.


    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



  3. To select jurisdiction(s), click Add. Use the Remove button to remove jurisdictions from the Selected Jurisdictions list. To add or remove all jurisdictions at once, use the Remove All or Add All buttons.

  4. Verify the check box is selected to create a Throwback column for all workpapers. By default, the check box is selected. Unchecking the box removes the Throwback column from all workpapers.

  5. Click Save.


REMOVING A JURISDICTION

  1. Go to the Jurisdictions screen. All jurisdictions are automatically listed in the Selected Jurisdictions list by default.

  2. From the Selected Jurisdictions list, select any jurisdictions you do not want to use.

  3. Click Remove. The selected jurisdictions move to the Available Jurisdictions list.

  4. If you only need a few jurisdictions, select one state and click Remove All. All the jurisdictions are removed and shown in the Available Jurisdictions list. You now can select the individual jurisdictions from the Available Jurisdictions list and click Add to move them back to the Selected Jurisdictions list.

  5. Select the Select this box to create a throwback column on your State A&A Workpaper check box for the system to handle throwback sales.

  6. Click Save.

 Since jurisdictions are global, only remove a jurisdiction if no entity files in the jurisdiction.


You can remove all jurisdictions by selecting Remove All or add all jurisdictions by selecting Add All.

You cannot remove a jurisdiction from the Selected Jurisdictions field if any binder or entity associated with that jurisdiction contains data. If you attempt to remove it, the following message appears:

If you select Yes, the system shows you a list of binders containing balances for the jurisdiction.


Refer to the “State Workpaper Jurisdiction and Category Tables” on page 387 to see a list of jurisdictions and their system identifier.


CATEGORIES‌‌

Categories summarize each component (property, payroll, sales or allocation) of allocation and apportionment. You can customize the state workpaper system by selecting applicable system defined A&A categories.

Selecting and Creating Categories

  1. On the top menu bar, select Charts.

  2. Select State A&A | Categories.

  3. Categories in the Selected Categories list appear as a row in state workpapers. By default, all default categories are selected for use in workpapers.

  4. Select the appropriate year from the drop-down list.

  5. Click the appropriate tab, Property, Payroll, Sales, or Allocation

  6. Click the + or - buttons to expand or collapse category lists.

  7. To select categories, highlight a category from the Available Categories list and click the Add button.


     Select the minimum number of categories you need. Additional categories may be added later. Categories containing balances cannot be un-selected.

  8. Use the Remove button to remove categories from the Selected Categories list. To add or remove all categories at once, use the Remove All or Add All buttons.

 If a category for Property, Payroll, Sales, and Allocation is removed, it is removed for all existing years.


CREATING SUBCATEGORIES

User-defined subcategories can be added to track data in greater detail at a lower level. Subcategories are added for items that will require logic customization. For example, a LIFO Inventory subcategory might be added to the Inventory category for states that do not allow the LIFO method of inventory valuation in computing the property factor.

  1. On the Categories screen, select the appropriate tab for defining the subcategory.

  2. Select the category where you want to add the subcategory and select New.


  3. Enter the name of the new subcategory. The name can be up to 64 characters.

  4. Choose the implied sign for the new subcategory. The system assumes that all values are entered as positive and totaled on the state workpaper based on the implied sign. For instance, the buildings category has a positive implied sign while accumulated depreciation has a negative implied sign.

  5. Click OK. The new subcategory appears in the category list.

     You can remove a subcategory from the Selected Categories to the Available Categories list by clicking Remove.

    However, if there are any balances for the subcategory in the State Workpapers, you cannot remove it.

  6. Repeat steps 3-6 for each subcategory you wish to add.

  7. Click Yes to update all Cross-Reference charts.

 Do not use double quotations in the subcategory description. Double quotations are reserved characters and must not be used. If used you will encounter problems using state workpapers.

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



EDITING SUBCATEGORIES

  1. Go to the category which contains the subcategory you want to edit.

  2. Expand the category.

  3. Select the subcategory and click Properties.

  4. From the Subcategory Property dialog box, edit the Name (up to 64 characters), and the Implied Sign.

  5. Click Apply, and then OK.

  6. Repeat steps 1- 5 for each subcategory you want to edit.


IMPORTING SUBCATEGORIES

  1. Go to the Category dialog box.

  2. Select a Year.

  3. Click Import.

  4. Click Browse to select the file you wish to import.

  5. Click Import.

  6. If errors are reported, click Error Log to review the errors. Use View or the source file to correct errors then repeat the import process.

 Subcategories imported for Property, Payroll, Sales, and Allocation will be added to all years.


PREPARING A SOURCE FILE TO IMPORT SUBCATEGORIES

You must set up the import file as either a .CSV or .DIF file type.

We recommend you export a state workpaper to use as a template to make sure you have the correct Type and

Category for the subcategories you add.

  1. In your spreadsheet application, open your file or the state workpaper CSV file exported from the application. (Only the Type, Category, and Sub-Category columns will be used. The other columns will be eliminated when formatting this file.)

  2. Modify this file to contain just the new subcategories to import. The spreadsheet file should look like the following:


    TYPE

    CATEGORY

    SUBCATEGORY

    IMPLIED SIGN

    Property

    Buildings

    Name of user defined subcategory

    1

    Payroll

    Cost of Operation

    Name of user defined subcategory


    Sales

    Miscellaneous

    Name of user defined subcategory

    -1

    Allocation

    Other interest

    Name of user defined subcategory



    • Every row must have Type, Category, and Sub-category data.

    • Only rows with new subcategories should be in this file.

    • The implied sign is optional. Leave it blank to default to the sign used for the Category. Use 1 to designate a positive amount. Use -1 to designate a negative amount.

 Important: Do not use double quotations in the subcategory description. They are reserved characters and cannot be used. If you use them, you will encounter problems using state workpapers.

 To see lists of category tables, refer to “State Workpaper Jurisdiction and Category Tables” on page 387.


ADDING LOGIC CHARTS‌‌

The system includes a yearly default A&A logic based on state tax law for most corporations. Logic charts are year specific and can be rolled over from year to year.

You can create user-defined logic charts to assign A&A calculations to categories and sub-categories for each state jurisdiction.

  1. On the top menu bar, select Charts.

  2. Select State A&A | Logic.



  3. On the Chart menu, select Add Chart.



  4. Enter the name for the chart.

  5. Select the Year from the drop-down list.

  6. To copy an existing chart, select the chart from the Copy from: drop-down list.

  7. To apply the defaults to this chart, check Apply default logic to this chart.

  8. Save the chart.

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



Editing the Logic Chart

  1. Select the appropriate chart.

  2. Click Edit.

  3. Click in the cell to make changes and select the appropriate logic from the list.

  4. Click Save or check the save Always check box.

 You cannot change the Default Logic Chart. If you change a Logic Chart that is assigned to binders, you must recompute the binders to see the change(s).


ROLLING OVER THE LOGIC CHART

  1. Select Charts | State A&A | Logic.

  2. Select the Year to rollover.

  3. Select the Logic chart to rollover.

  4. On the browser menu on the left-side, click Rollover.


    LOGIC CHART FACTS

    • Logic charts can be manually entered or imported

    • To use A&A workpapers, binders must have a logic chart assigned to them

    • Logic charts can be individually assigned to binders or assigned through the Enterprise Control Panel.

    • Custom sub-categories inherit logic from the default category and can be edited.

    • Logic codes are used to determine the impact on workpaper factor calculations.

    • Change default logic codes to edit logic charts.


LOGIC CODES


LOGIC CODES

IMPACT ON STATE A&A CALCULATIONS

B

Category/sub-category included in both the numerator and denominator

N

Category/sub-category included in numerator only

D

Category/sub-category included in denominator only

X

No applicable

Blank

Factor excluded by state statute



IMPORTING LOGIC

  1. On the Chart screen, select the chart.

  2. On the top menu bar, select Edit.

  3. From the Logic Chart screen, click Import.

  4. Click Browse.

  5. From the Select Import File list, select the appropriate file.

  6. Click Open.

  7. Click Import.

  8. If there are import errors, open the Error Log.

  9. Make the necessary changes to your file and import again.


EXPORTING LOGIC

  1. From the Logic Chart screen, click Export.

  2. Enter a name for the file.

  3. Open the file in a spreadsheet application and make the appropriate changes.

  4. Save the .csv file.

  5. Follow the steps for importing a file to import the new information into your logic chart.


FORMS CROSS-REFERENCE CHARTS‌

The State Forms Cross-Reference Chart relates the amounts in the State A&A Workpapers to the amounts reported on an individual state tax return. This provides an audit trail, which is beneficial after the tax return has been filed.

You must create a custom Forms Cross-Reference chart for each state (jurisdiction). This custom Forms Cross- Reference is the mechanism used to transfer the amounts from the state workpaper to the state tax return.

The State Workpaper Forms Cross-Reference is used to assign user-defined subcategories to state tax return lines. It allows you to control how data is summarized on a state-by-state basis.

You can create custom forms cross-reference charts by copying an existing chart.


CREATING FORMS CROSS-REFERENCE CHARTS

  1. On the top menu bar, select Charts.

  2. Select State A&A | Forms Cross-Reference.



  3. Select the appropriate Year.

  4. Click New Chart on the menu on the left side.

  5. Enter a Name for the new forms cross-reference chart.

  6. Select the Jurisdiction from the drop-down list.

  7. If copying from another forms cross-reference chart, select the chart from the Copy from: drop-down menu.

  8. Un-check any item you want to exclude in the cross-reference charts.

    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



     All factors are included in the cross-reference charts by default.

  9. Check Suppress automatic tax return presentation to un-assign categories.


EDITING CROSS REFERENCE CHARTS

  1. On the Income Tax menu bar, select Charts

  2. Select State A&A | Forms Cross Reference.

  3. Select the appropriate Year.

  4. Select the Forms Cross-Reference chart and click Edit.


  5. Select the Tax Return Section (Factor) to assign to a category or subcategory. The drop-down menu varies from state to state depending on each state's tax law (i.e. franchise or banking factors).

  6. Click the Add/Delete button to change the tax return sections available in the drop-down list. (Optional)

  7. Select Tax Return Presentation (lines of the tax return) for the categories or subcategories.

  8. In the Unassigned Subcategories list, navigate to the unassigned subcategory by clicking the + beside each category.

  9. Select the appropriate unassigned subcategory and drag it to a yellow folder in the Assigned windows. Yellow folders represent Organizer lines that carry to the state tax return.

  10. Click Save or check Always.

 Items must first be assigned to Everywhere categories before assigning them to Within categories.


STATE FACTOR RECONCILIATION CHART‌‌

Use the State Factor Reconciliation Chart to map State A&A Categories to Federal Tax Return lines. When you assign this chart to a binder, the system populates the associated State Factor Reconciliation workpaper with state category and federal tax return data. The workpaper is inside the binder on the Tax Accounting System navigation tree.


CREATING A STATE FACTOR RECONCILIATION CHART

  1. On the top menu bar, select Charts.

  2. Select State A&A | Reconciliation.




  3. On the Chart menu, select Add Chart.

  4. Enter a name for the chart. The system defaults to the current tax year and the tax return type 1120.

  5. You can copy the Default Chart of Reconciliation or any other existing chart or accept the system default of

    None.

  6. Open the chart.

  7. The chart has three tabs, Property, Payroll, and Sales.


    The tabs for Property, Payroll, and Sales group the state A&A categories and federal tax return lines.

    For Property tax, assign Asset categories to Assets (Schedule L) tax return lines, and Rent categories to Rent expense tax return lines.


  8. The left pane of the screen shows Available Categories. The right pane shows Tax Return Lines/ Categories.

  9. Select one of the Available Categories in the left pane.

  10. Select the appropriate Tax Return Line in the right pane.

  11. Click the Add button to map them.

  12. Use the Remove button to un-map categories and make them available for mapping again to different tax return lines.

  13. When you are finished assigning categories to tax return lines, select Save.

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



ASSIGNING A STATE FACTOR RECONCILIATION CHART TO A BINDER

A State Factor Reconciliation chart must be assigned to a binder for the system to populate the State Factor Reconciliation workpaper with state category and federal tax return data.

  1. On the top menu, select Binders.

  2. Select the appropriate binder.

  3. On the Binders menu bar, select Properties.


  4. Select the State Workpapers tab.

  5. Select the chart from the drop-down list.

You can also assign a State Factor Reconciliation chart to multiple binders by using Enterprise Control Panel.

  1. On the top menu bar, select Tools.

  2. On the left navigation tree, select Enterprise Control Panel | States.

  3. Select the binder year from the Select a Year drop-down list.

  4. Select a chart from the Select State A&A Reconciliation Chart list.

  5. Click Select Binders to select binders to assign to the chart.

  6. After the chart is assigned to a binder, open the Organizer so the system can populate the State Factor Reconciliation workpaper with category and tax return data from the binder.

    Tips:

    • You do not have to use the same chart for all the members of a consolidated group.

    • You can use different charts for different industries within one consolidated group.


CREATING FILTERS‌‌

Filters are defined to customize your workpaper view. Jurisdictions and sub-categories can be filtered from a workpaper presentation. They can be defined, saved, and selected from data entry and review screens.

Filters are setup globally and available for selection in the binder. They are the same for both allocation and apportionment and state taxable income workpapers. They do not affect any system calculations.

  1. On the top menu bar, select Charts.

  2. Select State A&A | Filters.

  3. On the Chart menu bar, select Add Chart.

  4. Select the Year and the click Save.

  5. Double-click the newly created filter to Edit it.

  6. Select the filter items.

  7. Click Save.


ASSIGNING STATE WORKPAPER CHARTS TO BINDERS‌‌

After setting up State A&A Workpapers, Logic, and Forms-Cross-Reference charts, you must assign them to each binder.

The Logic and Forms Cross-Reference charts are assigned to the binder’s properties to control the state A&A workpaper calculations and flow of data to the A&A Organizer Override screen.

You can assign the charts either in the individual binder Properties or in the Enterprise Control Panel.


ASSIGNING CHARTS TO A BINDER ON THE BINDER PROPERTIES SCREEN

  1. On the My Binders screen, select the appropriate binder.

  2. On the menu bar, select Properties.


    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



  3. Select the State A&A Workpapers tab.



  4. Select the Logic Chart from the drop-down list.

  5. Select the State Factor Reconciliation Chart from the drop-down list.

  6. Select the appropriate Forms Cross Reference chart(s) in the Available window and click Add to move the chart(s) to the Assigned window.

  7. Click Update to activate the changes.

 Default Logic and Forms Cross-Reference charts cannot be assigned to binders.


ASSIGNING STATE WORKPAPER CHARTS TO BINDERS WITH THE ENTERPRISE CONTROL PANEL

Using the Enterprise Control Panel allows you to assign Logic and Forms Cross-Reference Charts to multiple binders simultaneously.

  1. On the top menu bar, select Enterprise Control Panel.

  2. Select States | States.



  3. The Year is already selected. To change it click the drop-down list.

  4. Select the State A&A Logic Chart to apply from the drop-down list.

  5. Select the State A&A Reconciliation Chart to apply from the drop-down list.

  6. Select the appropriate Forms Cross-Reference chart(s) in the Available window and click Add to move the chart(s) to the State Forms Cross-Reference Charts Assigned window.

  7. Check the Toggle Update with State A&A On so State A&A detail will transfer to Organizer.

  8. Check the Toggle Update with State A&A Off so State A&A detail will not transfer to Organizer.

    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



  9. Click Select Binder Group or Select Binders.


    Select Binder Groups


    Select Binders



  10. Select either a Binder Group or a Workarea. The Year is selected from the previous screen.

  11. Click Search. The binder groups and binders that fit the criteria appear in the Assignment area. The system defaults to selecting all binders.

  12. Select the binders for chart assignment. A green check mark appears over selected binders and binders.

  13. Click Select All if all binders should receive the chart assignments.

  14. To select multiple binders, select the first binder and then hold down the Shift key and select the last binder.

    All the binders between the first binder and the last binder will be selected.

  15. Click Select to apply the option to all the highlighted binders.

  16. Click OK.

  17. Click Yes to verify assignment of the charts. The message Enterprise Control Panel Charts Updated

    appears.

  18. Click OK to return to the Enterprise Control Panel Charts screen.

     You must have Administrator rights to use the Enterprise Control Panel.

  19. After assigning the reconciliation chart to a binder, open the Organizer so the system can populate the State Factor Reconciliation workpaper with category and tax return data from the binder.

Reconciliation Chart Tips

  • You do not have to use the same chart for all the members of a consolidated group.

  • You can use different charts for different industries within one consolidated group.


    ENTERING DATA INTO STATE A&A WORKPAPERS IN THE TAX ACCOUNTING SYSTEM‌‌

    After customizing state workpapers and assigning Logic and Forms Cross-Reference charts, enter state workpaper data in the TAS area of a binder.

    There are two methods of State A&A Workpaper data entry:

  • Manual - Enter data directly in white workpaper cells.

  • Import - Export a blank customized A&A template, enter A&A data into the template and save it as a .csv file. Using the saved file, import State A&A data from the .csv file to State A&A Workpapers in TAS.


    MANUALLY ENTERING STATE WORKPAPER DATA

    1. Open a binder.

    2. On the TAS navigation tree, select State Workpapers. The State Workpaper area, provides spreadsheet views on a Data Entry - Corporate Entity or Single state basis. The Corporate Entity allows users to enter or review multiple states by factor, the single state allows users to enter or review by individual state(s).

    3. Select the appropriate factor for data entry. The following image shows the Property screen.



    4. Expand the Factor, Category, and Subcategories.

    5. Enter data into the workpaper.

    6. Continue selecting workpapers until all the information is entered.

     You can only enter data in white cells. Blue and orange cells are protected fields and designate calculated amounts or totals.

    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



    PREPARING A SOURCE FILE TO IMPORT STATE WORKPAPERS

    You can prepare a source file as a .csv or dif file to import data for state workpapers. The import requires the following elements:

  • name, category, and subcategory

  • jurisdiction

  • balance

    FROM A GENERAL LEDGER PROGRAM. If you exported your source file from a general ledger program as a csv or dif file, we recommend you open your file up in a spreadsheet application to make sure it is prepared correctly.

    USING A SPREADSHEET APPLICATION. If you are setting up the source import file using a spreadsheet application, the application must support csv or dif file types. We recommend exporting a state workpaper from ONESOURCE Income Tax to use in your spreadsheet program to enter workpaper amounts.


    IMPORTING STATE WORKPAPER DATA

    1. Open a binder.

    2. From the TAS navigation tree, click State Workpapers.

    3. Select Data Entry | State A&A | [Corporate Entity (excluding Partnerships), States (with partnership detail)] | [Property, Payroll, Sales, Allocation or All State A&A].

    4. Click Import.

    5. Click Browse to select the import file. It must be a .csv file.

    6. Click Import.

    7. If there are import errors, open the Error Log.

    8. Make the necessary changes to your file and import again.


    STATE WORKPAPER DESCRIPTION‌





    WORKPAPER FEATURE

    DESCRIPTION

    Jurisdictions

    Columns of the workpaper.

    Categories/Subcategories

    Rows of the workpaper.

    Control Total

    —First column of the workpaper.

    —User defined amounts that equals the sum of the Jurisdiction and Throwback columns.

    —If the Control Total column, does not equal the Everywhere column total, then the offsetting balance is in the Unallocated column.

    Throwback

    —Third from the end of the workpaper.

    —Sum of all Throwback amounts in the workpaper.

    —Individual amounts can be designated as throwback amounts by selecting a cell and checking the Enable or disable throwback for the current cell.

    —When activated, the amount from that cell is added to the Unallocated and Throwback columns.

    Unallocated

    —Second from the end of the workpaper.

    —Calculated when there is an amount in the Control Total column.

    —Result of Control Total minus each Jurisdiction plus Throwback.

    Everywhere

    —Last column of the workpaper.

    —Sum of all Jurisdictions less Throwbacks plus Unallocated amounts.


    ENTERING OR REVIEWING WORKPAPER DATA


    1. Expand the appropriate row on the workpaper by clicking or the + next to categories or subcategories.

    2. Enter or change amounts in the white fields for the Control Total and each applicable Jurisdiction. Click Enter

      after an entry to move the cursor to the next field.

    3. If applicable, select the Enable or disable throwback for the current cell check box. When this is activated, the Throwback and Unallocated columns will increase by the amount entered in that cell.

      • The Unallocated column calculates only when an amount is in the Control Total. It is the Control Total value decreased by the values entered for each jurisdiction that is not a throwback cell.

      • The Everywhere column equals the sum of all jurisdictions less throwback plus unallocated amounts.

    4. Click Save or check the Always check box to save automatically. Notes:

  • All the values that you enter should be positive, regardless of whether they are debits or credits.

  • Enter a negative number only as an exception, when the value should be handled as a contra amount.

  • If the item is incorrectly entered as a negative value (in other words, the item was not a contra amount), the value transfers incorrectly to the tax application, and the resulting calculations will be incorrect.

  • Each system-defined category has a default implied sign.

  • The user-defined categories use the sign assigned to them when they were created (the default is the sign of the category under which they were created.) The system calculates workpaper data based on the implied sign of the category.

    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



    UPDATING ORGANIZER WITH STATE WORKPAPERS

    After entering all state workpapers data and assigning logic and cross-reference charts, you must compute the binder to transfer the state workpaper balances into the A&A area of Organizer.

    1. In a binder, on the Tax Accounting System navigation tree, select Compute.

    2. On the Domestic Compute tab, select the Update Organizer with State A&A check box.

       This option is only available if you have assigned logic and cross-reference charts to the binder.

    3. Click Compute.

    4. Click Close to exit.

     Data will not transfer or compute in the tax forms unless states have been activated. Data transfers into the A&A Organizer/Overrides for each state.

    Best Practice

    Once you have entered your A&A data and run a compute with the Update Organizer with State A&A, un- check the option. Doing so reduces your compute times and the system will not update State A&A again.

    Reviewing and Reconciling State Workpaper Data

  • State A&A Workpaper information transfers from TAS to the A&A Organizer/Overrides area in Organizer.

  • From Organizer, it then flows to individual state tax returns.

  • In the State A&A Review Workpapers you can reconcile detail amounts that are summarized on the state forms to verify the data is flowing to the forms based on your A&A data entry and setup or customization.


STATE FACTOR RECONCILIATION WORKPAPERS‌‌

Each variation of this workpaper enables you to review variances for the State A&A factors. The variances compare the federal tax return lines to data you have entered for State A&A Everywhere in the Tax Accounting System.

The initial setup for this workpaper starts with creating a State Factor Reconciliation Chart.


STATE FACTOR RECONCILIATION WORKPAPER FOR A SINGLE COMPANY

Use the State Factor Reconciliation workpaper for a single company to review variances for the State A&A factors. The variances compare the federal tax return form lines to data you have entered for the Tax Accounting System State A&A Everywhere factor. The workpaper allows you to enter explanations for each variance at the Tax Return line and at the State Factor level or both.

  1. Open a binder.

  2. On the TAS navigation menu, select State Workpapers.

  3. Expand the State Workpaper folder and then the Review folder.

  4. Select the State Factor Reconciliation workpaper.


    The system displays the data from the Tax Return Form Lines and the TAS State A&A Categories data entry workpaper (based on the Reconciliation Chart assigned to the binder).

  5. The variance for each tax return line is automatically calculated and displayed in the Variances column.

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



WORKPAPER DATA ENTRY FOR EXPLANATIONS

Add explanations for variances at either the Factor level and/or at the Tax Return Line level. The system maintains the variances in a master list for the entire account.

You can use explanations multiple times within the binder or account but can only use them one time at each factor level or in any given tax return line.

Adding Explanations

  1. Select the Tax Form Lines/TAS A&A Categories cell where you wish to add the explanation.

  2. Right-click or on the toolbar in the Variance section, click Add.


  3. Click the drop-down list to see a list of all the explanations available or enter the explanation in the

    Description box to see a filtered list based on the entered letters.


  4. Enter a value if applicable.

  5. Click OK.

  6. Enter or edit workpaper values directly on the workpaper by selecting the cell and entering the value or you can right-click on the description or cell and select Edit. You can also use the Edit icon in the Variances section of the toolbar.

  7. To remove explanations, either click the Remove icon in the Variances section of the toolbar or select the description or cell that displays the amount, right-click and select Remove.

  8. A confirmation will appear and confirm removing the explanation. The explanation will be removed from the workpaper but still be in the master list of explanations for the account.


MANAGING ACCOUNT EXPLANATIONS

  1. On the toolbar, in the Manage section, select Explanations.



    The system displays a list of all the explanations added for the account in alphabetical order. You can insert (add), edit, or delete the explanations.


  2. To add an explanation, select Insert.

  3. In the Explanations dialogue box, enter the explanation and then select OK. The item is inserted into the alphabetical list.

  4. To edit or delete an explanation, select the explanation.

  5. A list of the binders that currently use the explanation appears for your review.

  6. If you edit the explanation, a confirmation request appears to confirm the change. If you delete the explanation, the system gives instructions regarding what action to take when you delete it.


EXPORTING AND PRINTING

  1. To export the State Factor Reconciliation workpaper, click Export. You can either export to an Excel *.XLSX format or a *CSV format.


  2. To print the State Factor Reconciliation workpaper, click Print. You can print in portrait or landscape. We default the print to portrait.

  3. To print in landscape click Print, then select Preferences and change it to landscape.

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



STATE FACTOR RECONCILIATION CONSOLIDATED SUMMARY WORKPAPER‌

Use the State Factor Reconciliation workpaper to review variances for the State A&A factors. The variances compare the federal tax return form lines to data you have entered for the Tax Accounting System State A&A Everywhere factor data. The workpaper allows you to enter explanations for each variance at the Tax Return line and at the State Factor level or both. In addition, you can enter explanations at the consolidated level on the Consolidated Summary and Consolidated Columnar workpapers.


ACCESSING STATE FACTOR RECONCILIATION IN TAS

  1. Open a consolidated binder.

  2. On the TAS navigation menu, select State Workpapers.

  3. Expand the State Workpaper folder and then the Review folder.

  4. Select the State Factor Reconciliation workpaper. The system displays the data from the Tax Return Form Lines and the TAS State A&A Categories data entry workpaper (based on the Reconciliation Chart assigned to the binder).

  5. The variance for each tax return line is automatically calculated and displayed in the Variances column.


    VARIANCE EXPLANATIONS‌

    You can add explanations for variances at either the Factor level or at the Tax Return Line level. The system maintains the variances in a master list for the entire account. The members of the consolidation with explanations are displayed as Read Only at the Tax Return Line or the Factor level.

    • In the consolidated binder, explanations entered at the factor level as consolidated amounts are displayed under the Consolidated heading.

    • If you enter explanations in the members, at the factor level, they are displayed under the From Members

      heading.

    • If you enter explanations at the tax return line level, from the members or entered explanations at the consolidated level, amounts are displayed in the row as Explanations associated with specific return lines.

    • You can use explanations multiple times within the binder or account but they are restricted to being used only once at each factor level or in any given tax return line.


ADDING EXPLANATIONS

  1. Select the factor or tax return line where you wish to add the explanation.

  2. Right-click or on the toolbar in the Variance section, Add.

  3. Click the drop-down list to see a list of all the explanations available or enter the explanation in the

    Description box to see a filtered list based on the entered letters.

  4. Enter a value if applicable.

  5. Click OK.

  6. Enter or edit workpaper values directly on the workpaper by selecting the cell and entering the value or you can right-click on the description or cell and select Edit. You can also use the Edit icon in the Variances section of the toolbar.

  7. To remove explanations, either click the Remove icon in the Variances section of the toolbar or select the description or cell that displays the amount, right-click and select Remove.

  8. A confirmation will appear and confirm removing the explanation. The explanation will be removed from the workpaper but still be in the master list of explanations for the account.


MANAGING ACCOUNT EXPLANATIONS

  1. On the toolbar, in the Manage section, select Explanations. A list of all the explanations added for the account is displayed in alphabetical order. You can insert (add), edit, or delete the explanations.

  2. To add an explanation, select Insert.

  3. In the Explanations dialogue box, enter the explanation and then select OK. The item will be inserted into the alphabetical list.

  4. To edit or delete an explanation, select the explanation.

  5. A list of the binders that currently use the explanation appears for your review.

  6. If you edit the explanation, a confirmation request appears to confirm the change or if you want to delete the explanation, then the system will give instructions regarding what action to take.


EXPORTING AND PRINTING

  1. To export the State Factor Reconciliation workpaper, click Export. You can either export to an Excel *.XLSX format or a *CSV format.

  2. To print the State Factor Reconciliation workpaper, click Print. You can print in portrait or landscape. We default the print to portrait.

  3. To print in landscape click Print, then select Preferences and change to landscape.

STATE TAXABLE INCOME WORKPAPER SYSTEM‌‌

The State Taxable Income (TI) Workpaper system gives the flexibility to create up to 500 custom subcategories to use for state modifications and apportioned income adjustments. It allows you to control each aspect of the flow of data to the tax return.




Import and export capabilities are available for all aspects of the setup process – including setting up subcategories, assigning them to applicable jurisdictions, and setting up Forms Mapping charts used for transferring data to and from the tax return. These capabilities are available in both individual binder and batch modes.

Workpaper screens for State Tax Expense and Payments of Tax have also been added.

 This system is applicable for 1120 corporations (only), for years after 2002.

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



STATE TAXABLE INCOME FOR INSURANCE RETURNS‌‌

For the 2012 tax year, we added the State TI Workpapers for insurance binders. New York, Mississippi, Michigan, Oregon have insurance specific forms to file for insurance companies. For those states, a Forms Mapping Chart allows you to create insurance mapping charts so you can map the additions and subtractions for state modifications to the insurance forms and schedules. For other states, you can assign the income type of mapping chart to insurance binders.


JURISDICTIONS‌

Adding State TI Jurisdictions

  1. From the Home Window, click Charts | State TI Workpapers | Jurisdictions.

    The jurisdictions are the same jurisdictions used for State Allocation and Apportionment. Selected jurisdic- tions appear in the right pane of the screen.


  2. All jurisdictions are selected by default.

  3. To add or remove jurisdictions, select the jurisdiction and click either Add or Remove. You can also click Remove All and then add back the applicable jurisdictions. Hold down the Ctrl key to multi-select states, then click Add All.


Creating a State TI Forms Mapping Chart

  1. In the Home Window, select Charts | State TI Workpapers | Forms Mapping.

  2. Click New to create a new Forms Mapping Chart. The State TI Mapping New Chart dialog box opens.

  3. Select the applicable state from the drop-down list.


    State TI Mapping New Chart


  4. Select the Return Type: Income, Financial, or Insurance.

  5. Enter the name for the new chart.

  6. Select the chart to copy, from the drop-down list.

  7. Click Save and Close.

  8. Open the newly created Forms Mapping chart for a jurisdiction to see the unassigned subcategories in the left pane, and the applicable tax form lines in the right-hand pane.


New Forms Mapping Chart

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



AUTOMATIC CALCULATIONS LEGEND‌

The forms mapping charts have colored indicators to visually show how each line on the state workpaper is determined.


None (blank)

Refers to lines that have no automatic calculations.


Federal

The amount flows from the federal return to the state return if the state is activated in Organizer.


State

Refers to fields that are automatically calculated for the state from the Common State area in the tax application.

Override

Indicates that a particular tax form line comes from a schedule that requires activity detail entered in the Organizer or a unique computation is performed on another schedule. This detail must be entered in the Organizer or use the State TI Workpapers to override the schedule.



FEDERAL

Amounts flow from the federal return to the state return unless:

  • A subcategory has been assigned in the Forms Mapping chart for the state return type (income tax or financial), and data has been entered on the data entry workpaper for this line in the binder, or

  • There is an override for the federal amount entered in the state organizer - with or without a valid subcategory code, or

  • The option to toggle off automatic calculations from federal has been selected on the Enterprise Control Panel by navigating to Tools | Enterprise Control Panel | States | State TI Workpapers tab, and then selecting the applicable entities and binders.

    Examples of federal adjustments include such items as Interest from US obligations, Foreign Dividend Gross- up, Federal Depletion, Subpart F Income, and the Work Opportunity Credit.


    STATE

    State adjustment examples are Taxes, Depreciation (all flow through the state depreciation area), State and Local bond interest, State Gains, and State Dividends.


    OVERRIDE

    Override fields in the state Organizer screens are the target fields for the State TI data entry workpapers. If a state modification/adjustment is marked as an override in the Forms Mapping legend, it will always appear on the Organizer/Override line on the Single-State Review workpapers.

     If a state modification/adjustment is marked as an override in the Form Mapping legend, it will always appear on the Organizer/Override line on the review workpapers.


    SETTING UP CUSTOM SUBCATEGORIES‌

    You can add user-defined subcategories manually or by import under existing categories in the system. The system includes predefined Categories. All data is setup in user-defined subcategories under these categories.

    We recommend that you follow these rules when creating user-defined categories:

  • A user is limited to 500 subcategories, total, for the State Modifications workpaper.

  • Subcategories are defined via a three to twelve-digit alphanumeric character code.


  • The first two-digits of the code are system-defined and correspond to the category under which the sub- category is set up. The remaining characters are user-defined and can be comprised of numbers or letters or both.

  • The length of the description is limited to 50 characters.

  • Subcategories rollover from year to year.


    CREATING SUBCATEGORIES

    1. From the Income Tax menu bar, select Charts | State TI Workpapers | Categories.



    2. Choose whether the category will be an Addition, Subtraction, or Adjustment to federal income.

      ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



    3. Click New.

    4. Assign the alpha-numeric code and description.



    5. Click Save.

    6. Close the chart. You will see the new subcategory in the Category Assignment chart.

     You can import all subcategories from a file containing the subcategory code and description.


    ASSIGNING SUBCATEGORIES TO STATE JURISDICTIONS‌‌

    The system defaults for all subcategories to be applicable to all states. You must map the subcategories to the appropriate type of return (Income Only, Financial Only, Insurance Only, All Form Types) to transfer data to the tax return.

    For 2012 and forward, we added functionality for states (Michigan, Mississippi, New York, Oregon) that have separate 1120 forms to file for insurance returns. The additions and subtractions for state modifications can be mapped using a State TI Insurance Mapping Chart to the insurance forms and schedules.

    1. From the Home Window, select Charts | State TI Workpapers | Category Assignment.

    2. In the drop-down list, select the appropriate type of return Income Only, Financial Only, Insurance Only, All Form Types.


    New drop-down selections.


    IMPORTING JURISDICTIONS

    1. Click Export. Using the file, add columns to the file for each jurisdiction.

    2. Add a 1 (one) under each state jurisdiction if that subcategory applies. A 0 (zero) indicates not applicable.

    3. On the Category Assignment screen, click Import to re-import the file. The check mark that appears indicates that the subcategory applies to that jurisdiction. Subcategories can be unassigned but not deleted.


    MAPPING FOR RETURNS‌‌

    You can create mapping for income, financial, and insurance returns. The capability to map for insurance returns was added for 2012 returns and later. The mapping for each type of return is designated with a graphic in front of the jurisdiction.

  • The letter I indicates an income return map.

  • The letter F indicates a financial return map.

  • The letter N indicates an insurance return map.


The different types are designated by symbols in front of the jurisdiction. Income Tax


Financial


Insurance


Mapping the Subcategories to lines on the State Tax Return

  1. On the State TI Forms Mapping screen, select the Return Type: Income Tax, Financial, or Insurance.

  2. Enter a name for the chart in one of the following formats which coincide with the return type:


    Income Tax PrefixStateNameIncTax

    Financial PrefixStateNameFin

    Insurance PrefixStateNameInsurance


  3. Select the Jurisdictions and click Save. Shell assignments are created automatically for each of the applicable jurisdictions.

  4. Check the Unassigned Subcategory in the left pane, check the tax form line in the right pane, and then click

    Add to assign where the selected subcategory flows to the tax return.

  5. Subcategories can be unassigned by putting a check mark next to the subcategory in the right pane and clicking Remove, provided there is not a balance in any binder that is using the subcategory.

ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



Globally Turning Off System Automatic Adjustments

You can turn off automatic calculations in one of two ways:

  1. Map the line in the Forms Mapping chart for the applicable state. This allows you to enter data for the subcategory on the State TI Data Entry Workpaper. Or, globally turn off automatic entries on the Enterprise Control Panel.

  2. From the Tools tab, select Enterprise Control Panel | States | State TI Workpapers tab.

  3. Click the Yes to suppress system automatic calculations.

  4. Click Select Entites/Binders or Binder Group.

  5. Select the binders or group to apply this option.


ASSIGN FORM MAPPING CHARTS TO BINDERS WITH THE ENTERPRISE CONTROL PANEL‌

You can either use the Enterprise Control Panel or manually assign the chart for form mapping to binders.


USING THE ENTERPRISE CONTROL PANEL

This feature allows you to assign charts to multiple binders.

  1. On the Tools tab, select Enterprise Control Panel | States.



  2. Select the State TI Workpapers tab.

  3. Select the applicable charts, holding down the Ctrl key to multi-select charts, and then click Add. The selected charts now display under Assigned Charts.



    You can also set State TI compute functions for multiple binders on this screen.

  4. Click Select Binders or Binder Group in the lower left hand corner.

  5. Click the drop-down list for the Workarea or Binder Group listing and select the workarea or Binder Group containing the appropriate binders. Select the specific binders to apply the Forms Mapping charts to all binders.

  6. Click OK.


MANUALLY ASSIGNING A CHART

  1. Select a binder.

  2. On the menu bar, select Properties | State TI Workpapers.



  3. In the Available pane, select the appropriate forms mapping chart and click Add.

  4. Click Update and then Close.

Therefore, each of these states will have two Forms Mapping Charts.


STATE TI WORKPAPER IMPORT‌

You can import all modifications and apportioned income adjustments used to calculate state taxable income. The amounts flow to the correct lines of the state tax returns for all entities and binders. The modifications and adjustments are predetermined by you, so you do not need automatic calculations or overrides from the tax application. This method allows you to control all applicable adjustments for the entire consolidated group.

 As with all taxable income workpapers, amounts entered as zeros transfer a value of “none” to the Organizer. You must activate the states in Organizer and compute the binder in order for the jurisdictions to appear in the review workpapers.

The resulting data and review worksheets in TAS will be the same when they are done. You must map all the subcategories correctly to specific lines on the state tax return forms. Turn off automatic tax adjustments that flow to the review screens and do not use organizer/override entries.

The system contains certain specific tax form lines that do not have codes associated with them. If any of these are used, they appear as an override on the workpaper.

Importing Adjustments into the State TI Workpaper

  1. Open the binder.

  2. On the TAS navigation tree, select State Workpaper to open the workpaper navigation tree.



  3. Select Data Entry | Taxable Income and Taxes | Modifications and Apportioned Income Adjustments.



  4. Click the Import button.

  5. Browse to the .csv file containing the subcategory codes, descriptions, and amounts by jurisdictions.

  6. Click Import.

  7. Compute the binder by selecting Compute, then Compute.

 Data Import is also available in batch mode.


IMPORTING IN BATCH MODE

  1. On the Income Tax menu bar, select Batch.



  2. Select a Binder Group, then click Next.

  3. In the Batch Operation area, click Import.

  4. Select the State tab.

    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



  5. Browse to the location of your .CSV file.

  6. Click Import.

  7. On the Enterprise Control Panel, select State | State TI Workpaper.

  8. Select the option Update Organizer with State TI TAS for binders or the Binder Group.

  9. From the Tools tab, click Batch | Binder Group.

  10. Select a Binder Group and click Next.

  11. In the Batch Operation area, click Compute to compute all the binders simultaneously.


CREATING A BATCH IMPORT TEMPLATE FOR STATE TAXABLE INCOME

  1. Open a binder to TAS | State Workpaper | Taxable Income and Taxes | Modifications and Appointed Income Adjustments.

  2. At Modifications and Apportioned Income Adjustments click Export.

  3. Enter the location to Save As and the file name.

  4. Click Save. (Make sure the file is saved as CSV.)

  5. Open the file and insert a column to the far left (Column A).


  6. Enter the unique company number on all rows with sub-category codes. (Go to Entity | Binder Properties to find the Company number.)

  7. Copy and paste this template to the first empty row and change the company number to reflect the next binder to import.

  8. Enter the applicable data for the binder.

  9. Repeat copying the template and entering the company number and data for all binders to import in batch.


STATE TI WORKPAPER FILTERS‌‌

Use filters to remove subcategories or jurisdictions from the view screens. They can be defined, saved, and selected from data entry and review screens. They are the same for both Allocation and Apportionment and State TI workpapers.

Creating a Filter

  1. On the Charts screen, select Filters.

  2. Select the Year of the chart.

  3. On the menu bar, select New | Chart or select a chart in the list.

  4. To edit a filter, select the filter, on the menu bar, select Edit.

  5. Select the jurisdictions you wish to display in the left pane and click Add. They will appear in the right pane.

  6. Click the Sub-Categories tab to determine what sub-categories you wish to display.

  7. Click Save.

The system also gives you an option to view and compute State TI Workpapers listed in columnar format for multiple binders. The Columnar Workpaper is designed to show a list of entities for a single taxable income calculation.

Columnar Workpapers can also be used to view or edit separate state data for filing separate company returns for states such as Alabama. Multiple binder and state selection scenarios can be set up from this area for easy access to data entry, compute, and review. A Binder Group cannot have more than 120 binders for workpaper viewing purposes.

    Expand the Additions, Subtractions, and Apportioned Income Adjustments sections to see the subcategories. The subcategories display the user-defined account number and the user-defined descriptions. The system pulls the amounts on each of these lines from the tax application when:

      STATE TI COLUMNAR WORKPAPERS‌‌

      ONESOURCE Income Tax State TI Workpapers also gives you an option to view and compute State TI Workpapers listed in columnar format for multiple binders. The Columnar Workpaper is designed to show a list of entities for a single taxable income calculation. The view for this calculation can be further modified for listing the workpaper for review only or it can be used to enter data for the following three types of data:

    • Modifications and apportioned income adjustments

    • Tax payments

    • Tax expense

Columnar Workpapers can also be used to view or edit separate state data for filing separate company returns for states such as Alabama. Multiple binder and state selection scenarios can be set up from this area for easy access to data entry, compute, and review.

  1. Open a binder.

  3. Expand the State Workpapers | Review and select NOL.


  4. On the NOL Workpaper screen, select the applicable state from the drop-down list.


  5. In a single member binder, this list includes the states you activated in Organizer | States | Add/Delete | States and Cities. In consolidated binders, the list includes those states which you designated as consolidated/combined in Organizer | Consolidated Returns | Step 1 - What to Consolidate | States to Combine/Consolidate, in addition to those activated in Organizer.

  6. Selecting a state generates a workpaper which summarizes the Net Operating Loss, with years for loss carryover generated in rows, and years for loss utilized in columns. The first column of loss data displays the loss carryover remaining at the end of the year. In addition to the year columns, the workpaper contains a

    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



    Prior Year Utilization (no detail provided) column. The purpose of this column is to capture the amount of prior year utilization of an NOL where you elected to not provide year by year detail.

  7. If you want to view the workpaper without seeing the navigation tree on the left, click the View Full Screen

    button. To return to the standard view, press the Esc key.

  8. This workpaper is read only. Click Export to save the data in .csv, .xls and .xlm formats. Multistate Review Workpaper

The multistate review workpaper has a separate column for each state that has been activated. This workpaper

can be exported and printed.

  2. The subcategory is mapped in the forms mapping chart (unless you are an Organizer-only user and have not entered anything on the Data Entry worksheets).


Single-State Review Workpaper

RECONCILIATION TOOLS‌‌

Total modifications on the tax return and total modifications on the Taxable Income Data Entry Workpaper should be the same. The following review tools help you reconcile differences and understand the flow of data to the return.

If the total modification numbers are different, there are four reasons why:

  1. Override Amounts - The user overrode amounts entered in the Taxable Income Data Entry workpaper in Organizer.

     Turn off the option update Organizer with State TI TAS to keep overrides during Compute.

  2. Automatic Calculations - The user chose not to enter a modification for any given modification, but chose instead to use the automatic calculation in the Tax Application.

  3. Invalid Subcategory Codes - The user entered amounts into Organizer without using a valid subcategory code.

  4. Override Amounts on the tax form - The user overrode amounts directly on the Tax Forms. System Features

The following section describes the system features:

  • The system compares the amount entered in the data entry fields and the amount pulled back for each subcategory. If the amount pulled back is different from the amount entered, the system displays a visual indicator to alert you to the fact that the number in the return is not the number that was entered in the TI data entry. This enables the user to see differences caused by State TI data entry. (Multi-state and Single-state)

  • There is a system-defined subcategory for each Category which includes the word “Auto”. Data entry is not allowed for this subcategory. The results of any modification made as a result of automatic calculations in the tax application are displayed here. This information comes from the tax application, and enables you to see differences caused by the second reason above. (Multi-state only.)

  • There are system defined Other adjustments for each Total Additions, Total Subtractions, and Total Apportioned Income Adjustments. The Total Additions per the return are compared with the sum of the subcategories (including the TaxAuto defined above). Any difference is reflected in the Organizer/override system-defined category on the Single-State Review workpaper. Total Subtractions and Total

    ONESOURCE Income Tax 2016



    Apportioned Income Adjustments also work in the same manner. This enables you to see differences caused by number three and four above.

  • State credits do not display individually - only in total for each state. (Multi-state).

CHAPTER 15: STATE CONSOLIDATIONS‌‌


STATE COMBINED VS.CONSOLIDATED RETURNS‌‌

A combined return calculates each entity’s taxable income, applies limitations to the total amounts and totals all entities to reach the combined taxable income. The graphic below illustrates the combined return process.



A consolidated return sums amounts from each entity, totals them at the top consolidation level and applies limitations to the total amounts.




In general, the same preparation processes apply to both consolidated and combined state returns.



Combined/Consolidated State or City Returns
