THE STATE CONSOLIDATION PROCESS‌‌

The process for preparing state combined or consolidated returns is almost identical to the federal consolidation process.

  1. Create new or use existing binders

  2. Complete member binders

  3. Consolidate!

  4. Review and revise

  5. Print the state combined or consolidated return

 For more about Divisional Consolidations, see Chapter 8, State Consolidations.


PRE-CONSOLIDATION

We recommend doing the following before continuing the state combined/consolidation process:

  1. Enter state data consistently across all members of the consolidation. This includes activating desired states and the allocation and apportionment area of each member of the consolidation (even if a lower level binder does not file in a particular state, i.e. eliminations.)

    Detail Consistency. Keeping the level of detail consistent for each company in the consolidated group is the key to a successful consolidation. The consolidation process sums the TAS and Organizer fields. TAS fields are naturally consistent because of their direct tie to TRC codes that transfer data to Federal Organizer fields and eventually to activated states. Conversely, Organizer information is entered in fields that do not have TRC codes associated with them.

    For example, allocation and apportionment can be entered in State Organizer by two different methods. Therefore you must be sure to maintain consistency from entity to entity for consolidation purposes. Data is most commonly entered inconsistently in the following ways:

    • Activating States and the A&A areas within each binder including the eliminations binder.

    • General data entry (adjustments, eliminations, etc.)

      ONESOURCE 2016



    • State A&A Organizer overrides and Organizer A&A data entry.

      We recommend that you enter data at the lowest level of detail in Organizer on all binders.

  2. Clear all binder overrides and diagnostics.

  3. Balance and fully recompute all individual and company returns.

BINDER SETUP

If you filed a federal consolidation return using the software, much of your work is complete. You may use the existing binders which were created for filing the federal return to file the state return.

 Please refer to the Federal Consolidation chapter for more information about consolidation entities and binders.

New binders may be needed for:

  • Consolidation binders if the state return members are different from your federal, if you did not process a federal consolidation, or if you want to maintain separate data files for state purposes.

  • Entities in your combined group for which you are not using an existing federal return binder.

 Within the Common State and individual state folders in Organizer is the ability to activate the state you wish to combine or consolidate. By activating the state, the application automatically carries a basic set of data from the federal entries to the state return you indicate. Special state allowances and reporting requirements are built into the state application.

COMPLETING MEMBER BINDERS

The state combines/consolidates the amounts from the parent binder, the elimination binder, and each subsidiary binder. Sub-consolidations and/or divisional consolidations may be included as well.

Each member binder must be completed individually before you can generate an accurate combined/ consolidated return. This includes completing the federal return, entering allocation and apportionment data, activating the state, entering state adjustments, and state specific entries.

If this combination/consolidation contains a subconsolidation or divisional consolidation, you must:

  1. Complete the binder(s) for each lower tier of the consolidation.

  2. Consolidate the divisional consolidation or subconsolidation prior to including them in the top consolidation.

See “Chapter 14: State Processing” on page 342 for steps to complete the member binders. In addition to the subsidiary binders, you must also use an elimination binder. You can use the same elimination binder from the Federal consolidation or create a new one for the state combined/consolidated return.

 When entering data, be sure to keep the level of detail consistent for each company in the consolidated group.


CONSOLIDATED BINDER MEMBERS TAB

Once all the member binders have been completed, you must create a consolidated binder. The federal consolidated binder can be used for combined/consolidated state filings if the members are the same. If the members are different for any particular filing, you must create a separate top consolidation binder.

When you create the binder, select the appropriate members for the consolidated group on the Member tab on the Binder Properties screen.

Refer to the following topics in Chapter 9: Federal Consolidations for step-by-step information about: Consolidating Entities and Binders

Creating Binders for Consolidations Entering Eliminating Entries

Adding Members to a Consolidated Binder Selecting Members

  1. Select a binder.

  2. On the menu bar, select Properties.

  3. Click the Members tab.

  4. Click the Add button on the right-side of the screen to add the Elimination binder.

  5. Select the appropriate workarea. The workarea where the consolidation binder was created is automatically selected.

  6. In the Entities in Selected Workareas, select the Elimination binder.

  7. Click OK. The elimination entity is added.

  8. Below the Entity area, click Add to select the member binders.

  9. Select the appropriate workarea.

  10. In the Entities in Selected Workareas section, select the entities and binders. Use either the Shift key or click Select All to choose more than one.

  11. Click Apply and then Close. The selected entities and binders will now appear in the Members tab.

ONESOURCE 2016



CONSOLIDATING ORGANIZER‌‌

Once the consolidation of the subsidiary listing screen is complete, consolidate Organizer. The organizer consolidation process consolidates detail entered in the various member binders such as Form 4562 detail, Form 4797 detail, M3 detail NOL carryforwards, etc. The consolidation binder holds the results of the consolidation. Enter only a minimal amount of data in the consolidation binder, since each time you consolidate, the application deletes Organizer data and replaces it with the new consolidated amounts.


Complete the consolidation steps in Organizer.

These appear on the navigation menu Organizer | States | State Combined Returns | State Consolidation Steps.


STEP 1 - WHAT TO CONSOLIDATE

Refer to “Step 1 - What to Consolidate” on page 253.

  • Consolidated Return List tab. Confirm the members listed here.

  • Federal Forms to Consolidate tab. This tab is not needed for state consolidations.

  • States to Combine/Consolidate tab. Use this tab to activate states for which you which to file combined/consolidated return using this binder. If the state does not allow combined/consolidated filings, the state will not be listed here.

  • Inactive State Activation tab. Use this tab to identify and then activate any particular state in the subsidiary binders for which you have activated in the consolidated binder. For example, if CA is marked to be combined in the consolidated binder, CA must be activated in each member binder as well. Click the 'list' button to list each state for each member binder that needs activation. Click the


activate states button to activate these states in each of the member binders. Use the 'activate A&A' button to activate A&A in each of the member binders.


States to Combine/Consolidate

tab.


Click Mark the state to Combine.

The States to Combine / Consolidate screen is displayed. This is the same screen displayed when you select States | State Combined Returns | Step 1 - What to Consolidate.

Click the check boxes to indicate the states to combine or consolidate in the top consolidation (topcon) company.


 As shown on the screen above, Delaware, Louisiana, New Jersey, North Carolina, and Pennsylvania do not allow a state combined or consolidated filing. However, you may file a combine / consolidate return for North Carolina if it is approved by the state.

 The following states do require a consolidation, but do not allow for state combined returns: Alabama, Arkansas, Georgia, and Kentucky. Mississippi and Virginia can also file as consolidated returns.


STEP 2 - ENTER CONSOLIDATED OVERRIDES

Refer to “Step 2 - Enter Consolidated Overrides” on page 256.

This step is for federal overrides you may wish to make on a top consolidation level. Overrides entered here are used instead of the consolidated amounts from subsidiaries. If you override on the top consolidation, the system creates and adjustment on the white paper schedule with possible footing errors.


STEP 3 - SELECT PRINT AND CALCULATION

Refer to “Step 3 - Select Print and Calculation Options” on page 259.


STEP 4 - REVIEW PRECONSOL CHECKLIST

Refer to “Step 4 - Review Preconsol Checklist” on page 260.

Use this tab to check some preconsolidation items. Select preconsolidation utilities to see the available checklists.


STEP 5 - CONSOLIDATE!

Refer to “Step 5 - Consolidate!” on page 261.

This button starts the Organizer consolidation. It includes an option to consolidate with Cross-Ties. State returns do not use Cross-Ties. Each individual state has a specific whitepaper presentation format based on the state- required information.

A consolidation binder may be consolidated prior to the completion of the member binders, however, it will only consolidate data that has been entered. The binder may be consolidated as many times as needed.

ONESOURCE 2016



STEP 6 - REVIEW CROSS-TIE INFORMATION

If the return was consolidated using cross-ties, use this review screen to identify any TCC inconsistencies. If you use a common chart of TCC's, then the only cause of inconsistent TCCs would be if you entered data manually in Organizer.

When the consolidation is complete, use the review tools in the next section to review the return.


REVIEW AND REVISE‌

Review tools are available in Organizer to alert you to potential errors within the consolidation. The functionality that is available in individual binders are also available in consolidated binders, however, consolidated binders offer additional methods of reviewing the return.

  • Subview

  • Consolidated Review Screens

  • Single Company Recomputation - (State Consolidations only)

  • Combined Reports - (State Consolidations only)

  • Tax Summary (discussed in “Tax Summary” on page 236)

  • Drill-Down Arrows (discussed in “Drill - Down Arrows” on page 236)

  • Hyperlinks (discussed in “Hyperlinks” on page 237)

  • Workpapers (discussed in “Workpapers” on page 237)

  • Diagnostics and Overrides (discussed in “Overrides” on page 238)


    SUBVIEW

    Subview is a special feature that allows you to review the amounts from each subsidiary included in the consolidation. This is especially helpful when processing multi-tiered consolidations. See “Subview” on page 263.


    CONSOLIDATED REVIEW SCREENS

    Tax Forms | 1120-U.S. Corporation Return | Consolidated Review provides review screens for many of the forms in the consolidation. Similar to Subview, these review workpapers display any adjustments. The adjustment column is the difference between what is on the return and what is combined from the member binders. See “Consolidated Review” on page 264.


    SINGLE COMPANY RECOMPUTATION

    Single Company Recomputation is located in the software by navigating to Tax Forms | State | Common State

    | Single Company Recomputation. Use this screen to view the adjustments made to the Federal return to calculate the starting adjustable taxable income for the states. Although the subsidiary is used in a Federal consolidation, it may be recognized as a single entity for state purposes. This workpaper replaces the need for a proform single company return and can be printed and attached to the return.


    COMBINED REPORTS

    Use Combined Reports to view combined forms and workpapers associated with the state. You can find these reports by navigating to Tax Forms | State | Name of State | Combined Reports.

    Printing the State Combined/Consolidated Return

    You can view your state returns using Print Preview or print the entire return.

    1. From the File menu, select Print Entire Return or click the Print button on the toolbar.

    2. Or, from the File menu, select Print Preview.

    Refer to “Using Print” on page 403 for more information.


    CHECKLIST FOR COMBINED OR CONSOLIDATED RETURNS‌‌


    INDIVIDUAL BINDERS INCLUDING PARENT, SUBSIDIARY AND ELIMINATION

  • Are all of the members' binders in balance?

  • Have the Diagnostics and Overrides from the View menu on the individual entities been reviewed?

  • Were all entries to the Organizer made at the same level of detail?

  • Has each entity been recomputed on the current version of the software?

  • Has the state you are combining been activated for each entity within the combined report, including the elimination binder?

  • If using Summary A & A, has the area been activated and the information entered in the Data Entry or Organizer/Overrides folder on each Parent and Sub binder?


    PARENT BINDER

  • Was all general information pertaining to the state entered on the Parent binder?


    ELIMINATION BINDER

  • Does the state law require filing using different entities than the Federal and if so, is there a separate consolidation and elimination binder for the state?


    TOP CONSOLIDATION

  • Have the States to Combine been marked on the consolidation binder?

  • Has the consolidation been performed?

  • Have you reviewed each combined state from the Tax Form Combined Report?

  • Did you check the Diagnostics and Overrides from the Access Menu on the consolidated return?

  • Did you print the state combined/consolidated return?

    TIPS AND TRICKS FOR STATE CONSOLIDATIONS


    TAX ACCOUNTING SYSTEM

  • On the TAS Compute (Domestic Compute tab), check the option to Update with Federal TAS option off. This prevents any changes made to TAS in the Preliminary Balances or Adjustment area from affecting the state or federal return. If TAS is turned on, any overrides or manual entries made to the Organizer for any field coded to a TRC (that is, Balance Sheet and P/L information) are removed and replaced by the TAS information. This information then flows from the federal return down to any active states.

  • Select Apportionment and State Consolidation Options in the Enterprise Control Panel, see “CHAPTER 8: Tools” on page 107 for more detail.


    STATE COMBINED RETURNS

  • The system has Combined Return Processing online Help for all states with combined / consolidated returns. Users can review the detail under the Organizer | States | California (for example) | Combined Help screen to know where to enter information.

  • Many of the State Combined returns have Top Consolidation override fields. These fields allow data entry in the consolidated level and can prevent having to go back to the subsidiaries and parent to make adjusting entries that would require recomputing and reconsolidating.

  • The Common State area of the Organizer is helpful when a company is compliant in multiple states. The organization of the Common State area allows a more efficient method of data entry for multiple items. If the Common State area is utilized for the data entry on a particular entity, then in order to keep the levels of data

    ONESOURCE 2016



    entry consistent, the Common State area should be used for data entry on the parent and subsidiaries in that consolidated group. Estimated payments, credits, tax accruals, general information, and depreciation are all examples of screens that can be completed through the Common State area.

    • If the binder you are working in is the parent for a federal return, but a subsidiary for the California Combined return, the entity type can be changed under the Organizer |Common State | General Information | Filing Status/Entity Type screen.

    • Options for Combined States - On a Top Consolidation binder, go to Organizer | States | Common State | State Combined Returns | Option for Combined States to mark compute options for states involved in a consolidation. Some states require a particular option to be marked on all binders involved in the consolidation. This screen allows you to view and select any options that apply to your consolidation and transfer the selection down to all the binders in the consolidation. Click to select an option and click Transfer Information to apply the option to all members of the consolidation.

  • Combined Information subtopic is available for states that require the filing of a combined return. The Combined Information subtopic is usually listed near the bottom of the topic list in Organizer.

  • New York Elimination - The Combined Information screen is a common screen for all combined questions and calculations for each particular state. Duplicate check boxes or fields can be found throughout other topics of the individual state’s folder.

     Selecting a check box or populating a field in the Combined Information screen automatically affects the duplicate field listed in other subtopics of Organizer.

     Eliminations for the New York combined return are made in the elimination binder but are entered differently from other eliminating entries. Traditionally, eliminating entries are entered as positive or negative amounts, which increase or decrease consolidated totals. For example, an eliminating entry for Intercompany Sales is entered as a negative to reduce consolidated gross income or sales.

     However, eliminations for a New York combined return are entered in a dedicated Elimination Adjustments subtopic of the New York folder.

    Entering New York Eliminations

    1. From within the Organizer of an open Elimination binder, double-click States | New York | Combined Return Information.

    2. Double-click Elimination Adjustments.

    3. Enter amounts in the appropriate fields.


      STATE CHECKLIST‌‌


      TASK LIST


      • All the individual entities are in balance


      • Check Access | Diagnostics and Overrides on the individual entities.


      • All entries to Organizer made at the same level


      • Each entity has been recomputed on the current version of the software.


      • Does the state file use different entities than the Federal?


      • If so, is there a separate consolidation and elimination return for the state?


      • All general information pertaining to the state was entered on the PARENT return.


        

        Has the state you are combining been activated for each entity within the combined report, including the elimination return?


        

        State Combined Processing Instructions have been reviewed from within Help and followed for each state on the return


      • Mark state to combine on the consolidation return.


      • Consolidate TAS with the Organizer - Subsidiary listing box checked.


      • Perform the consolidation in Organizer.


      • Review each combined state from the Tax Form Combined Report


      • Check Access | Diagnostics and Overrides on the consolidated return.


      • Print the state combined return


    ONESOURCE 2016


    CHAPTER 16: PRINTING‌‌


    You can print many types of reports in ONESOURCE Income Tax. You can print administrative reports for workareas, entities, and binders or reports for a specific binder, entity or workarea.

    The Administrative reports contain information such as what charts are being used by an entity or a specific binder. These reports also contain information about each binder, such as the binder name, filing period, binder type, and binder identification number.

    Domestic reports provide complete information about Tax Accounting System details. These reports pertain only to the contents of a single binder, entity, or workarea such as:

  • Tax Basis Balance Sheet Reports

  • Adjustment Reports (Current Period and Comparative)

  • Schedule M-3 Reports.


    GENERATING REPORTS‌‌

    1. On the My Binders screen, select the Report icon on the appropriate binder. The Reports screen has two tabs, Domestic and Administrative. It initially opens on the Domestic Report page and then defaults to the last used page.



    2. Select the report(s) you wish to print.


    3. Select Export to Excel to save the information to a spreadsheet file or Export to PDF to save the information to a PDF file.



    4. Select Open to open the file.

    5. Select Save to keep a copy of the file on your computer.

     Detailed reports display only the accounts with balances. Accounts with zero balances are automatically suppressed.


    PRINT PREVIEW‌‌

    Advantages of the print system include:

  • Preview opens in a new window, allowing continued access to Tax Form pages while Preview is open.

  • Within Preview, attachments open in new windows, allowing side-by-side viewing of forms and attachments.

  • The tree on the left can be expanded and collapsed.

  • Powerful right-click options on the left tree enable intuitive printing of subsets within the document or a "Quick Print" of the viewed page within the collection.

  • From the Print Selection screen, you have enhanced granular choices to choose to generate print for only a subset of the return.

  • When deciding whether to use an existing print file, you can see the date and time when the print file was generated.

  • Menu choices are dynamic in Preview Return.

  • You can "refresh" the print file with updated data while previewing.

  • Tool bar buttons allow quick access to printing options.

  • You can use enhanced K-1 Package Print and Preview abilities.

    ONESOURCE 2016



    USING PRINT‌‌

    To begin the print process, select Print on the Organizer toolbar.




    The Print Selection screen opens a new window. Within this screen you can:

  • Verify the return type to print

  • Select desired copy types

  • Include e-File attachments

  • Select the all returns, or portions of the return to print

  • Enter a file name

  • Create the print file

  • Review previous print history for the return


CREATING A PRINT FILE

  1. Select the return(s) you wish to print.



  2. Enter the File Name.

  3. Click Create.



  4. Clicking Create populates the History, located below the Create button. This History area shows the file name, print status, print selection, start date and time, and end date and time.

  5. Once the print process has completed, you will see three options in the Actions column: Open, Download, and Delete.

    • Click Open to open the print file in PDF format within a separate browser window.

    • Click Download to save the PDF to a desired location.

    • Click Delete to delete the print file.

Note 1: For most of the forms not consolidated, it prints from the return that you enter the information. If you want to print from consolidated return, you need to input information on the

consolidated return.

Note 2: You may select the option to print every company in the consolidated group in the Organizer | Consolidated returns | Step 3 - Prrint and Calculation and Form Print Options

Note 3: If information is entered on the Topcon, it will print with Topcon.

Note 4: Form 1118 can be aggregated only on the Topcon or Single Entity by uploading the XML using Edit | Insert | Efile Attachments - Third Party XML file.
